<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-White     08-23 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-White,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Far East AP Reporter Dead at 81</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jenifer is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENTFIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James D. White, a reporter with The
Associated Press for 36 years and one of the ``China hands'' who
covered the Far East in the 1930s, has died of a heart attack. He
was 81.
   White died Thursday at Kentfield Rehabilitation Hospital in this
city about 10 miles north of San Francisco while being treated for
injuries from a fall. He lived in nearby Mill Valley.
   His last AP assigment before his retirement in 1972 was in the
San Francisco bureau.
   The Appleton, Mo., native graduated from the University of
Missouri School of Journalism, and went to work for the AP in what
was then called Peiping.
   White, who met and married his wife Jenifer in Peiping, covered
Inner Mongolia and other parts of the East until 1941, when World
War II broke out.
   The Whites, who were in Shanghai, were unable to leave for some
months. They finally left aboard a Swedish liner.
   On his repatriation to the United States, White was assigned to
the State and War departments in Washington. In 1945, he joined the
AP's San Francisco bureau. He wrote an interpretive column on world
events for five years, and edited news going to Far Eastern
newspapers.
   White is survived by a sister, Lucille Alexander, of Napa.
   A memorial service was scheduled for Aug. 31 in Corte Madera.
</TEXT>
