<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-23 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Gov. John R. McKernan's mother walked
into a popular capital deli and insisted a sandwich be named after
her son, the owner obliged.
   But sandwich man Michael Burns first made sure the menu entry _ a
turkey sandwich _ didn't offend the chief executive.
   ``We've got other turkeys. We've got a turkey named after veteran
legislator Dan Hickey, a good legislator. But I sent a messenger
over to the governor's office to ask. He thought it was fine,'' said
Burns from behind the orange counter at Burnsie's Lunch.
   His spokesman, Willis Lyford, said McKernan was delighted with
the honor.
   ``As long as it's not baloney,'' Lyford added.
   About a block from the Statehouse complex and gubernatorial
mansion, the lunch shop has a back wall covered with comic
illustrations of the many choices. Customers need only point, Burns
said. Some are named after past and present politicians who are
caricatured by Walter Winchester of Augusta.
   ``Joe Brennan was governor when I came here, of course we became
friendly,'' said Burns, recalling a visit by the two-term governor.
``We talked for a while, then I said, `We've got to have a sandwich
named after you.'''
   The ``Big Governor Joe,'' a popular item at Burnsies, is
prominently advertised.
   ``Well, Mrs. McKernan came in one day and saw that and said,
`Where's my son's sandwich?'
   ``I told her next time she came in, she'd see the sign right up
there,'' said Burns.
   The Duke's Special, named after a capital barber famous for his
informal _ but usually accurate _ political polls, led to a
situation that Burns characterized as ``really quite comical.''
   ``This lady came in, she had all these Dukakis buttons on her.
She jumped up and down at that sandwich, she said she wanted to kiss
me,'' he said. ``I didn't tell her it was for a hard-working local
guy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers, professors and a Fortune
500 company have been assembled to flush out malfunctioning toilets
in south Florida.
   The problem, in part, is an 80-cent rubber seal that
deteriorates, causing toilets to run or stop flushing. A leading
manufacturer of the seal, hoping to solve the mystery, has given a
$4,000 grant to a water-quality researcher at Florida International
University.
   ``The university is as puzzled as we are on the exact problem,''
said Mitchell Kleppe, Florida representative for Fluidmaster Co. of
Anaheim, Calif. ``It has not been able to pin anything down on the
exact cause.''
   For three years, the leaky and malfunctioning toilets have
affected nearly 95 percent of the homes in Palm Beach, Broward and
Dade counties, said Kleppe.
   He said the company is the world's largest manufacturer of the
seal.
   The quarter-size seals fail about every six months in south
Florida, but in most parts of the country they last up to five
years, he said.
   The seal is part of a valve that triggers the toilet to fill or
empty the tank. When the seal malfunctions, it swells and prevents
the valve from working, often leaving the noise of water running in
the tank.
   Besides the university study, the manufacturer is conducting
tests at Fort Lauderdale's water plants and is teaming up with
California engineers and makers of rubber products, such as the
Fortune 500's Du Pont, he said.
</TEXT>
