<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Resort     08-23 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Resort,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Popular Resort Tries to Salvage Tourist Season</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIDAIHE, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tourism industry at this seaside
resort, the summer playground of China's leaders, is struggling to
recover from the spring military crackdown on students.
   The violent June 3-4 suppression of students protesting for
democratic reform in Beijing not only scared away foreign tourists
but has kept many Chinese from traveling.
   In addition, an economic austerity program that began last fall
has meant Chinese have less money for vacations. Many government
employees have canceled their vacations this year.
   The tourists who came to frolic on the beaches of the Bohai Sea
about 180 miles northeast of Beijing have had plenty of room this
summer.
   Even China's top leaders, who usually spend all of August here,
have made only brief visits. Senior leader Deng Xiaoping reportedly
is the only one who has stayed on.
   Party chief Jiang Zemin, who normally would be here with
government leaders plotting the nation's course, is campaigning to
boost the party's image, traveling to the provinces, visiting
factories and eating in workers' cafeterias.
   ``Usually, these places are filled,'' said a taxi driver
gesturing to private guesthouses in a deserted area of town several
miles from the center.
   In past years, the clear water and fresh seabreezes of Beidaihe
drew visitors from all over the country.
   Work units from northeastern China have hostels in Beidaihe for
selected employees to relax for a week or more.
   ``Usually, it's a sea of people,'' said a tanned junior high
school student.
   A few spots along Beidaihe's 3.7-mile-long beachfront were
crowded, especially the public beach near downtown.
   But even in the crowded areas, stacks of unrented red and blue
air mattresses indicated there were fewer people than normal.
   Along the Beidaihe coastline, sunbathers dotted the beach, the
men in surprisingly skimpy briefs and women in modest one-piece
suits.
   Older beachgoers crouched under umbrellas, hiding from the sun,
but the younger ones played in the sand and water.
   Perceptions of how bad the situation is vary.
   The taxi driver said on condition of anonymity that tourism this
summer was down by two-thirds.
   Sun Dali, an employee at the Jinshan Hotel, Beidaihe's fanciest,
said there were so few guests in June that some temporary hotel
employees were let go, but occupancy in August has been 100 percent.
   Beidaihe's tourism office said it didn't have statistics on the
number of visitors this year, but official reports in mid-July said
there were 1 million fewer tourists than last year, when 5 million
people visited.
   The loss is felt by both the government and the small-time
private entrepreneurs who run guest houses that charge $1.35 a night
for a bed or sell ice cream bars for a few cents on the roadside.
   Last year, 60 percent of the area's tax revenues came from
tourism. And the income of many town residents comes from the summer
tourism trade.
   An elderly man renting air mattresses, inner tubes and a rubber
raft on the beach said he made less than $100 in June, compared to
thousands in past Junes.
   At the Come-In Restaurant, a man serving at the counter said
there will be only about 20 days of good business in August before
cooler temperatures and the start of the school year sends the
tourists home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
