<FIRST>u p AM-SCarolina-Abortion 3rdLd-Writethru a0743 08-23 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SCarolina-Abortion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0743,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Candidates Outdistance Abortion Foe in S.C. Legislative
Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf, `Miss Cork ...,' to UPDATE with
comment from candidates; picks up 6th graf, `The issue ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pro-choice candidates
outdistanced an anti-abortion candidate in a Republican primary
Tuesday to fill a vacant state Assembly seat, putting them in a
runoff next month.
   The primary was South Carolina's first election since the U.S.
Supreme Court last month gave states more latitude to restrict
abortion.
   According to unofficial results, former legislative aide Holly
Cork led with 2,654 votes to 2,226 for developer David Ames and
1,805 for Robert Graves, a businessman who opposes abortion, said
Beaufort County Republican Party Chairman Frank Gibson.
   The result was expected to be finalized Thursday, when any
questionable votes could be challenged. If the vote stands as
expected, a runoff will be held Sept. 5 between Miss Cork and Ames,
Gibson said.
   Miss Cork, who was bidding to succeed her father, the late Rep.
William N. Cork, favors a woman's right to abortion, as does Ames.
Graves opposes abortion.
   Miss Cork said after the election that the national attention
focused on abortion, ``made the voters here think about it more,''
but said she wasn't sure if it played a role in the primary.
   Ames said the issue was important, but said it would probably be
less of a factor in the runoff because both he and Miss Cork are
pro-choice. He said such issues as real-estate taxes, uncontrolled
growth and traffic, and drugs would become more important.
   Graves said his stand on abortion may have cost him votes.
   The issue had dominated the campaign, transcending the
environment, education, taxes and crime. The General Assembly is
expected to decide whether it will place more restrictions on
abortions when it reconvenes in January.
   About 30 percent of voters turned out, Gibson said, compared to
50 percent to 65 percent in previous primaries. He said it was
``really hard to tell'' whether the abortion issue was the deciding
factor in the race.
   Miss Cork, 23, a former legislative aide to U.S. Rep. Arthur
Ravenel, R-S.C., said voters overwhelmingly favor abortion rights.
She said her position was based on ``personal beliefs'' not
``political expediency.''
   Ames, 45, said he favors legalized abortion and would not support
legislation to restrict a woman's right to abortion. ``But I feel
that through education we have to reduce the need for abortions,''
he said.
   Graves, 51, opposes abortion but favors exceptions for rape,
incest and to save the life of a mother.
   Cork, who was elected to the House of Representatives in 1982,
died in June of a heart attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
