<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     08-23 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeachment Witness Balks at Senate Questions, Judge Orders Him Jailed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disbarred lawyer William Borders will go to
jail Friday unless he answers questions from senators gathering
evidence in the Alcee Hastings impeachment case, a federal judge
says.
   ``This court ... confines him to the custody of the U.S. marshal
until he purges himself,'' District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
said Tuesday after holding Borders in civil contempt of court at the
request of the Senate.
   The order came hours after Borders refused to answer 10 questions
from Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., about impeachment charges against
Hastings, a 52-year-old U.S. District judge from Florida.
   ``We do not have any interest in putting you in jail,'' Specter
told Borders, ``but that is the established procedure.''
   Borders has been granted immunity from prosecution for what he
might tell the committee and ordered by a federal court to testify.
But he still balked, saying the questions violated his
constitutional rights, including the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination.
   The husky, gray-bearded Borders, a Washington power broker in the
1970s, arrived in court with two hefty paperback books, apparently
bought over the lunch hour. Jackson, however, gave him until 10 a.m.
Friday to put his affairs in order before surrendering to U.S.
marshals.
   Specter posed his questions to Borders at a session of the Senate
committee gathering evidence in the Hastings case.
   Hastings is accused of plotting with Borders in 1981 to obtain a
$150,000 payoff and lying about it to a jury that acquitted him in
1981. Borders was convicted in a separate trial, disbarred and
served 33 months in prison.
   Despite the jury acquittal, the House in August 1988 approved 17
articles of impeachment against Hastings, charging him with the
payoff conspiracy, perjury and improper disclosure of information
obtained from a court-approved wiretap.
   The committee will produce a report on the evidence against
Hastings, and the Senate then will vote on whether to remove him
from the bench.
   Under Jackson's order, Borders could purge himself of contempt
and get out of jail by answering the committee's questions.
Otherwise, he most likely would remain behind bars until the Senate
votes on impeaching Hastings. That vote is expected before
mid-October.
   The questions posed by Specter on Tuesday ranged from whether
Hastings received any payoff money to the alleged relationship
between Borders and the late Florida Mafia boss Santo Trafficante.
   Borders replied to each question by citing a statement he made
July 27 when he also refused to testify before the committee. The
statement said the questions violated his rights.
   Borders also objected on the grounds that with Specter the only
senator on hand for the session a quorum of the committee was not
present.
   Specter, however, reminded him of a resolution providing that one
senator constitutes a quorum for purposes of hearing testimony from
Borders. The measure was approved before lawmakers left for their
August recess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890823-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CocaineCanine     08-23 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Cocaine Canine,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>This Was Not Your Usual Doggie Bag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INSTITUTE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The neighborhood stray dragged a shopping
bag containing $25,000 worth of crack into a woman's driveway,
prompting State Police Sgt. Don Cook to say:
   ``You've heard of drug pushers. This was a drug puller.''
   The dog, which roams around the neighborhood in which the woman
lives, left the bag in her driveway Monday night. Cook on Tuesday
said she was going to throw it out with the trash Tuesday, but
looked in the bag before tossing it out.
   ``It had these strange vials that she couldn't identify. She
thought they might be drugs, so she called us,'' Cook said.
   Some 160 vials containing the highly potent, smokeable form of
cocaine were in two plastic bags inside the shopping bag.
   ``And no telling how many vials the dog might have lost while it
was dragging it,'' Cook said. ``It may have fallen from a car, it
may have been stashed under a house, whatever.
   ``I'd say some individual is very unhappy at the moment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
