<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief 550   08-23 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservationists Going to U.S. Appeals Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservationists who fear thousands of
endangered sea turtles will drown in nets unless Gulf Coast
shrimpers are required to use turtle excluder devices are taking
their case to a federal appeals court.
   A U.S. District Court judge Tuesday denied the National Wildlife
Federation's request that shrimpers be required to use the devices,
known as TEDs.
   Wildlife Federation lawyer Robert Irvin said he would appeal the
decision by U.S. District Court Judge Stanley Harris to the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
   On Monday, five conservation groups filed suit against Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher, alleging his actions on behalf of
shrimpers have virtually assured the drowning of thousands of
endangered sea turtles.
   The lawsuit alleges Mosbacher acted unlawfully when he suspended
regulations requiring shrimpers to use TEDs, which prevent sea
turtles from becoming ensnarled in the nets and drowning.
   Mosbacher suspended the regulations after shrimpers, angry about
having to use devices they say reduce their catch by as much as
one-third, blocked shipping channels along the Texas Gulf Coast.
   Under a court order to protect endangered sea turtles in a
separate lawsuit by the Wildlife Federation, Mosbacher then ordered
shrimpers who don't use TEDs to limit their trawling times to 105
minutes at prescribed intervals.
   Michael J. Bean, a lawyer for the Environmental Defense Fund,
said there has been no sign that shrimpers are complying with the
limited trawl times.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Board Recommends Against Early Parole</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A board of examiners of the U.S. Parole
Commission is recommending that early parole be denied for Anne
Henderson-Pollard, convicted in the espionage case against her
husband, Jonathan Pollard, her lawyer says.
   The panel heard the case at the Danbury, Conn., federal
penitentiary where she's serving a five-year sentence as an
accessory after the fact, said lawyer Hamilton P. Fox.
   The panel's recommendations goes to a regional parole
commissioner for a ruling, Fox said.
   ``This is a cruel blow,'' said Morris Pollard, her father-in-law.
He said Mrs. Pollard had lost about 70 pounds during her
incarceration because of a digestive tract ailment, and weighs 86
pounds.
   Her first appeal for parole was denied last year.
   Mrs. Pollard was sentenced March 4, 1987, and is almost certain
to be granted mandatory parole under prison guidelines at the end of
March, once she has served two-thirds of her sentence.
   Her husband is serving a life sentence at the federal prison in
Marion, Ill., for selling secrets to Israel while an intelligence
analyst with the U.S. Navy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Remains of Virginian, Georgian, Pennsylvanian Coming Home</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of three U.S. Army servicemen who
died in South Vietnam are being returned to the United States today,
the Pentagon says.
   They were identified as Capt. Henry M. Spengler III, of
Alexandria, Va., Chief Warrant Officer Charles C. Windeler Jr., of
Savannah, Ga., and Spec. 1st Class Edward D. Reilly Jr., of
Philadelphia.
   The remains were to arrive today at Travis Air Force Base, Calif.
   A statement issued by the Pentagon said the remains were among 21
repatriated by Vietnam on April 29, five of which have been
identified. The others are undergoing analysis to determine
identification.
