<FIRST>r w PM-PostalCuts 1stld-writethru a0421 08-23 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postal Cuts, 1st ld-writethru, a0421,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Cutbacks in Postal Facilities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTs ``effect'' to ``affect''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service is trimming its managerial
and administrative work force by 1,000 people in a consolidation
move the agency says won't affect mail service.
   The merger of 37 management sectional centers and two field
divisions into other operations takes effect Sept. 23 and is
expected to save $30 million to $35 million a year, the service said
Tuesday.
   There will be no layoffs. Jobs will be eliminated through early
retirements and other forms of attrition, postal officials said.
Facilities that house the management centers and field divisions
will continue their mail-handling operations.
   Employees affected by the mergers will be reassigned within
commuting distance of their present jobs when possible, or they will
be relocated, the service said.
   The moves continue a reorganization that began in March 1986.
Since then, the Postal Service has established 75 field divisions,
eliminated 42 district offices and cut the number of management
sectional centers from 212 to 131. After the latest round of
consolidations, there will be 73 field divisions and 94 sectional
centers.
   Under the consolidation, the Brooklyn field division in New York
will become part of the Queens division, and the St. Paul division
will become part of the Minneapolis division.
   The management sectional centers to be eliminated are:
   Northeast Region: Binghamton and Utica, N.Y.; Red Bank and
Summit, N.J.; Portsmouth, N.H.; Burlington, Vt.; and Bangor, Maine.
   Eastern Region: Ashland, Corbin and Bowling Green, Ky.;
Charlottesville, Va.; Bluefield, W.Va.; and Zanesville, Ohio.
   Southern Region: Alexandria, La.; Huntsville, Ala., Jonesboro,
Ark.; Tupelo, Miss.; Waco, Texas; and Chattanooga, Tenn.
   Central Region: Carbondale and Champaign, Ill.; Sioux City, Iowa;
Lafayette and South Bend, Ind.; Eau Claire and Oshkosh, Wis.;
Lincoln, Neb.; Saginaw, Flint and Kalamazoo, Mich.
   Western Region: Pasadena, Redding and Marysville, Calif.;
Pocatello, Idaho; Salem, Ore.; Fairbanks, Alaska; and Flagstaff,
Ariz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
