<FIRST>r a PM-GreenRiver     08-23 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Vacation Photos Don't Necessarily Clear `Suspect'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographs of a family vacation don't necessarily
prove a suspect in the Green River slayings was on the East Coast
when the serial killings began, the case's chief investigator says.
   ``The proof that they say is conclusive and the proof police
investigators need involve two different standards,'' King County
Police Capt. Robert Evans said.
   The family of William Jay Stevens II produced photographs and
credit card receipts last week in an effort to prove Stevens was not
in Seattle when the first four victims were killed.
   The Green River killings involve the deaths of at least 40 young
women who disappeared from the Seattle and Portland, Ore., areas
from 1982 to 1984.
   Another eight missing women are believed to be victims in the
case, which takes its name from the river where the first victims
were found.
   Stevens, 38, has not been arrested or charged.
   On Tuesday, The Associated Press quoted Evans as saying the
family's records appeared to clear Stevens of suspicion in the first
four killings.
   But later, Evans said the records have neither cleared nor
intensified police interest in Stevens.
   ``For example, one photo shows this guy with his mother in front
of a building. That's all it is,'' he said.
   Evans said he had a ``personal hangup'' with the family's
description of the trip as a ``family vacation.''
   ``He was a fugitive from justice at the time. How can that be
called a vacation?'' he asked.
   Stevens, a former Gonzaga Law School student, is serving time in
the King County Jail in Seattle for a 1981 escape from a work
release program after a conviction for possessing stolen property.
   He was arrested in January in Spokane, and is scheduled for
release Sept. 25.
   Stevens was identified as a ``viable suspect'' in the affidavit
used last month to obtain a search warrant of two Spokane residences
where he lived. That search yielded 1,800 videotapes, police
uniforms and extensive credit card records.
   Among other theories, investigators have speculated that someone
posing as a police officer was responsible for the killings.
</TEXT>
