<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0312EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abe'sArtifacts     08-23 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abe's Artifacts,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Faults State's Handling of Lincoln Papers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The curator of Illinois' Abraham Lincoln
collection rejected criticism that the documents aren't being cared
for properly, saying there's nothing amiss that a little money
wouldn't fix.
   ``If someone wants to imply that they're in danger of being
stolen, that's clearly wrong, or that ... these materials are
threatened in any way, that's also wrong,'' curator Thomas Schwartz
said Tuesday.
   The report, released Monday, said the state Historical Library
``had not properly tagged, cataloged and periodically inventoried''
significant parts of its Lincoln collection, which experts say is
second only to that of the Library of Congress.
   At issue are about 800 portraits, cartoons and prints of Lincoln,
and a 46-volume collection of the papers of Robert Todd Lincoln, the
16th president's eldest son, who served as secretary of war and
ambassador to Great Britain.
   Schwartz blamed a shortage of funds for the library's failure to
complete the project, expected to cost less than $20,000.
   Though the state frequently trumpets Lincoln's ties to Illinois
in tourism promotions, some Lincoln buffs say the state has
shortchanged efforts to preserve that heritage.
   ``There have been times at auction where I would buy Lincoln
things and hold them until the state could afford to buy them,''
said Ralph G. Newman, a Chicago manuscript dealer and Lincoln
expert. ``I didn't want to see them get away.''
   The auditor general issued a similar report in 1986 citing more
widespread neglect of Lincoln documents and artifacts, including the
gown Mary Todd Lincoln wore to her husband's second inauguration and
a silk tablecloth used on their wedding day.
   Schwartz said an inventory of the Lincolns' manuscript letters
has been completed, and that most of the other shortcomings cited in
the 1986 report have since been corrected.
   ``We've made a conscious effort to identify the most valuable
items and deal with those first,'' Schwartz said. ``We have been
making progress, but the auditor general won't remove the finding
until we have completed the entire process.''
   The inventory of the estimated 22,000 Robert Lincoln items has
proceeded slowly, in part because Schwartz is the only full-time
employee assigned to the Lincoln collection, and his work is
interrupted by research demands.
   ``If all I did was to catalog that collection without
interruption, it would probably take me a year, a year and a half,''
Schwartz said. ``But life's not that simple.''
   He acknowledged that the lack of a complete inventory means
library officials wouldn't know if items were stolen or misplaced.
For that reason, the papers are locked in a vault, and access is
strictly limited, he said.
   Only two scholars have been allowed to use the Robert Lincoln
papers, and their work was carefully supervised, he said. Similar
precautions will remain in place until the long task of cataloging
the collection is completed.
   ``When you go at it one item, one card at a time, it just takes a
long time to do it,'' Schwartz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
