<FIRST>r a PM-RussianWaterBeds     08-23 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Russian Water Beds,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Thank U.S. Water Bed Donors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By URSULA THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official visited a water bed
trade show to thank the U.S. water bed industry for supplying beds
to the victims of a June railroad disaster.
   ``We have an expression: `You can recognize your friends in
hardships,''' Yuriy Menshikov, a Soviet embassy attache stationed in
Washington, said Tuesday. ``We were deeply touched _ and not only
those injured. (It shows) mankind's compassion.''
   Menshikov presented industry representatives meeting in Nashville
with a Russian antique-style jewel box containing a scroll
commemorating the donation.
   Two industry groups donated the 50 beds, and they were flown to
Moscow's Vishnevsky Surgical Center two weeks after the June 4
accident.
   Soviet reports say 645 people died when a leaking gas pipeline
exploded and engulfed two passing trains in the Ural Mountains along
the Trans-Siberian Railroad. Many of the victims included children
bound for summer camp.
   Joe Nathanson, an industry spokesman who helped organize the
``Flight of Waterbeds,'' said manufacturers and dealers decided to
donate $25,000 worth of beds after reading a newspaper account of
the disaster.
   ``This story identified a real need at the burn center,'' he
said. ``The story just describes such agony. We know that water beds
are helpful to burn victims. The bed gives even support, so it's
more comfortable and there are no pressure points.''
   The beds, including heaters, frames and liners, were flown from
New York to Los Angeles by Pan American World Airways and picked up
by the Soviet airline Aeroflot for the trip to Moscow.
</TEXT>
