<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceShootings     08-23 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Shootings,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Officers Killed, One Critically Wounded in Shootings in Three
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly drifter walked into police headquarters in Florence,
S.C., and shot an officer to death, then turned the gun on himself.
   In Florida, a Palm Beach County sheriff's deputy was shot to
death by a man armed with a high-powered hunting rifle after
deputies went to the man's house to commit him to an
alcohol-treatment center.
   Meanwhile in southern New Jersey, a state trooper was critically
wounded in a shooting after pulling over a car for a motor vehicle
violation on the New Jersey Turnpike.
   Florence authorities say they didn't know of any motive for
Tuesday's attack by Angelo Nicosia, a resident of Johnson City,
N.Y., who drifted in and out of town and knew many city police
officers. Florence County Sheriff William C. Barnes said Nicosia was
``about 85.''
   Nicosia walked into the police department at the City-County
Complex and asked to speak to Lt. Rick Gould, said Hugh Munn,
spokesman for the State Law Enforcement Division.
   Nicosia entered Gould's office and talked to him for about five
minutes before pulling out a handgun and shooting the officer once
in the head, Munn said. He then ran outside the station and shot
himself in the head, Munn said.
   Nicosia and Gould, an 11{-year veteran, were pronounced dead at
McLeod Regional Medical Center, hospital spokeswoman Celia Whitten
said.
   Gould, 35, and other officers apparently knew Nicosia, but not in
connection with any crime, Munn said.
   Barnes said the gun used by Nicosia was purchased Tuesday morning
in Florence, a city of 32,000 about 80 miles east of Columbia. South
Carolina does not require a waiting period to purchase a weapon,
Munn said.
   In Florida, Deputy James Dickinson, 29, was killed Tuesday
evening at a home near Royal Palm Beach, about 10 miles west of West
Palm Beach.
   As Dickinson approached the house, David Boswell, 42, popped out
from behind the front door and shot the deputy once in the head,
Palm Beach County Sheriff Richard Wille said.
   Boswell, a land surveyor, was charged with first-degree murder
and held overnight in the county jail pending a court hearing this
afternoon in West Palm Beach.
   His estranged wife, Beverly Boswell, had asked for an emergency
court order earlier Tuesday to commit him to an alcohol abuse
clinic. The two had been arguing at the house and Boswell had
pointed a gun at his wife, sheriff's spokesman Bob Ferrell said.
   In New Jersey, Anthony V. DiSalvatore was in critical but stable
condition early today after surgery at the Cooper Medical Center in
Camden, a hospital operator said. Authorities said he was shot in
the abdomen and the chest.
   Three Maryland men suspected of heading a cocaine ring were
arrested in connection with the shooting and were to be arraigned
today in Superior Court in Gloucester County. One man had fled the
scene on foot and the others were arrested after fleeing in the
trooper's cruiser and later commandeering a pickup truck.
</TEXT>
