<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BlindJustice     08-23 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blind Justice,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sight Reading Requirement Discriminated, U.S. Education Department
Ruled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A music school's requirement that graduates
sight-read music discriminated against the blind, the U.S.
Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights ruled.
   The Berklee College of Music, one of the largest independent
music schools in the nation, has for years required its students to
show they can sight-read sheet music as part of the core curriculum.
   The school warned blind applicants that they could never fulfill
core requirements and therefore would not graduate. Most were
discouraged and did not apply, The Boston Globe reported today.
   Thomas J. Burns, regional director of the New England division of
the Office of Civil Rights, said qualified blind students should not
be held back based on their inability to perform a single test.
   ``I think it's a very important right that's been clarified,'' he
said. ``The case was unique and certainly the first we've come
across.''
   Berklee changed its curriculum and graduation requirements before
the ruling to ``de-emphasize sight reading,'' said Lawrence Bethune,
dean of the 2,900 students at the school.
   ``This is certainly noteworthy,'' said Kenneth Jernigan,
executive director of the National Federation of the Blind. ``This
case recognizes that we are really dealing with a civil rights
matter, and that's a refreshing change.''
   The case began two years ago when a visually impaired woman
decided to apply to Berklee and was told she would not graduate. Her
mother filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. The office
ruled against the school last month.
   A curriculum committee at Berklee had been looking at the core
requirements and decided to change the sight reading requirement
irrespective of the discrimination case, Bethune said.
   ``The problem we had was that at the time, we felt the standard
could not be modified,'' he said. ``But we have no bone to pick with
blind students. We accept them, and we're happy to have them.''
</TEXT>
