<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-1939Pact     08-23 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-1939 Pact,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Party Condemns Secret 1939 Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baltics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party strongly condemned a
secret Soviet-German agreement that divided Poland at the start of
World War II.
   In a statement released Tuesday, the eve of the 50th anniversary
of the agreement, the party's Politburo said the pact ``flagrantly
violated'' international law.
   The secret protocol to the pact defined spheres of influence and
allowed for the occupation of eastern Poland by the Soviet Union and
western Poland by Nazi German troops.
   Party spokesman Jan Bisztyga, responding to questions at a news
conference, said the statement did not mean that Poland would seek
to regain territory in present day Byelorussia, Lithuania and the
Ukraine that remained in Soviet hands after World War II.
   He also said there were no plans to seek any war damages from the
Soviets.
   The Soviet Union had long denied the existence of the secret
protocol, agreed to on Aug. 23, 1939, by Soviet Foreign Minister
Vyacheslav Molotov and German Foreign Minister Joachim von
Ribbentrop.
   The agreement also led to the Soviet annexation of Lithuania and
the Baltic states of Latvia and Estonia.
   Eight days after the pact was signed, Germany declared war on
Poland to start World War II. On Sept. 17, 1939, Soviet troops
occupied Poland from the East, claiming that the Polish government
had collapsed and that they were coming to protect Byelorussian and
Ukrainian nationalities in Poland.
   The Politburo branded the secret protocol and a subsequent Sept.
28, 1939, German-Soviet agreement that adjusted their border through
occupied Poland as ``non-existent and invalid'' from the very
beginning.
   ``This leaves no doubt about the political, legal and moral
assessment of those treaties,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Wladyslaw
Klaczynski later told the state PAP news agency.
   However, the Politburo said its statement was intended to have no
bearing on ``the borders decided (after the war) and existing in
Europe.''
   After the war, Poland lost about 71,300 square miles of its
pre-war eastern territories to the Soviet Union. It was compensated
with a smaller amount of German territory in the west.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
