<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     08-23 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Swimmer Asks for Political Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Chinese swimmer announced today he is
seeking political asylum in this British colony because of his
activity in support of the crushed pro-democracy movement in China.
   Yang Yang, 20, said he feared he would be arrested if he returned
home.
   Yang told reporters that after arriving in Hong Kong on a tourist
visa in March he participated in local marches supporting Beijing
students demonstrating for more freedom.
   He also said he helped pro-democracy activists and claimed to be
a member of the New York-based Chinese Alliance for Democracy, which
has been sharply criticized by Beijing authorities.
   The Communist Chinese government crushed the movement for
democracy in June and subsequently arrested thousands of people in a
crackdown on dissent.
   The swimmer said he asked the Hong Kong Immigration Department
earlier this month for asylum but had not received a response. He
said his tourist visa has expired.
   An Immigration Department spokesman refused comment on Yang.
   Yang, a Beijing native, was the second best male swimmer in China
last year and has represented his country at competitions in Hong
Kong and Yugoslavia, according to biographical information provided
at his news conference.
