<DOCNO> AP890823-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-AmericanUniversity     08-23 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American University,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>American University to Stay in Beirut Despite the Situation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American University of Beirut will never
leave the Lebanese capital despite fighting that has closed it for
more than five months, the school's chief administrator said.
   ``It will not exist anywhere else,'' Dr. Ibrahim Salti said
Tuesday.
   The school's president, Frederick P. Herter, is based in New York
because Lebanon remains off limits to Americans, and Salti now
handles administration in Beirut.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, the Jordanian
physician said ``it would take decades'' to reproduce the programs
AUB offers on its 73-acre seaside campus.
   He said that in the 123 years since it was founded by
Presbyterian missionaries, American University has developed a
``close symbiotic relationship'' with Beirut that makes the city and
campus inseparable.
   The school, which has educated many of the Arab world's most
prominent figures, was forced to suspend classes in March when heavy
shelling erupted between Syrians in west Beirut and the largely
Christian army of Gen. Michel Aoun in east Beirut.
   Since then, 70 shells have hit the campus, located in west
Beirut, Salti said.
   He said most of the damage was ``superficial,'' however, and that
none of the staff or 5,300 students had been killed, largely because
classes had been suspended.
   He said the university's 421-bed hospital and medical school have
continued to operate, although a shortage of nurses has cut
operations by a third. The American University Hospital is by far
Lebanon's largest and most sophisticated medical center.
   Before the nation's civil war began in 1975, the hospital was the
most popular in the Middle East, with people arriving from all over
the region for treatment.
   Salti said the school had become used to battles and cease-fires
during the past 14 years but that the current round of fighting _
which began in March _ was ``probably the most cruel, the most
protracted'' of the war.
   Scores of Westerners have been kidnapped or assassinated in
Beirut in recent years.
   There currently are 16 Westerners held hostage in Lebanon; eight
are Americans.
   Three of the hostages were employed by American University:
Thomas Sutherland, 58, Scottish-born acting dean of agriculture, was
kidnapped June 9, 1985. American Joseph Cicippio, 58, acting
comptroller has been held since Sept. 12, 1986; Brian Keenan, 32, of
British-ruled Northern Ireland, an English language teacher, has
been held since April 11, 1986.
   Longest held is Terry Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Salti said if the university can meet its Sept. 11 target date
for reopening classes, or even one in October, it should be able to
make up for the lost time by holding classes through scheduled
vacation breaks.
   ``If a cease-fire is declared tommorrow, in a few days the campus
will be a beehive of activity again,'' he said.
   Salti said the war has driven away nearly all of the foreign
staff, who once made up 30 percent of the faculty, and has reduced
non-Lebanese students to about 10 percent of enrollment.
   But he said interest from non-Lebanese students remains strong,
partly because of the school's standards, location and low cost.
   And despite, all the problems facing American University, its
pre-med students recently scored above the U.S. average on the
standard American test used to rate qualifications for medical
school, Salti said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
