<FIRST>r a PM-SixFlagsDeath     08-23 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Six Flags Death,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Examiner Says Boy Died of Seizurelike Episode at Theme Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy who collapsed last month during
a roller-coaster ride at Six Flags Over Georgia died from a
``seizurelike disorder,'' a medical examiner concluded.
   After a month-long investigation, Cobb County Associate Medical
Examiner Wayne Ross said Tuesday that the two-minute ride apparently
aggravated a previously undiagnosed condition in William ``Brett''
Pope, of Talladega, Ala.
   ``Somehow, I feel that the ride, through the acceleration or the
G-forces, lowered his seizure threshold,'' Ross said.
   He said the results do not mean the ride is dangerous for people
in good health.
   Ross said his office learned about two incidents involving Brett
that might constitute a pattern of similar episodes. One was a
near-drowning last year.
   Ronald Pope, Brett's father, on Tuesday said he accepted the
medical examiner's conclusions but rejected assertions that the past
incidents are connected to his son's death.
   ``When he got on that ride, he was a healthy boy,'' Pope said.
</TEXT>
