<HEAD>Showers in Lower Missouri Valley; Winds Hit Several Areas of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were moving eastward across the lower
Missouri Valley early today, and strong winds from thunderstorms
blew through several areas of the nation.
   Thunderstorms moving through south-central Kansas produced wind
gusts to 50 mph at Winfield, and gusts to 60 mph at Marion.
Wellington was drenched with 2 inches of rain in two hours.
   A flash flood watch was in effect for northeastern Kansas Tuesday
night, when thunderstorms produced up to 2 inches of rain south of
Salina and southeast of Topeka.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in northern and eastern Iowa
early this morning.
   Thunderstorms produced high winds in northeastern Iowa and
southwestern Wisconsin early Tuesday evening. Strong thunderstorm
winds downed trees north of Dubuque in Iowa, and gusted to 65 mph at
Balltown, Iowa. Thunderstorm winds also downed large tree limbs in
Grant County, Wisc.
   A flow of cool air was bringing showers and thunderstorms to the
Pacific Northwest, while similar conditions developing along the
cold front were scattered from the northern Rockies to northern
California. Thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph at Havre, Mont.,
Tuesday evening, and 46 mph at Elko, Nev.
   Strong southwest winds continued in western Nevada ahead of the
cold front. A wind gust to 45 mph was reported at Lovelock, Nev.,
Tuesday evening.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms fell in the Florida
peninsula and the Northeast this morning.
   The high Tuesday was 106 degrees at Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from parts of the southern Plains across the middle Mississippi and
Ohio valleys, and the central Appalachians to the northern Atlantic
Coast states; showers and thunderstorms widely scattered from the
lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to Florida; a few
thunderstorms from the Pacific Northwest across the northern and
central Plateau to the northern Rockies; gusty winds in Utah and
Nevada.
   Predicted highs: 80s and 90s across most of the nation; 70s from
northern New England to much of the Great Lakes region, with 60s
near the shores of Lakes Michigan and Superior; 60s and 70s from
western Montana across the northern and central Plateau to the
Pacific Northwest, and along the California coast; and about 100
degrees in the desert Southwest, along the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas and the central parts of South Carolina.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 45 degrees at
Sexton Summit, Ore., to 88 at Phoenix.
