<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0644EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Earthquakes     08-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Earthquakes,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Kill Two in Ethiopia, Injure Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earthquakes this week spawned
landslides that killed two people and hundreds of livestock,
destroyed a half-dozen bridges and left a major highway impassable,
the Ethiopian News Agency reported.
   Eight people also were injured in the four temblors that hit
northeastern Ethiopia Sunday through Tuesday. The quakes registered
as high as 6.5 on the Richter scale, the agency reported Tuesday.
   The fatalities occurred when landslides overturned four trucks
and badly damaged a 19-mile stretch of highway leading to the Red
Sea port of Assab, the agency said.
   The port handles 70 percent of Ethiopia's trade as well as much
of the relief food needed by refugees and drought victims in this
impoverished East African nation. Ethiopia's only oil refinery also
is at the port.
   The agency said six bridges also were destroyed in the earthquake.
   Assab officials said the landslides killed 250 camels and goats
and covered many of the water wells in the arid region.
   Much of the region's semi-nomadic population had fled the area
seeking shelter and food from nearby villages, the news agency said.
   The earthquakes' epicenter was described as 320 miles northeast
of the capital, Addis Ababa, between the towns of Dubti and Serdo.
Earthquakes of similar severity hit the same region in 1961 causing
several buildings to collapse.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means the ground motion is
10 times greater. A quake of magnitude 6.5 can cause severe damage.
</TEXT>
