<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Refugees     08-23 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Refugees,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Escape Wave Swells, More Than 2,000 in Four Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 East Germans have
escaped to the West through Hungary the past four days and sought
refuge in West Germany, a Foreign ministry source said today.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that so far
this month about 3,300 East Germans had illegally escaped from their
country. The refugees have overwhelmed West Germany's embassies
abroad and threatened its relations with communist East Berlin.
   The source said 2,000 East Germans who had escaped between
Saturday and Tuesday had applied to the West German Embassy in
Vienna for travel documents.
   He said Bonn's embassy in Prague, Czechoslovakia, was sheltering
nearly 140 East Germans. The Foreign Ministry said that mission was
closed this morning because its ability to house or help the
refugees was ``totally exhausted.'' A handful of the East Germans
could be seen through the fence of the embassy's large garden,
sipping coffee and smoking cigarettes early today. Czechoslovaks
seeking visas lined up outside.
   Bonn has also temporarily shut down its missions in East Berlin,
where 116 East Germans are holed up, and in Budapest, Hungary, where
171 had sought refuge. There also was one East German at the West
German embassy in Warsaw, Poland.
   The East German government of Erich Honecker has accused West
Germany of instigating the escapes and warned that relations between
the two Germanies will suffer if Bonn continues to harbor the
refugees.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Tuesday that he was willing to meet
with Honecker to try to resolve the issue. But he also said the
escapes would not stop unless East Berlin gives in to demands from
its public for social reforms.
   While Poland and Hungary have loosened the Communist Party's grip
on power, Honecker has held fast to policies that severely restrict
travel and free expression.
   Many refugees have said they fled across Hungary's border with
Austria because they had lost hope for change.
   Although the closure of the Budapest embassy had locked out
hundreds of East German arrivals, West German envoys have been
quietly issuing passports outside the mission grounds.
   That has allowed East Germans willing to sneak across the
Hungarian border at night to go directly to West Germany instead of
having to seek travel documents from Bonn's embassy in Vienna.
   Foreign Ministry officials said last week that more than 1,000
passports had been issueed to East Germans in Budapest after the
embassy closed.
   Spokesman Peter Rothen said today that the ministry would not
disclose the latest total because of the sensitivity surrounding the
refugee issue.
   Tensions between East Germany and West Germany have been
exacerbated by the shooting death late Monday of an East German
trying to flee across the Hungary-Austria border with his wife and
child.
   Hungary's MTI news agency said the man, Kurt-Werner Schulz,
struggled with a Hungarian border guard who tried to stop his flight
and was fatally wounded when he guard's handgun accidentally fired.
   The West German Foreign Ministry has demanded an explanation and
assurances from Budapest that armed force will not be used against
East German escapees.
   Bonn's Ministry for Inter-German Affairs reported earlier this
week that more than 65,000 East Germans have arrived here so far
this year in the largest migration since the Berlin Wall was erected
in 1961. At that time, East Germans were fleeing at a rate of 2,000
per day.
   West Germany expects more than 100,000 East Germans by the end of
the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
