<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0841EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WhaleKilled     08-23 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whale Killed,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sea World Resumes Whale Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The show goes on in the killer whale tank where
an aggressive orca bled to death after ramming her performing
partner before thousands of spectators.
   Sea World officials say they are continuing the shows to maintain
the routine for the park's other whales, including the orphaned
11-month-old calf, Baby Shamu, but environmentalists say the death
of the 6,000-pound Kandu points up that the giant creatures should
not be in captivity.
   ``Killer whales live out in the wild to be 50 to 70 years old but
only seven to eight years following their capture and this is one of
the reasons why Greenpeace has a long-standing opposition to their
captivity,'' said Ben Deeble with Greenpeace in Seattle.
   But Sea World veterinarian Jim McBain and other whale experts
said the altercation between the whales was neither unusual nor
unprecedented.
   Ken Norris, professor at the University of California, Santa
Cruz, who has studied whales for 35 years, said killer whales and
other marine mammals often fight, ram, chase and nip each other as
part of maintaining a social hierarchy.
   A necropsy on the 14-year-old Kandu revealed that she suffered an
upper jaw fracture after striking Corky, a 25-year-old, 8,000-pound
female killer whale. The fractured jaw triggered a hemorrhage into
her nasal passages.
   Kandu died Monday about 45 minutes after the collision.
   ``This is a difficult time for us,'' whale trainer Mike Scarpuzzi
told the audience at a shortened show Tuesday.
   ``The best thing to do is to get back into the daily routine with
normal exercise and activity that these whales so desperately
need,'' he said. ``What we're hoping is to get the baby back into a
sequence she is accustomed to.''
   ``The baby was showing a little confusion ... and then acts as if
she's expecting mom to show up at any time,'' McBain said. ``She was
agitated (Monday) night, but she's much more relaxed now.''
   Baby Shamu was nearly weaned at the time of her mother's death,
getting 90 percent of her diet from the 40-45 pounds of fish she
eats daily. McBain said he was optimistic that Baby Shamu was
sufficiently independent to survive the loss of her mother.
   Deeble wasn't so optimistic.
   ``Killer whales in captivity have a poor history of success and
having calves and the chances of having them live to adults is
poor,'' he said. ``Now in this case, where the mother is dead, it's
going to cut (Baby Shamu's) chances of survival.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
