<FIRST>r a PM-O'MalleyResignation     08-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Malley Resignation,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Regents Chairman Quits Over Turmoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the University of Maryland Board
of Regents has resigned in a swirl of controversy over his role in
causing the resignation of the new president of the system's
Baltimore campus.
   Peter F. O'Malley resigned Tuesday following an admission last
week that he made a mistake in proposing to move two professional
schools from the jurisdiction of the University of Maryland at
Baltimore. That proposal caused the abrupt resgination Aug. 14 of
UMAB President Augustus A. White III.
   The resignation of White, a prominent Harvard surgeon whose
hiring was seen by the faculty as a beacon of leadership for their
campus into the 1990s, infuriated the 32-member faculty senate. The
senate voted Monday to condemn O'Malley's call to transfer the
schools of social work and community planning and law from Baltimore
to Prince George's County, where O'Malley, a lawyer, is politically
powerful.
   ``I am a realist. My profession is to solve problems. I have gone
from being part of the solution side of the equation to being on the
problem side,'' O'Malley said in resigning. ``The alarming number of
distractions and the inability to focus on the issues cause me to
take this step.''
   White was upset that neither he nor faculty members were
consulted about the move, which he said O'Malley presented to him as
a done deal.
   O'Malley admitted his blunder last week and apologized for his
``serious and significant mistake'' that prompted White to quit
before he had even started work.
   ``Mr. O'Malley has done the right thing. I hope his decision will
make it more likely we'll be able to get Gus White to reconsider
coming here or at least help us get another candidate of equal
quality to become president of our campus,'' said Robert Bennett,
president of the UMAB faculty senate.
   White said through a spokeswoman Tuesday that O'Malley's
departure did not change his feelings about resigning the UMAB
presidency.
   ``His only comment on reconsidering the job is the new
development does not change his position,'' said the assistant,
Suzanne Hunerwadeo.
   The faculty senate's resolution said O'Malley's resignation was
the best way for the new University of Maryland system to recapture
its ``high standards'' and credibility in national academic circles.
   ``In light of Mr. O'Malley's resignation, I expect to become more
involved with plans for higher education in Maryland,'' Gov. William
Donald Schaefer said.
   Schaefer said last week he supported O'Malley despite the
controversy over White.
   O'Malley had been chairman of the Board of Regents since July
1979.
</TEXT>
