<FIRST>r i PM-Flight103     08-23 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 103 Relatives Pay Tribute to People of Lockerbie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of people killed in the Dec.
21 bombing of a Boeing 747 held a memorial today in the Scottish
town where the plane crashed and demanded stricter control of
airline safety.
   Bert Ammerman, U.S. president of the Victims of Pan Am Flight
103, also paid homage to the people of Lockerbie. He said the town
will ``always be sacred and have a special place in our hearts.''
   Speaking at a memorial service in Lockerbie Town Hall, which
became a temporary mortuary following the disaster, Ammerman said:
   ``It is right and proper that from this building where so many of
our loved ones lay, that we pay public tribute to the many people
from Lockerbie and surrounding area, from all walks of life, who
enfolded us in a cloak of love, prayer and compassion and have in so
many ways helped us day by day in our mourning and our struggle to
comprehend this insanity.''
   All 259 people on the plane died, along with 11 people on the
ground. Investigators said the aircraft was downed by plastic
explosives planted inside a radio-cassette player.
   Relatives of disaster victims are pushing for an inquiry into
airplane safety and say they are not satisfied with the British
government's responses since the bombing.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, but switched to
a larger airplane and took on more passengers and baggage in London.
The flight was bound for New York.
   ``We have a duty to the memory of those lost and to travelers of
the future to demand positive ongoing action to change dramatically
the current totally unacceptable thinking on air security and
responses to international terrorism rather than outraged
condemnation of the culprits,'' said Ammerman, whose brother, Tom,
was among the passengers killed.
   He criticized the security at Heathrow Airport, saying: ``The
smugness of the security people that they are doing an effective job
came through loud and clear.
   ``The feeling we got from them was that their system was fine.
But you can't have airlines giving security to themselves. It's like
a fox watching a hen coop.'
   After the Town Hall address, Ammerman, five other Americans and
Jim Swire, head of the British Relatives' Group, visited the Garden
of Remembrance at Dryfesdale Cemetery, where they placed a wreath
containing 270 red roses, one for each victim of the crash.
   ``We come to lay a wreath of 270 flowers representing all those
from 17 different nations who lost their lives in that disaster,''
said the Rev. Patrick Keegans, a Roman Catholic priest whose home
was damaged by the plane's falling wreckage.
</TEXT>
