<FIRST>r p PM-SCarolina-Abortion     08-23 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SCarolina-Abortion,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Candidates Headed For Runoff in Hilton Head Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters gave two pro-choice
candidates the nod over an abortion opponent in a primary for a
state House seat, but no one's sure what effect abortion had on the
election.
   Neither Holly Cork, a former legislative aide, nor David Ames, a
developer, received 50 percent of the vote so they will compete in a
runoff election Sept. 5 to become the Republican candidate for the
seat left vacant by the the death of Miss Cork's father, state Rep.
William Cork.
   Democrats have not fielded a candidate for the Oct. 10 general
election.
   Unofficial results from Tuesday's primary showed Miss Cork with
2,654 votes; Ames with 2,226 votes; and, Robert Graves, a
businessman who opposes abortion, with 1,805 votes, said Frank
Gibson, chairman of the Beaufort County Republican Party. Turnout
was about 30 percent, compared with 50 percent to 65 percent in
previous primaries.
   It was South Carolina's first election since the U.S. Supreme
Court's recent decision giving states more latitude to restrict
abortion.
   The race was watched closely by legislators for signs of public
sentiment on the issue. The General Assembly is expected to tackle
the question of whether the state should restrict a woman's right to
abortion when it reconvenes in January.
   Leading up to the election the candidates and party leaders said
abortion would be a pivotal issue in the race.
   But Tony Denny, executive director of the state Republican Party,
said Tuesday that hard work may have had just as much effect.
   ``Holly Cork led the ticket but she also was a very hard-working
candidate and knocked on more doors than the other two. Whether she
led the ticket because of her stand on abortion is hard to say _ all
three were strong candidates,'' he said.
   ``As to whether or not this is a referendum on abortion, I think
has yet to be determined.''
   He said that at the candidates' last stump meeting Monday night,
two questions were asked about abortion. Questions also were raised
on taxes, tourism and beachfront management.
   Ames, 45, said the abortion issue was very important in the race.
   ``But it will probably not be as important in the runoff because
both my opponent and I have views that are much closer than the
other candidate in the primary race.''
   Miss Cork, 23, said the national attention on the abortion issue
``made the voters here think about it more.''
   ``The abortion issue has magnified in the last couple of weeks
and that's been the result of the attention that we've gotten
through the media,'' she said. But she added: ``I'm not sure if
people were voting for the other candidates for their abortion
positions.''
</TEXT>
