<FIRST>r i PM-Baltics-Glance     08-23 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baltics-Glance,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at the Three Restive Soviet Baltic Republics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baltics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the three Soviet Baltic republics:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LITHUANIA _ This southernmost Baltic republic has 2.9 million
people. The Lithuanian language is spoken by 98 percent, and Russian
is the main language of 52 percent. The capital is Vilnius.
   The republic has declared Lithuanian its official language and
restored the flag of the state that was independent before World War
II.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LATVIA _ Just north of Lithuania, this Baltic republic has 1.4
million people. Latvian is spoken by 95 percent and Russian by 57
percent. The capital is Riga.
   A popular movement has been demanding more autonomy from Moscow.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ESTONIA _ This northernmost Baltic republic has 1 million
people. Estonian is spoken by 95 percent and Russian by 24 percent.
Tallinn is the capital.
   Estonia has issued a ``declaration of sovereignty'' from the
central Moscow government in all areas but defense and foreign
policy.
   It has also approved an amendment to the republic's constitution
requiring Estonian approval of all new Soviet laws.
</TEXT>
