<FIRST>r a PM-PolarCap 1stLd-Writethru a0476 08-23 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polar Cap, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Cocaine Finance Chief Defendant in Massive Laundering Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Polar Cap ...' to insert that Romero was among
those charged.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian economist facing extradition to the
United States is accused of laundering huge sums of drug money,
federal officials said.
   Eduardo Martinez Romero, the reputed financial wizard behind the
Medellin cartel, is a suspect in ``Operation Polar Cap,'' the
biggest money-laundering investigation ever conducted in this
country, Ronald Caffrey, a special agent in charge of the Drug
Enforcement Agency's Atlanta office, said Tuesday.
   The Medellin cartel is believed to be responsible for most
cocaine shipments to the United States.
   Martinez, 35, was arrested along with thousands of others in
Colombia in recent days in a crackdown on drug kingpins.
   Polar Cap has resulted in charges against 127 people, including
Romero, and two foreign banks.
   The multi-agency investigation spent more than two years
infiltrating a bogus gold shipping and smelting scam allegedly used
to launder hundreds of millions of dollars of drug money.
   Papers filed in federal court in Atlanta say the money-laundering
operation, known by its users as La Mina _ ``the mine'' _ laundered
some $1.2 billion in drug money between 1987 and February 1989.
   Polar Cap discoveries led to a guilty plea by Banco de Occidente
of Panama earlier this month to charges of laundering drug money.
The bank forfeited $5 million to the U.S. government. Similar
charges against the bank's parent institution, Banco de Occidente of
Cali, Colombia, were dismissed.
   A DEA agent in Atlanta, Cesar Diaz, said he visited Martinez in
the Colombian city of Medellin in October 1987. Martinez produced a
ledger showing he had laundered some $12 million in the previous
month through La Mina, Diaz said.
   ``Eduardo Martinez acted as a `broker' in negotiating with
various money-laundering groups as to their cost and services in
laundering the cartel's drug monies,'' the Atlanta indictment says.
</TEXT>
