<FIRST>r w PM-OAS-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0426 08-23 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OAS-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAS Mediation in Panama Seen a Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with remarks by opposition leader; picks up
at 3rd graf pvs, Panama's constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian opposition leader said today than
an Organization of American States effort to bring about a
democratic transfer of power in Panama has failed because Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega refused to step down as the nation's military
commander.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, a vice presidential candidate in the
abortive election process last May, told a news conference that OAS
mediators made an 11th-hour effort over the past few days to achieve
a solution.
   ``The basic result ... was to prove beyond any doubt that the one
issue that remained unresolved from beginning to end of the
negotiation was essentially General Noriega,'' Arias Calderon said.
   ``At no point did the representatives of the regime consider any
formula under which General Noriega would retire from his position
as commander in chief.''
   ``He now holds the Panamanian people as hostage,'' Arias Calderon
said, comparing the plight of his countrymen to that of the foreign
hostages being held in Lebanon.
   The opposition figure spoke hours before OAS foreign ministers
prepared to meet here today for the fourth and perhaps final time to
discuss Panama's political crisis, which began in May when
authorities voided the country's national election results.
   Panama's constitution requires a new president to take office by
Sept. 1.
   U.S. officials, asking not to be identified, said Tuesday it
appears likely that Noriega will arrange for the incumbent
president, Manuel Solis Palma, a Noriega loyalist, to be replaced by
an equally reliable successor. Noriega would retain
behind-the-scenes control in defiance of Bush administration wishes.
   Ecuadoran Foreign Minister Diego Cordovez, a member of the
mediating team, indicated in Panama the group lacks time to fulfill
the OAS call for a democratic transfer of power in Panama.
   ``I'm rather pessimistic,'' Panamanian Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, a
leader of the anti-Noriega forces in Washington, said Tuesday in a
telephone interview. ``The OAS will lose an opportunity to speak
loudly in support of democracy and freedom. I don't see within the
OAS the will to act in defense of the self-determination of the
people of Panama.''
   After a week-long visit to Panama that ended Tuesday, the
mediating team was to present a report on their efforts to the OAS
foreign ministers.
   Since May, the OAS deadline to achieve a democratic power
transfer has been extended twice. U.S. officials said Tuesday that
it is doubtful a further deadline will be set.
   Panama's election results were voided amid widespread allegations
of fraud. Independent observers said the anti-Noriega candidate,
Guillermo Endara, appeared to have won by a large margin.
   The Bush administration, Noriega's principle antagonist in the
hemisphere, has been pressing for a solution by the time the new
president is required to take office.
   ``We've supported the OAS mission,'' State Department deputy
spokesman Richard Boucher said Tuesday.
   ``We've supported the mandate they have to achieve a transfer of
power. We've stated very clearly that for that to occur Noriega must
go. We've stated very clearly our policy that there will be no
accommodation with the Noriega regime.''
   Sosa said Tuesday that he will close Panama's embassy here Aug.
31. That is the eve of the date on which Eric Arturo Delvalle, the
ousted president whom the United States still recognizes as the
country's legitimate authority, was scheduled to leave office.
   Delvalle was forced out by Noriega's allies 18 months ago but
Sosa, with U.S. government support, has refused to relinquish
control of the embassy.
   He said it would be inappropriate for him to remain at the
embassy after Delvalle's term expires.
   ``We have always maintained we are fighting for a constitutional
principle,'' Sosa said, adding that he and his family will move to
an apartment in Washington. He intends to continue his struggle
against Noriega, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
