<FIRST>u a PM-HelmsleyTrial     08-23 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Chapter in Helmsley Tax Evasion Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire hoteliers Harry and Leona Helmsley
evaded both personal and business taxes by contriving a ``clever
plan'' to charge millions in personal expenses to their businesses,
a prosecutor said today.
   ``Every dollar they spent in this scheme enabled them to save on
their own taxes and their businesses,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Cathy Seibel. ``They got twice the bang of the buck.''
   The prosecutor made her closing argument after seven weeks of
testimony in Mrs. Helmsley's trial. Harry Helmsley, 80, was
separated from the case because of failing mental competence.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is accused of evading more than $1 million in
federal taxes by charging personal expenses to her businesses.
Former aides Frank Turco and Joseph Licari are charged with
assisting in the scheme.
   Mrs. Helmsley's lawyers called only four witnesses. Two of them
were tax experts who told the jury that Mrs. Helmsley and her
husband actually overpaid taxes during 1983-85, the period covered
by the indictment.
   Jurors are expected to begin deliberations Friday.
   Ms. Seibel today called Turco and Licari ``two trusted
lieutenants'' who willingly undertook the job of executing the
scheme.
   The prosecutor listed expenses allegedly mischarged by the
Helmsleys, including $1 million to enclose a pool at their
Connecticut estate, Dunnellen Hall; $500,000 for jade art; $45,000
for a clock in the shape of the Helmsley Building in Manhattan; and
purchases as minor as milk from a grocery.
   ``It was really a clever plan,'' she said.
   Ms. Seibel responded to complaints from the defense that Mrs.
Helmsley, who faces 41 counts including tax evasion, mail fraud and
conspiracy, was overcharged. ``It is not an attack on Mrs. Helmsley
but a fulfillment of our obligation to enforce the law fully and
fairly,'' she said.
   Mrs. Helmsley and Turco also are charged with conspiracy to
extort payoffs from vendors doing business with Helmsley businesses.
   The prosecution called 44 witnesses, a number of whom depicted
Mrs. Helmsley as arrogant and greedy. They described how she
disputed bills for renovations at her estate and then charged many
of them to her hotel empire.
   Three liquor salesmen testified that they were forced to pay
kickbacks to keep their accounts at Helmsley hotels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
