<DOCNO> AP890823-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LAWater 1stLd-Writethru a0529 08-23 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Water, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0529,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Tells Los Angeles Hands Off Endangered Lake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `El Dorado ...' to CORRECT spelling of Audubon.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists have won a
victory with a judge ordering Los Angeles to temporarily stop
diverting water from streams feeding Mono Lake, a haven for birds
that has been steadily shrinking.
   Los Angeles officials said the ruling could mean depletion of
water reserves.
   El Dorado County Superior Court Judge Terrence Finney granted a
preliminary injunction Tuesday for the Audubon Society and the Mono
Lake Committee, which are trying to protect the Mono Lake nesting
grounds of California gulls.
   Finney said diversions from four of the seven streams that feed
the environmentally sensitive lake, surrounded by bizarre formations
of salt and minerals from the evaporating lake, must stop until
March 30, 1990, to allow the lake's water level to rise about two
feet.
   The judge ruled that the gulls would be threatened by coyotes
that could cross land bridges to island nesting grounds if the lake
dropped below a level of 6,377 feet above sea level.
   Finney also said mineral deposits exposed as the lake recedes
could be a source of dust hazardous to people living near the lake,
located on the arid eastern slope of the Sierra Nevada some 200
miles east of San Francisco.
   The diversions provide Los Angeles with hydroelectric power and
17 percent of its water, but combined with evaporation to lower
Mono's shoreline 43 feet between 1941 and 1981, although wet winters
have periodically raised the level a few feet.
   The city's critics have argued for years that unchecked
diversions eventually will cut the lake to a third its natural size,
raise the lake's salinity and threaten brine shrimp and birds that
eat the shrimp.
   The lake's Negit Island and Twain Island are nesting grounds for
California gulls. Finney said that when the lake drops to 6,376 feet
a land bridge forms to Negit, and at 6,373 feet there's a bridge to
Twain.
   ``Both of these islands were exposed to coyote predation earlier
in the decade as a result of land bridging, and the consequent
decline in the nesting population is still being repaired,'' he said.
   City officials say the ruling means about $15 million will have
to be allotted to purchase water and energy.
   Mitch Kodama, southern district engineer for the Los Angeles
Department of Water and Power and manager of Mono Basin issues, said
the city will have to purchase an additional 50,000 acre-feet of
water, the amount needed to cover 50,000 acres one foot deep.
   Because of current drought conditions, Kodama said the city is
already buying about four times the normal amount of water from the
Metropolitan Water District, an agency that serves as a water broker
for the city and other communities in Southern California.
   ``What we see here is a fivefold increase in the amount of water
we have to purchase from MWD this year,'' Kodama said. ``Certainly,
the ruling doesn't help us during this drought year. In order to
sell us the water, it means MWD will basically be dipping into next
year's storage.''
   ``We are extremely disappointed with this ruling because we feel
there would be no significant impact to the lake's ecosystem this
year by continuing planned diversions from four Mono Basin
streams,'' said James F. Wickser, the DWP's assistant chief engineer
for water.
   Betsy Reifsnider, associate director of the Mono Lake Committee,
hailed the judge's decision.
   ``I feel this is really a victory for the people of Los Angeles
because over 60 percent of those who visit Mono Lake each year are
from Southern California. It's their lake too,'' Ms. Reifsnider said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890823-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a BC-Hijacking-List     08-23 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hijacking-List,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Other Hijack Incidents in 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of other hijackings in 1989:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 20 _ Mental patient tries to commandeer airliner at Odessa
in the Soviet Union. Man taken into custody by policeman who boarded
the craft in exchange for passengers.
   JAN. 21 _ Passenger wielding torch attempts to take over
passenger plane at Ukrainian city of Ivano-Frankovsk in the Soviet
Union but is subdued by crew and several passengers.
   JAN. 31 _ Nicaraguan Indian exiled in Colombia hijacks airliner
with 122 aboard to Costa Rica by threatening to set passenger afire
with gasoline. Copilot overpowers hijacker, who was carrying two
juice cartons of gasoline with wicks, just before plane lands.
   MARCH 29 _ Two Czechoslovakian teen-agers shoot their way onto
Malev Airlines jetliner and commandeer plane to Frankfurt after crew
told them plane was incapable of flying all the way to United
States. They surrender when U.S. military authorities do not let
them enter the Air Force base adjacent to Frankfurt's commercial
airport. No one was hurt in the incident.
   MARCH 30 _ Man demanding $855,000 and flight to Pakistan tries to
hijack Soviet airliner, threatening to blow it up. After
negotiations in which some hostages were freed, KGB security agents
subdue the hijacker.
   APRIL 10 _ Two Haitian soldiers shoot their way aboard a small
plane preparing to take off from Haiti and hijack it to Florida.
Both men threw down their weapons and surrendered upon arrival at
Miami.
   APRIL 24 _ Hijacker with explosives strapped to his back
attempted to force domestic Chinese airliner carrying 50 people to
fly to Taiwan. Pilot fools hijacker by flying around before landing
in Fuzhou in Fujian. Reports said hijacker then blew himself up.
   MAY 18 _ Two South Africans attempt to divert to Johannesburg a
Soviet Aeroflot jet flying from Angola to Tanzania. Reports said
Soviet guard shot and injured would-be hijacker. Some reports said
the African National Congress had chartered the plane to transport
members evacuating bases in Angola. Crew member was also reported
injured. At least one man was sentenced to 30 years in jail after
pleading guilty to charges in Tanzania.
   MAY 27 _ Cuban immigrant attempts to hijack Miami-bound American
Airlines jet to Cuba. He is arrested after the pilot lands at Miami,
saying plane didn't have enough fuel to reach Havana.
   MAY 31 _ Claiming to have a bomb, two unarmed Haitians board an
Antillean Airlines jet in Haiti and demand they be flown to Israel.
The pilot continued on to his destination, Curacao, without telling
passengers of the attempted hijacking, having convinced the Haitians
they bound for New York. After landing, the pilot told passengers to
evacuate and two men were arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890823-0069 </DOCNO>
