<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Boats 1stLd-Writethru a0488 08-23 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Boats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Recover More Bodies From River Thames Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with four more bodies recovered; work
beginning to refloat pleasure boat; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers pulled more bodies from the River Thames
today, bringing to 48 the number of people known to have died when a
pleasure boat sank after being rammed by a barge, police said.
   Police believe the death toll from Sunday's accident could be as
high as 57 and searchers were continuing to look for more bodies.
There are 79 known survivors of the disaster.
   A Scotland Yard spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in
keeping with British practice, said 17 bodies were recovered from
the river Tuesday night and through today from several locations.
Some bodies had been carried for miles by the strong tides.
   The 90-ton Marchioness, carrying revelers on a late-night party
cruise, sank after being hit from behind by the 1,475-ton dredger
Bowbelle near Southwark Bridge in central London.
   The Marchioness, which had been hired for the 26th birthday party
of a London financier, was licensed to carry 149 passengers and two
crew members.
   Work began today to refloat the Marchioness so that it could be
towed downriver to a drydock at Greenwich.
   Salvage supervisor Ron Livett said it would probably be scrapped.
``Who wants to sail in her after this?'' he said.
</TEXT>
