<HEAD>Robbery Suspect Uses Police Station Phone Call to Intimidate a Witness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYLAND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect in a convenience store holdup has
been charged with intimidating a witness, by means of the one phone
call he was allowed from the police station after he was arrested,
police said.
   ``I've had prisoners use our telephone to order a pizza, but
never to call someone to intimidate them,'' Police Chief Thomas
O'Loughlin said.
   Police said Frenchman Glover, also known as Teddy Glover, 21, was
charged with armed robbery, conspiracy to commit a felony and
intimidation of a prosecution witness.
   Jeffrey Barber, 18, was also charged with armed robbery and
conspiracy to commit a felony in the holdup Monday night.
   Police said two men entered the store and put a kitchen knife to
a clerk's ribs, threatening to kill the clerk, then escaped with
$214.77
   Glover and Barber were arrested a short time later. The money
from the robbery and a knife were recovered at a residence, police
said.
   When Glover was allowed to make a phone call, he called a witness
at the residence and threatened to kill him if he cooperated with
police, O'Loughlin said. The person immediately reported the threat
to police, he said.
