<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru   08-23 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0522,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Threaten to Shell French Warships</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with arrest of hijacker. Pickup
5th graf pvs, `In another...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nabih Berri, leader of the Syrian-backed
Shiite Moslem militia, said today that his forces will shell French
warships gathering in the eastern Mediterranean if they approach the
Lebanese coast.
   Moslems accuse the French of backing Lebanese Christians. ``We as
nationalist and Moslem forces do not want a clash with France, but
we have to defend our dignity and homeland,'' Berri said.
   Also today, an Air France jetliner was hijacked by a man who
reportedly demanded that an international conference on Lebanon be
held.
   The Airbus A300 with 115 people aboard landed in Algeria, and an
Air France spokeswoman said the hijacking ended less than an hour
later with the arrest of a suspect. The spokesman gave no other
details.
   In another development, Sheik Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan,
president of the United Arab Emirates, called today for an emergency
Arab summit to assign Arab peacekeeping troops to Lebanon.
   ``If Lebanon collapses, that will be the end of the Arab
League,'' Zayed said in an interview with the Paris-based
Al-Hawadass weekly that was circulated by the official WAM news
agency.
   A three-member Arab League committee made up of officials from
Saudi Arabia, Algeria and Morocco has been unable to find a
settlement in the battle between Christian troops and Syrian and
allied Moslem forces.
   In Paris, European Community foreign ministers today issued an
urgent call for an immediate cease-fire in Lebanon and announced
that a fact-finding mission would be sent to Beirut within days.
   The ministers said the situation in Lebanon is ``fraught with
danger'' and ``urgently appealed to all parties to cease all gunfire
and bombing on land and sea and all forms of blockade and to
implement a total ceasefire ...''
   Syrian and Christian artillery exchanged fire sporadically in and
around Beirut during the night, violating a 6-day-old cease-fire.
Police reported one person was killed and 11 wounded.
   That raised the casualty toll since the latest civil war fighting
broke out March 8 to 790 killed and 2,201 wounded.
   There were renewed fears that France would join the fray. In
Beirut, the pro-Syrian Ash-Sharq daily declared in a front-page
headline: ``France reinforces its fleet. Lebanon and the region face
the threat of a large explosion.''
   Most of the eight-ship French task force, led by the aircraft
carrier Foch carrying nearly 2,000 marines, was expected off Lebanon
later today.
   French officials have said the flotilla was dispatched to
evacuate 7,000 French nationals, mostly Lebanese with dual
nationality, if the 5-month-old battle between Christian leader Gen.
Michel Aoun and the Syrian army worsens.
   But the mission has been threatened by Syrian-backed Moslem
forces, who claim the warships were sent to support Aoun.
   Aoun's estimated 20,000 troops, outnumbered about 3-1 by the
Syrians and their Moslem allies, are besieged in the Christian
enclave north of Beirut.
   Berri said his 6,000-strong militia, which has heavy artillery
and tanks, has ordered all its men in south Lebanon to ``carry arms
and join other Moslem and nationalist forces in confronting the new
crusaders.''
   Berri said in a statement published by Beirut newspapers that
France will be held responsible for the consequences resulting from
any military intervention by its warships in Lebanon.
   The Iranian-backed Shiite Hezbollah, or Party of God, has
threatened suicide bombings. The Revolutionary Justice Organization,
a faction allied to Hezbollah, has warned that two American
hostages, Joseph Cicippio, 58, and Edward Tracy, 58, are in danger
if the French force intervenes in Lebanon.
   Aoun was quoted as saying in an interview with Paris' France-Soir
daily that he had received military supplies from France as well as
his primary backer, Iraq, despite a Syrian blockade. Iraq is Syria's
main Arab rival.
   Aoun said: ``Of course, I wish for French military intervention,
but I cannot compromise the French position.'' He said he expected
the French warships ``to be put at my disposal to assure freedom of
movement in territorial waters,'' in an apparent reference to the
Syrian blockade.
   The Christian Ad-diyar daily, which is close to Aoun, said the
French flotilla was ``coordinating with the American 6th Fleet and
its radar bases in Cyprus,'' 100 miles northwest of Lebanon.
   Chris Shepherd, spokesman for the British forces on Cyprus,
denied the Ad-Diyar report. He told The Associated Press in Nicosia,
the island's capital: ``There is no such operations room. Our
aircraft are not on alert.''
   Asked if there were any arrangements for cooperation with the
French and the U.S. 6th Fleet, Shepherd noted: ``I have no idea and
it would be inappropriate for me to comment.''
</TEXT>
