<FIRST>r a PM-RingoSuit     08-23 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ringo Suit,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Starr Details Drinking in Court Deposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ringo Starr says he drank 16 bottles of wine a day
at one point during his bout with alcoholism and was frequently
drunk while recording an album he doesn't want released, according
to court documents.
   The former Beatles drummer detailed his drinking problems in a
deposition filed with Fulton County Superior Court Judge Clarence
Cooper, who is considering Starr's lawsuit to stop release of the
album. A 30-day order blocking release expires Thursday.
   In his lawsuit against CRS Records of College Park, Ga., and
producer Chips Moman, Starr contends his performance on the album,
recorded in 1987 but never released, is below his standards. Moman
has said the record could earn $3.5 million if it is released now,
while Starr is on his first U.S. concert tour since 1966.
   Starr recently underwent a much-publicized treatment for
alcoholism.
   ``Six or seven years ago, I felt I had a real problem,'' he said
in the deposition, filed earlier this week. ``But I couldn't seem to
deal with it.
   ``I went through a lot of the different stages where I thought,
`I'll only drink wine,' and I certainly did that for a while. But, I
mean, 16 bottles of wine a day was as bad as drinking hard liquor.''
   Starr said that during the recording sessions with Moman, he and
the other musicians sometimes were ``all under the influence.'' He
also said marijuana was smoked.
   Moman has testified that he did not allow liquor in his Memphis,
Tenn., studio.
</TEXT>
