<FIRST>r a PM-MeredithSentenced     08-23 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meredith Sentenced,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Activist's Son Gets House Arrest for Vehicular Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Meredith Jr., son of the civil
rights activist who was the first black admitted to the University
of Mississippi, has been sentenced to one year's house arrest for
two counts of vehicular manslaughter.
   Meredith, who was sentenced Tuesday in Superior Court, had
pleaded no contest in February to charges stemming from a 1987 car
crash that killed Paul Huard, 44, and Kevin Jones, 26.
   Huard and Jones, who worked with Meredith at a restaurant, were
riding in Meredith's sports car when it missed a curve and struck a
large boulder. Police said speed and alcohol were factors in the
crash. Meredith, 20, was seriously injured.
   Justice Roland Cole sentenced Meredith to two years in prison,
both suspended, followed by two years' probation. He also was fined
$350 and his license was suspended for five years.
   Meredith, a student at the University of Pennsylvania, will serve
his house arrest in Pennsylvania, Deputy District Attorney Anne
Jordan said.
   The elder Meredith was admitted to the University of Mississippi
in 1962, becoming the first black to enroll there. Four years later
he was wounded by shotgun blasts during a civil rights march across
Mississippi.
</TEXT>
