<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0541-a0548-a0549 08-23 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0541-a0548-a0549,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Lauds Gorbachev's Advice to Polish Communists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files, moves up material on Colombia, updates hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today said that Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev's reported counsel to Poland's
Communists to take part in the new government there was ``very
positive.''
   Bush, in a question-and-answer session with reporters at his
vacation home, said that although many changes are taking place in
Poland, ``there will be bumps in the road as these countries move
toward more democracy.''
   ``I thought the comment I saw attributed to Mr. Gorbachev was
very positive in this regard,'' he said.
   The president was referring to reports that Gorbachev had called
Poland's Communist leaders and apparently urged them to back away
from their hard line against participating in a government led by
the Solidarity independent trade movement.
   Asked about the situation in Colombia, where President Virgilio
Barco is engaged in a crackdown on drug lords who have carried a
wave of assassinations, Bush said: ``I have great respect for what
President Barco is trying to do. I am convinced he is determined to
whip the problem, to beat it.''
   And he also said the process of extraditing drug-trafficking
suspects to the United States for trial ``should go forward.''
   Regarding the possibility of sending U.S. troops to help Colombia
fight drug cartels, Bush said ``that whole question of troop
speculation, I think, got out of whack.'' Officials have said there
are no plans to send troops and Barco does not want them.
   White House spokeswoman Alixe Glen said Tuesday that the U.S.
government was awaiting a request from the Colombian government for
non-military help. She said the United States stands ready to
provide a variety of assistance, including anti-terrorist training
to Colombian judges, if requested.
   Bush also said he has no problem with the French sending warships
to the Mediterranean, although pro-Iranian militants holding
American hostages in Lebanon have reacted threateningly to that move.
   ``The French have had a longstanding history in Lebanon. They
have tried to be a catalyst for peace in Lebanon....I am not about
to criticize the French for what they are doing,'' Bush said.
   On the turmoil in Lebanon, he said: ``I feel a certain
frustration about Lebanon because we have not been able to be a
catalyst for peace.'' He said the United States remains available to
``consult with individual parties'' in the Middle East to try to
resolve the nation's civil war.
   Bush said he had no details of today's hijacking of an Air France
plane other than that the White House situation room had informed
him it had occurred. The plane subsequently landed in Algiers and an
unarmed Algerian emigre who had commandeered the airliner
surrendered.
   The president covered a wide range of subjects in his interview
with Maine reporters and a small group of national traveling press
corps.
   He said first lady Barbara Bush was fine following her eye
examination in Washington on Tuesday. After the news conference, he
took the reporters and camera crews to the tennis court on his
property to see his wife playing a game of doubles tennis.
   ``She'll kill us,'' the president said as he led the entourage to
the court.
   Mrs. Bush, grumbling about her tennis game, was asked how she
felt. At first she blurted out jokingly that she was ``just sick
about'' her game. She interrupted herself with a laugh and said,
``No, I feel wonderful.''
   The first lady posed for the cameras cross-eyed in a gesture
mocking the eye irritation that accompanies her Graves disease, a
thyroid imbalance. Bush ran on to the court laughingly and told her,
``Don't do that'' as he put his hand over her eyes.
   Doctors at Walter Reed Army Medical Center prescribed prednisone,
a cortisone derivative, to help combat symptoms of the disease,
which include eye tearing and some double-vision, according to a
statement issued by the first lady's office.
   On other matters, the president said:
   _Vice President Dan Quayle accurately stated U.S. policy when he
said this week that humanitarian aid to the Contras rebels should
continue even after Nicaragua's elections in February if the Contras
do not find the internal conditions satisfactory to permit their
return to their homeland.
   _The controversial Seabrook nuclear power plant in New Hampshire
should be allowed to go on line as long as safety considerations and
evacuation plans are assured.
   _He is disappointed he hasn't caught a single fish despite daily
attempts since he arrived in Maine on vacation a week ago, but ``I'm
going to get them today.''
   _Regarding his reflections on eight months in office, ``I try not
to measure by presidency by personal wins or personal losses, who's
up or who's down ....''
   Although polls show high public approval for his presidency, Bush
said he couldn't take those indicators too seriously because ``these
things change. ... So I don't make too much of these polls.''
   As to why he is apparently so popular, he said: ``Some of it is
my wife. Some of it is the fact that people see we're trying hard.
Some of it is fundamental values.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
