<FIRST>r w PM-UndergroundExplosions 1stLd-Writethru   08-23 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Explosions, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0535,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Agency To Decide Next Week Whether To Proceed In Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to fix first reference to Neal.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Nuclear Agency plans to decide
within 10 days whether a Texas ranch still will be considered as a
possible test site to simulate underground effects of nuclear
explosions, congressional aides said today.
   Officials from the agency met with aides to Sens. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, and Phil Gramm, R-Texas, this morning and said an
announcement on the future of the site near Del Rio would likely be
made next week, according to spokesmen for the senators.
   The proposed test site about 25 miles from Del Rio has drawn
opposition from area residents who are worried about the possible
effects the non-nuclear explosions could have on the water supply
and environment.
   Gramm plans to meet with officials and residents of the west
Texas city of 40,000 on Monday to discuss the tests and ``simply
give them a chance to tell him directly how they feel,'' said Larry
Neal, a spokesman for Gramm.
   The agency has spent two years chosing a site for the series of
graduated explosions, which would culminate in November 1992 with a
470-ton blast using conventional explosives. The tests are to
simulate the effects of nuclear explosions on underground missile
silos.
   The agency says the explosions are designed to have no
significant environmental impact.
</TEXT>
