<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   08-23 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: Gaza strip.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Aug. 22
   The News-Leader, Springfield, Mo., on Voyager 2:
   Humanity's thirst for knowledge of the heavens will be quenched
again as Voyager 2 pulls alongside the planet Neptune.
   What a bargain.
   Launched 12 years ago, this tiny exploratory robot has far
exceeded anyone's expectations. The price tag: $865 million, more
than the average taxpayer can comprehend, but less than the cost of
a pair of B-2 bombers.
   In return for the investment, Voyager 2 has beamed back priceless
information about the solar system, including extraordinary
portraits of some 40 worlds along the way.
   President Bush has challenged Americans to continue our adventure
in space through continued exploration. Voyager is proof that it can
be done, that knowledge has value, and that there are bargains even
in space.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 17
   The Watertown (S.D.) Public Opinion on whistleblowers:
   Even as you read this, officials somewhere in the depths of the
federal government may be selling this country's interests down the
river.
   ... If we lived in a perfect world, the higher-ups would ferret
out the wrongdoing, announce it at a press conference and mend their
errant ways. Sometimes they do.
   Unfortunately, as the Watergate and Iran-Contra scandals
demonstrated, government officials are less than candid when the
mischief is politically embarrassing to an incumbent president.
   Enter the whistleblowers, government employees outraged enough by
the shenanigans to tip off the media.
   They deserve public service awards. Apparently, the U.S. Justice
Department would rather throw them in jail. Deputy Assistant
Attorney General John Keeney informed Congress recently that the
Justice Department would resume prosecuting government employees who
leak information about its criminal investigations.
   (The policy's) vagueness would allow the Justice Department to
prosecute the whistleblowers selectively. That's almost certain to
lead to politically motivated witchhunts for those who made somebody
important look bad.
   We simply can't afford to muzzle the whistleblowers and the media
watchdogs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 15
   The Post-Tribune of Gary, Ind., on stockades in Arkansas:
   It's easy to understand the frustration of officials in the
Arkansas community of Dermott who recently decided to deal with
lawbreaking minors by throwing their parents into a public stockade.
   If anything has characterized the last three decades of American
society it is the deterioration of discipline among youth _ both at
home and in school.
   In most schools, teachers are no longer allowed to hand out
corporal punishment. At home, fewer and fewer youth grow up in
stable two-parent families. In households with two parents, (often)
both work.
   The result is many parents seem not to have the time nor the
inclination to discipline their children properly. They then
complain when school authorities try to do the job.
   Dermott officials hope the humiliation of parents being put on
public display in a stockade will spur them to discipline their
children.
   Pressure on parents through public humiliation, however, is
unlikely to achieve the desired effect. What it's more apt to do is
clog up the courts with challenges to the ordinance's legality. That
will teach youth another important lesson _ if you don't like
something, sue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 19
   The Bangor (Maine) Daily News on President Bush vacationing in
Maine:
   President Bush is in Maine for a three-week vacation. Since we
don't have to direct the traffic in Kennebunkport, we're pleased as
punch that he's here. The president's catching the end of summer on
the Maine coast can't help but have a beneficial influence on
international affairs. His prolonged visit even makes up for the
fact that his predecessor never found the time to set foot in Maine
during either of his two terms, even though he was reminded on
several occasions that you can get here from down Washington way.
   ... President Reagan came from a state where the sun sets over
the ocean. In Maine, that's where the sun rises. Surely, as a
president looks out over the water and ponders his responsibilities,
that must make a difference.
</TEXT>
