<HEAD>Summit of Portuguese-Speaking African Nations Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A summit of the leaders the five
Portuguese-speaking African states slated for Wednesday was
postponed indefinitely, officials said.
   The meeting of the former Portuguese colonies of Angola, Cape
Verde, Guinea Bissau, Mozambique and Soa Tome and Principe was
called off because of leaders' other committments, a Zimbabwe
Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
   The spokesman said no firm agenda was drawn up and a timetable
was not confirmed.
   President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos of Angola and President Manuel
Pinto Da Costa of Sao Tome and Principe left for home Wednesday
after attending two other summits in Harare.
   A summit of the nine-nation economic grouping of southern African
nations, including Angola and Mozambique, is scheduled to open in
Harare on Thursday.
</TEXT>
