<DOCNO> AP890823-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Flogging     08-23 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flogging,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong to End Flogging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday it will abolish
flogging, a criminal punishment once widely used in Hong Kong during
the heydey of the British empire.
   The punishment _ in which a male offender is beaten a maximum of
18 times with a cane in the presence of a doctor _ has declined
markedly in this British colony. Hong Kong courts ordered only two
floggings this year, compared with 476 floggings in 1952.
   ``The decline in the use of corporal punishment as a sentencing
option to the point where it is now rarely used indicates clearly
that it cannot be regarded as an effective deterrent, and is clearly
not seen as such by the courts,'' the government said in a statement.
   Andrew Stables, former chairman of the local branch of Amnesty
International, described flogging as a remnant from the colonial era
that has ``no place in a modern society.''
   Only men can be flogged and ``the instrument used shall be a
light cane or rattan of a type approved by the governor,'' the
statutes say. The maximum number of strokes that can be applied are
18 for offenders aged 17 or older to six for offenders under 14
years.
   Offenses that can lead to flogging include indecent assault,
piracy, robbery and rape of a female younger than 16. Most recent
floggings have been for weapons possession convictions.
   Flogging was abolished in Britain four decades ago, and the
decision to end it in Hong Kong was in part because of sensitivity
to international criticism.
   The government noted that retaining flogging would ``have made
Hong Kong vulnerable to criticism from the United Nations Human
Rights Committee'' because the punishment contravened the 1966
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
   Although a public opinion survey found a large measure of support
for the punishment, there were more effective sentencing options,
the government said.
   The government said all legislation giving courts power to give
sentences of corporal punishment would be repealed, but it did not
give a timetable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
