<DOCNO> AP890823-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     08-23 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Marks National Day With Military Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania held its first military parade in
five years Wednesday, the 45th anniversary of the day an anti-Nazi
alliance overthrew the fascist government and switched sides in
World War II.
   There was no word on whether National Day also was marked, as
expected, by the opening of a massive white marble building from
which President Nicolae Ceausescu and his wife, Elena, plan to rule
the communist nation. It is officially called the Palace of the
People, and popularly known as the Marxist White House.
   The parade and rally was held for the first time in a new square
outside the Museum of National History, described by the official
news agency Agerpres as ``a monumental edifice in an advanced
building stage.'' The square is near the Civic Center, a huge
housing project also near completion.
   Agerpres said 200,000 people filed past Ceausescu and other high
officials in the parade. Workers, folk dancers and athletes joined
the soldiers, tanks, mobile missiles and amphibious vehicles, and
Romanian-built jet fighters flew overhead, the agency reported.
   No reason was given for the military parade. Romania dropped such
martial displays after the the Helsinki agreements on European
security and cooperation were signed in 1975, except for a parade in
1984, the 50th anniversary of the anti-fascist coup.
   On Aug. 23, 1944, a broad coalition headed by King Michael
overthrew Marshal Ion Antonescu and put Romania on the side of the
Allies. In December 1947, the Communist Party assisted by Moscow
forced Michael out.
   Rumors have circulated in Bucharest for some time that the Palace
of the People, which includes state and party offices and is topped
by triangular metal flagpole, would be inaugurated on National Day.
   The new Boulevard of the Victory of Socialism, lined with new
apartment buildings still uninhabited, cuts a three-mile path
through the heart of what once was lively Old Bucharest.
   Ceausecu, Romania's leader since 1965, conceived the palace,
which has nuclear-proof bunkers, and the avenue. Hundreds of private
homes and at least 20 churches were demolished to make room for the
project, which began in 1984.
   Foreign diplomats in Bucharest say Ceausescu has tried to
transform Romania from a backward, agricultural society into an
industrialized nation like the one Stalin tried to build in the
Soviet Union, using similar methods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
