<FIRST>u a PM-IranContra     08-23 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran Contra,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Closes Hearing In CIA Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals panel today closed a
hearing in the Iran-Contra criminal case against former CIA Station
Chief Joseph Fernandez because of concerns about national security.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
closed the hearing after Edward Dennis, acting deputy attorney
general, said the court would be hearing information relating to
national security.
   Timothy Dyk, an attorney for several media outlets, objected to
the closing on constitutional grounds. However, the court ruled that
the matter was not subject to debate because of the verbal
certification by Dennis.
   Fernandez is accused of lying to investigators about his
assistance to Oliver North's Contra network. He is charged with two
counts of obstruction and two counts of making false statements to
the CIA inspector general's office and the Tower Commission in 1987.
   The court also heard arguments on whether the Justice Department
has standing to intervene in the case over the objections of
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh. However, no decision was
immediately made on that issue.
   Walsh's office has objected to the Justice Department taking
legal questions concerning classified information in the Fernandez
case to the appeals court. The independent counsel says the Justice
Department's action in effect would take control of the case from
Walsh's office.
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va., ruled
last month that Fernandez is entitled to disclose as part of his
defense the locations of several CIA facilities and details of
secret CIA programs.
