<FIRST>r i AM-Morocco-Rights     08-23 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morocco-Rights,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Calls On Morocco To Help Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed Wednesday to the
Moroccan government to give medical aid to three political prisoners
who the human rights group said are in critical condition after a
two-month hunger strike.
   Four political prisoners began a hunger strike June 17 to protest
conditions at Rabat's Laalou Prison, Amnesty International said.
   One of the prisoners, Chbada Abdelhaq, 28, died Saturday in
Rabat's Avicennes Hospital, the group said.
   Alami Bouti Hassan, Benabdessalam Abdelllah and Boukourou
Abdelfattah, all serving eight-year sentences for belonging to an
illegal left-wing organization, are comatose at the hospital,
Amnesty International said.
   Amnesty International said other prisoners have been waging
hunger strikes since 1986. The most recent series began in April
after incidents in which prisoners reportedly were ill-treated, it
said.
   ``Abdelhaq is reported to have been left chained to the floor of
a small, windowless isolation cell for a week, bleeding from the
nose, with no medical attention, toilet facilities or possibility of
moving from the ring to which he was chained,'' Amnesty
International said.
   ``The prisoners reacted by declaring a hunger strike which lasted
21 days and ended in May when the prison director apparently
promised improvements in their conditions of detention,'' Amnesty
International said.
   The hunger strike was resumed June 17 when improvements had not
been implemented, it said.
   Amnesty International urged Moroccan authorities to ``ensure that
the prisoners receive all the medical assistance they require and be
allowed regular visits by their families.''
   ``It is also urging that the conditions of treatment of prisoners
in Laalou Prison be investigated and any form of cruel, inhuman or
degrading treatment ended,'' the statement said.
