<HEAD>Forbes' Moroccan Extravaganza Spoils Commoners' Vacations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire publisher Malcolm Forbes' 70th
birthday party in Morocco forced a bunch of American tourists to
spend two nights in what they called ``seedy, crummy'' hotels.
   Forbes had secured plenty of first-class hotel accommodations in
Tangiers, Morocco, for his guests, but due to unexpected renovations
on some of those rooms, 33 other vacationers were bumped.
   ``We were a little upset in Tangiers because of Malcolm,'' Senta
Rodoff of New York City told New York Newsday.
   Forbes invited about 600 guests to the weekend party that was
estimated to have cost $2 million.
   Members of the vacation group were told King Hassan II ordered
the change in reservations.
   The group spent two nights in second-class accommodations, the
second night in a hotel that was in a neighborhood they deemed so
dangerous they feared to leave the building at night.
   Harlan Coben, senior vice president of Club ABC Tours of Union,
N.J., said he was unaware that the group was forced out of its
reservations.
   ``We had this trip planned for months and months and then we were
put in a seedy, crummy hotel,'' said Beverly Levy of Rochester.
