<FIRST>r a AM-BoozeCrackdown     08-23 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Booze Crackdown,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merchants Restrict Sales To Fight Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of store owners in the suburban San
Fernando Valley hopes to curb candy before school and swigging beer
out of brown paper bags.
   Twenty liquor store owners and two grocery store owners announced
Tuesday they have agreed to abide by some self-imposed guidelines
aimed at combatting drug- and alcohol-related crime in their
neighborhood.
   ``We have to control the alcohol sales in the community,'' said
Fred Taylor, owner of a religious bookstore and chairman of the San
Fernando Valley Community Advisory Board. ``And to do that, we have
to cooperate with the liquor stores.''
   His group and the Merchants for a Better Community came up with
the rules, which include:
   _No alcohol sales after 10 p.m. Sunday through Thursday or after
midnight Friday and Saturday.
   _No more sales of so-called short dogs, which are small, cheap
bottles of wine, or single cans of beer.
   _All alcoholic beverages will be sold in clear plastic bags so
the buyer can't stand on a street corner and swig. ``If he does, the
police will see him,'' reasoned grocery and liquor store owner
Samuel Rose.
   _No sales of papers that can be used to roll marijuana cigarettes.
   _No sales of balloons, which can be used to store heroin.
   _No sales of candy from 8 to 10 a.m. on weekdays because
merchants say it contributes to the cycle of addiction among
children.
   ``The kids get high on sugar before they get to school,'' Taylor
said. ``When they're hyper, it's a problem for the teachers.''
   The store owners also promised to clear graffiti and litter from
their businesses, boot out drug dealers who hang around and remove
pay phones that can be used to make drug deals.
   Rose said the actions shouldn't cost the stores more.
   ``You're going to make more money,'' he said. ``Now more families
will come in.''
</TEXT>
