<HEAD>Pilot Acquitted of Resisting Arrest After Flying Near Reagan's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot charged with resisting
arrest after flying in restricted airspace over Ronald Reagan's home
last year was found innocent.
   A Municipal Court jury on Tuesday acquitted Douglas Davis of the
misdemeanor charge.
   ``I just feel super, great. It feels good to be a free man
again,'' said Davis, 44.
   Davis' attorney, Scott Raphael, said the decision bolsters his
client's $1 million civil suit, which contends that an Orange County
sheriff's deputy used excessive force against him while he was
detained for questioning by federal agents.
   ``It was a tough case. I could see where the jury might have
found a reasonable doubt about his guilt,'' said Deputy District
Attorney David Frank, who prosecuted the case.
   The Federal Aviation Administration forced Davis to land after he
flew over the former president's home last Dec. 28. FAA rules
prohibited low-level flights over the area when Reagan was at his
Bel-Air home.
   Davis, a part-time pilot for a map-maker, said he was not
informed the restriction applied that day.
