<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-23 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Burst Into Hospital While Pursuing Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers forced their way into a Gaza
City hospital Wednesday while pursuing stone-throwing Palestinians,
and a hospital official said troops abused medical staff and
terrorized patients.
   About 30 soldiers seized four Palestinians at the hospital but
subsequently released them, the official said. Hospital workers
staged a sit-down strike to protest the raid, she said.
   The army said soldiers entered the hospital because they were
pelted with stones from the facility's grounds.
   Also Wednesday, police rounded up 170 Arab laborers from the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip who were caught spending the night
in Israel, a violation of rules requiring them to return home after
work, Israel radio said.
   The laborers later were released, the radio said. Most of the
arrests took place in the Galilee region in the north and the
coastal towns of Akko and Nahariya, police said.
   Many Arabs customarily ignore the rule to avoid the long daily
commutes back to the occupied territories, or to avoid participating
in strikes called by underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising.
   The arrests follows regulations instituted Friday that require
Palestinians to have special computerized identity cards to enter
Israel from the Gaza Strip.
   Palestinians say the cards are aimed at trying to defuse the
20-month-old uprising against Israeli rule, but government officials
maintain the system is meant to block ``potential offenders'' from
entering Israel following attacks on Jewish civilians.
   Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain during the uprising. At
least 545 Palestinians also have been killed by Israeli soldiers or
settlers, and 97 others have been killed by fellow Arabs, often
after allegations they collaborated with security forces.
   On Wednesday, a Scottish doctor performed an autopsy on the body
of 14-year-old Amjad Jibril Tawil, a Palestinian-American whose body
was found with a single bullet wound last week in the West Bank town
of El-Bireh.
   The independent autopsy, by Dr. Derick Pounder, was requested by
the family, which alleged the boy was in army custody before his
death. Pounder represents the Boston-based Physicians for Human
Rights. Tawil was born in Denver.
   The army said the government's own autopsy cleared soldiers of
involvement.
   The incident at Ahli Arab Hospital began when soldiers forced
their way onto the hospital grounds behind an ambulance, said a
hospital official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``They (the soldiers) treated our staff in a bad way, especially
in the emergency room, hitting people with their rifle butts and
pushing them with their hands,'' the official said.
   She said soldiers ran through the wards, including the children's
wing, ``scaring them terribly.''
   The official said soldiers detained four Palestinians who had
been doing construction work with stones and cement at the adjacent
nursing school, run by the American Baptist Mission. The four later
were freed, she said.
   The army said in a statement that ``after people threw stones
from the yard of the hospital, Israeli forces entered the hospital
to catch the stone throwers and caught four.'' It gave no other
details.
   Hospital officials denied stones were thrown from the hospital
grounds.
   Hospital staff staged a three-hour sit-down strike to protest the
raid. The hospital official said the Anglican Church, which runs the
hospital, was notified and complaints were filed with U.S. British
and Danish embassies.
   ``We are aware of the incident and we are checking with the
proper authorities,'' said a U.S. Embassy official who asked not to
be identified.
</TEXT>
