<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Bosses     08-23 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Bosses,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profiles of Figures in Colombia Wanted in United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of Colombia's powerful
cocaine cartels have built gangland empires and managed to avoid
prosecution. Here are sketches of the top bosses, wanted for
extradition to the United States, based on information from local
and U.S. authorities:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PABLO ESCOBAR GAVIRIA _ Nicknamed ``El Padrino,'' or ``The
Godfather'' ... age 39 ... considered a top member of the Medellin
cartel ... alleged to have begun his criminal career as a car thief
and hired gunman ... arrested in Bogota for cocaine trafficking in
1976 but spent little time in jail, terrifying the courts and
allegedly ordering the killing of an investigator ... formed his own
organization in the late 1970s, and tried to cultivate a Robin Hood
image by giving away free houses and building free neighborhood
recreation centers in Medellin ... Fortune magazine listed him among
the world's richest people, with about $3 billion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JORGE LUIS OCHOA VAZQUEZ _ Also of the Medellin cartel ... age 40
... leads a family operation that is less ostentatious than other
luxury-loving smuggling chieftains, but it also may be worth
billions ... arrested in 1984 in Spain, which rejected an
extradition request from the United States and instead sent him back
to Colombia, where he was freed by a judge ... arrested again in
Colombia a year later ... eventually let go on a bail equivalent to
$10,500.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JOSE GONZALO RODRIGUEZ GACHA _ Known as ``The Mexican'' because
of his affection for that country's music and culture ... age 42 ...
considered the No. 3 member of the Medellin group ... U.S. narcotics
experts say he has been stung by raids on his organization in recent
weeks ... Colombian police claim to have shattered his network in
Bogota, used for processing and exporting cocaine, much of it to the
Los Angeles area.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GILBERTO RODRIGUEZ OREJUELA _ Banker, sportsman and chess lover
... age 50 ... reputed to lead the cartel based in Cali ... arrested
with Ochoa in Spain but also sent back to Colombia ... eventually
released there ... authorities say his organization is involved in a
bloody, 18-month-old feud with the Medellin cartel over the
lucrative New York market.
</TEXT>
