<FIRST>r a AM-DerbyDilemma     08-23 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derby Dilemma,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Employee Doesn't Want Fishing Derby Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Exxon employee whose 314-pound
halibut is likely to win the Homer Jackpot Derby wants to withdraw
from the contest and give up her chance at the $10,000 first prize.
   Dorothy Porter of Rahway, N.J., told the Homer Chamber of
Commerce she has been harassed, apparently because of her
association with Exxon and the nation's worst oil spill.
   Porter is on leave until Aug. 30 from her job at Exxon's spill
response office in Homer. Some of the 11 million gallons of oil
spilled March 24 by the Exxon Valdez in Prince William Sound washed
ashore at Homer.
   ``I talked to her for half an hour and tried to talk her out of
it,'' said Beverly Wood, who manages the visitors' center operated
by the chamber, which runs the annual fishing derby.
   But Wood said Porter was upset, and insisted on removing her
photograph from a derby display and reclaimed her entry form.
   ``She said she got a lot of harassment and calls and conflict on
it,'' Woods said. ``She said she mulled it over for days on end
before making that decision.''
   Porter, who had never been fishing before, caught the monster
flatfish on Aug. 6 from a charter boat in Cook Inlet. She withdrew a
few days later.
   Wood said Porter told her she had worked for Exxon for 16 years
and did not want to cause the company problems.
   Reached by phone at her home Tuesday by the Anchorage Daily News,
Porter refused to discuss the matter. ``I don't wish to make a
comment. Thank you. Good-bye,'' she said and hung up.
   The company did not ask her to withdraw from the derby, an Exxon
spokesman said.
   ``This was a private, off-the-job, non-Exxon decision she made,''
said Fred Davis, a public information official at the company's
cleanup headquarters in Valdez.
   The second-place fish so far in the contest that ends Labor Day
is a 247-pounder caught by an Anchor Point woman.
</TEXT>
