<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Convent     08-23 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Convent,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Progress On Convent From Israeli Minister, Cardinal Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's minister of religious affairs and
a Roman Catholic cardinal did not resolve the dispute over a convent
at the Auschwitz concentration camp, the chief Israeli diplomat to
Poland said Wednesday.
   Zevulun Hammer, the first Israeli minister to make an official
visit to Poland since diplomatic relations were severed 22 years
ago, on Tuesday asked Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of Krakow to
move the convent according to a 1987 agreement.
   The cardinal said, however, there was no immediate plan to
transfer the nuns, said Mordechai Palzur, head of Israel's interest
section in Poland.
   ``They are not moving for the time being and when it can happen
is unclear,'' he said. ``He did not say it was a closed matter, but
it is not a matter of days or weeks or even months.''
   Jewish groups and others have protested the convent as a
intrusion of Christian symbols at the place built by the Nazis
mainly to exterminate Jews. An estimated 4 million people, at least
2.5 million of them Jews, were murdered at the death camp complex.
   Hammer, who lost members of his family at Auschwitz, visited the
camp for the first time before meeting with Macharski in nearby
Krakow.
   Macharski said this month that the convent, housed in a former
Nazi warehouse on the perimeter of the camp, would not be moved as
had been promised in an international accord reached by Jewish and
Catholic leaders in Geneva.
   Catholic leaders had agreed to move the Carmelite nuns by Feb. 22
to an interfaith prayer center farther from the camp. Protests
increased after the deadline passed, including one July 14 when an
American rabbi and six students were roughly removed from the
convent. Macharski then said the agreement would not be honored in
an ``atmosphere of aggressive demands.''
   The cardinal said the protests had created opposition to moving
the convent, particularly among residents of the town in southern
Poland where the death camp is located.
   Macharski told the Israeli delegation that he had intended to
move the convent when the agreement was reached, ``but now was not
in a position to go ahead with the plan,'' Palzur said.
   Palzur said he assured the cardinal he would be available to help
in any way needed to mediate the situation but noted he had no
control over those who might protests at the convent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
