<DOCNO> AP890823-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     08-23 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Extending Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government will extend for
another month its unilateral cease-fire in the country's 6-year-old
civil war, a senior officer was quoting as saying Wednesday.
   Brig. Dominic Kasiano told the Armed Forces newspaper the
extension demonstrates the government's good will toward the rebels
even though the two sides failed to reach an agreement in their
first round of peace talks over the weekend.
   He said the cease-fire was being extended to the end of September.
   The country's military rulers, led by Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan
el-Bashir, deposed a civilian government in a coup in June and
pledged to promote peace efforts.
   Kasiano, a member of the 15-member ruling council, said the
government ``has shown good intent of seeking to halt the bloodshed
and find a durable and comprehensive solution to the question of
southern Sudan,'' according to the newspaper.
   The rebels of this East African nation took up arms in 1983,
demanding greater autonomy for the southern region.
   Fighting has ceased almost completely since April, when the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army declared a unilateral cease-fire to
allow a U.N. relief operation to distribute food to starving
Sudanese in the south. The rebels later extended their cease-fire
until the end of June.
   El-Bashir's government, in turn, ordered a cease-fire during July
and then extended it until the end of this month.
   The two sides are expected to resume their peace talks, but no
date has been set.
</TEXT>
