<HEAD>Opposition Leader Vows to Fight if Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung
underwent questioning Wednesday by prosecutors who have linked him
to a North Korean spy case, and he vowed to fight the accusations in
court if necessary.
   Government prosecutors have not filed formal charges against him,
but they have said they have enough evidence to do so.
   Newspapers quoted unidentified prosecution officials as saying
Kim would soon be indicted with two other lawmakers of his Party for
Peace and Democracy. The reports said they would be accused of
violating national security laws.
   ``Should the prosecution indict me, I will fight squarely in
court,'' Kim, 64, said after the questioning. ``I am innocent, and I
expect truth to be established.''
   He also has denied wrongdoing in the past. He has said the
government is harassing him and trying to embarrass the political
opposition.
   Kim, the leader of the country's largest opposition party, has
twice been indicted on charges of violating national security laws.
The two-time presidential candidate has spent almost seven years in
prison for sedition and anti-government activity in 1976 and 1980.
   He was allowed to leave early Wednesday after a 15-hour
interrogation by prosecutors. It was the second time in three weeks
he has faced questioning about the illegal trip to North Korea by
then-lawmaker Suh Kyung-won.
   Suh was arrested on June 28 and ousted from Kim's party because
of the publicity. He has been charged with espionage, making the
unauthorized trip to North Korea in August 1988, and receiving money
from North Korean agents.
   The opposition leader is suspected of receiving $10,000 from Suh,
who admitted to investigators that he was given $50,000 after
meeting with North Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
   Kim Dae-jung also is accused of knowing of Suh's trip two months
before the case was made public in June 1988. Failure to report such
a case to authorities is a crime under Korean law.
   Unauthorized visits to North Korea are also outlawed.
   Prosecutors have indicated they will also indict floor leader Kim
Won-ki and Rep. Lee Chul-yong, both of Kim's party, on charges of
failing to report Suh's case. The two lawmakers have denied the
accusation.
</TEXT>
