<FIRST>r a AM-LonetreeBook     08-23 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lonetree Book,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Stop Distribution of Book About Lonetree Spy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for former Marine Sgt. Clayton
Lonetree on Wednesday failed to stop distribution of a book about
his role in a sex-for-secrets scandal at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton refused to grant a preliminary
restraining order against the publisher, Henry Holt and Co. Inc. of
New York, saying Lonetree had waited too long to try to stop the
book sales.
   Lonetree, of St. Paul, Minn., claims the book, ``The
Court-Martial of Clayton Lonetree,'' contains confidential
information obtained by his defense team that could be used against
him if he wins a new trial on his espionage conviction.
   But Hilton said it was too late.
   ``These matters have already been in the press,'' the judge said.
``It's already out.''
   Holt published the book in June and says it has sold about half
the 13,000 copies.
   Hilton also said Lonetree had not proven that publication would
hurt his chances of reversing his conviction.
   Lonetree filed suit last week seeking $100,000 in punitive
damages from Holt and Las Vegas private investigator Lake Headley,
who worked for Lonetree's lawyers during the court-martial and
helped write the book.
   Lonetree was convicted in 1987 of passing U.S. Embassy floor
plans and the names of CIA agents to the Soviet Union at the request
of his Soviet lover. At the time, Lonetree was stationed as a
security guard in Moscow and Vienna, Austria.
   The book purportedly contains details of Lonetree's affair and
espionage activities that had not been disclosed before.
   An attorney for Lonetree, Lee Calligaro, argued that Headley
disclosed information about the case that Lonetree provided in
confidence to the investigator and his attorneys.
   During the hearing Wednesday, Calligaro read a passage of the
book that described in detail how Lonetree considered killing
himself. The information could only have come from Lonetree's
defense team, Calligaro said.
   ``The public and court system have an abiding and deep concern in
the sanctity of the attorney-client privilege,'' Calligaro said.
   Robert Callagy, an attorney representing Holt, told the judge
Lonetree ``has been on notice for at least nine months that Holt is
going forward with this publication.''
   The publisher claims Lonetree waived his right to maintain the
confidentiality of the information he gave his lawyers. Lonetree is
quoted in the book as once having told Headley: ``When this is over,
I want you to get my story out to the public.''
   Lonetree is serving a 25-year prison sentence at Fort
Leavenworth, Kan. An appeal of his conviction is pending with the
U.S. Navy-Marine Corps Court of Military Review in Washington.
</TEXT>
