<FIRST>r a AM-Iran-Contra     08-23 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Panel Closes Hearing in Fernandez Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court panel held a hearing
behind closed doors Wednesday to protect secrets during arguments
about an Iran-Contra criminal case against a former CIA official.
   Edward Dennis, acting deputy attorney general, said the
three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals would
hear information relating to national security.
   Judge Robert F. Chapman of Columbia, S.C., said federal law
required him to close the hearing if the attorney general's office
made that certification.
   ``There's nothing else we can do,'' Chapman said. ``The lives of
people who work for the United States would be endangered'' by an
open hearing, he said.
   Timothy Dyk, an attorney for several media outlets, had objected
to the closing on constitutional grounds. The court refused to hear
his arguments.
   The Justice Department and the office of independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh are feuding over how to proceed in the case against
Joseph Fernandez, a former CIA station chief in Costa Rica.
   The Justice Department wants to appeal a federal judge's ruling
that Fernandez may disclose as part of his defense secret
information that the department says would jeopardize national
security.
   However, Walsh's office says an appeal is a prosecutorial
function granted specifically to the independent counsel's office by
federal law. Lawyers for Walsh say the Justice Department's appeal,
in effect, would wrest control of the case from the independent
counsel.
   Gerard Lynch, an attorney for the independent counsel, told the
appeals court that the proper procedure for the Justice Department
would be to file an affidavit under the Classified Information
Procedures Act barring disclosure of the information.
   Dennis said such action almost surely would lead to dismissal of
some or all of the charges against Fernandez. Two counts in the
Iran-Contra case against Oliver North were dropped because
information vital to the prosecution could not be disclosed for
national security reasons.
   ``We're not trying to prosecute the case,'' Dennis said. ``But
the impact of an affidavit is appropriate for us to consider. It
would risk dismissal of the prosecution.''
   If that happened, Lynch said, the independent counsel's office
would appeal the dismissal.
   ``It's inevitably a two-headed monster here,'' Lynch said. ``The
question is which head is going to control the decisions.''
   Fernandez is accused of lying to investigators about his
assistance to North's Contra network. He is charged with two counts
of obstruction and two counts of making false statements to the CIA
inspector general's office and the Tower Commission in 1987.
   Among the secrets U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton of
Alexandria, Va., ruled Chapman has a right to disclose are the
locations of CIA stations in El Salvador and Honduras and another
CIA facility in a Latin American country.
   Hilton also ruled Chapman may reveal details about a
communications station and other projects in Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
