<DOCNO> AP890823-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Fertilizer     08-23 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Fertilizer,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Complain Of Ill Effects From Fertilizer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a half-dozen oil spill cleanup
workers have reported being burned or suffering other problems from
fertilizer being spread on Alaska beaches to help oil-eating
bacteria grow.
   Six workers on two beaches on the southern end of the Kenai
Peninsula apparently suffered minor burns last week from the ammonia
nitrate fertilizer, said industrial hygienist Mack Davis of the
state Office of Safety and Health.
   There have been at least three more cases since then, Steve
Provant, the state on-scene coordinator for the cleanup, said
Tuesday. The cleanup has been going on since 11 million gallons of
oil were spilled March 24 by the tanker Exxon Valdez in Prince
William Sound.
   The Coast Guard has begun requiring that workers spreading the
nutrient on the beaches wear respirators.
   Exxon has applied ammonia nitrate to 17 miles of beach so far.
Seventy more miles of coastline are to be fertilized to help
encourage microbes to devour some of the remaining oil.
   Workers suffered blisters and rashes on their hands, said health
aide Sandy Elvsaas in Seldovia. When the blisters burst, they leave
large, red patches of raw skin.
   ``It looks basically like a burn,'' she said. Elvsaas said the
workers she treated appeared to be healing well.
   Gary Hanson, foreman of a beach crew working near the head of
Chugach Bay, said workers saw the fertilizer on the beach and picked
some of it up. He said they were never warned not to.
   Workers who wear protective clothing issued to cleanup crews
shouldn't have any problem with the fertilizer, state safety and
health officials said.
   But because it is hot on the beaches, workers sometime discard
gear, Hanson said. Workers cutting oily logs into firewood-sized
chunks couldn't survive inside the plastic suits. ``It's a
sweatbox,'' he said.
   Exxon is doing urine analyses to determine whether workers have
absorbed unhealthy doses of ammonia nitrate, Bill Rainey, Exxon's
director of operations for the spill, said Tuesday.
   There should be no health risks from the fertilizer if it is
washed off with soap and water, he said.
</TEXT>
