<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Heartened by Gorbachev's Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 20th graf pvs, _He does, to CORRECT average income in Maine.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush praised Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Wednesday for urging the Polish
Communist Party to participate in the new Solidarity-led government,
saying the intervention was ``a positive sign.''
   Bush also told reporters at his vacation home that administration
and Colombian officials were discussing what U.S. aid the South
American nation might need to help fight drug cartels.
   And the president said he had no problem with France sending its
warships into the Mediterranean although the action has provoked
threatening statements from the pro-Iranian terrorists holding
Americans hostage in Lebanon.
   ``I am not about to criticize the French for what they are
doing,'' in sending ships to stand by for possible evacuation of
French nationals from Lebanon, he said. ``They have tried to be a
catalyst for peace in Lebanon.''
   Bush, standing with his back to the ocean at his scenic seaside
home, took questions on a variety of topics from a group of Maine
reporters and several Washington reporters traveling with him.
   He then took the group to watch his wife, Barbara, play doubles
tennis to prove she was feeling fine after being prescribed a new
medication for eye irritation stemming from her Graves Disease.
   Bush was asked if he thought the Soviets were playing a helpful
role in Poland in light of Gorbachev's 40-minute phone call to
Soviet Communist Party leader Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski. After the
call, Polish communist leaders announced they would be willing to
enter a partnership with the evolving Solidarity-led government.
   On Sunday, the Polish communists had demanded more than the two
ministerial posts promised to them earlier in an agreement with
Solidarity and had said it wanted to be treated as a full governing
partner in the new government.
   The Communists, in the unusual announcement of Gorbachev's call,
indicated anew their insistence on a strong Communist presence in
the government, but also reflected Moscow's acceptance of the idea
that the party should reach an accommodation with the Solidarity-led
coalition.
   ``There are a lot of changes taking place. ... It will be far
reaching. There will be bumps in the road as these countries more
toward more democracy. There's no question about that,'' Bush said.
   ``But I feel the statement I saw attributed to Mr. Gorbachev was
very positive in this regard _ very.''
   On another matter, Bush said that Vice President Dan Quayle had
``ably spelled out our policy'' when he said that humanitarian aid
to the Nicaraguan Contras should continue ``until safe and
democratic conditions'' exist in Nicaragua, even after the elections
there in February.
   ``I don't want to see the mandatory demobilization of those
Contras before the elections. I've felt ... that the pressure from
the Contras has been the thing that's led (President Daniel) Ortega
to start moving a little bit on free, fair elections,'' Bush said.
   Officials have said the administration supports the ongoing peace
efforts of the Central American presidents, who have called for
demobilization of the Contras by year's end coupled with democratic
reforms in Nicaragua.
   Bush reiterated his support for Colombia's President Virgilio
Barco in that nation's attempted crackdown on drug lords.
   ``I have great respect for what President Barco is trying to do
... It's a tough problem that he faces. I am convinced he is
determined to whip the problem, to beat it and free his country from
the grip of drug cartels.''
   He said speculation that the United States might send troops to
help Barco's anti-drug efforts ``got out of whack'' in news accounts
after Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Sunday that would be an
option if Barco asked for it. Barco has said since that he does not
want U.S. military personnel and administration officials have said
there are no plans to send troops.
   If such aid were requested, Bush said, ``Of course I'd take that
under consideration, but that is not what's being considered at
all.''
   On other matters Bush said:
   _He does ``my very best'' to stay in touch with average people's
concerns. Asked how he can relate to the average Maine resident, who
makes just over 15,000 a year, Bush replied:
   ``I'm very privileged and lucky in that regard. But I also don't
think the average Mainer begrudges me a vacation of any kind ...
I've got a lot of friends from all walks of life. And there is a
little tendency in this job to get isolated.''
   _Asked why Americans give him such favorable poll ratings, he
replied:
   ``Some of it is my wife. Some of it is the fact, I think people
see that we're trying hard. It's fundamental values. Some of it is
that I've tried to calm things down and work with Congress.''
</TEXT>
