<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     08-23 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibian Guerrillas Admits Prisoners Tortured, Says All Now Free</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Namibian guerrilla movement
acknowledged Wednesday it tortured its political prisoners, and it
invited foreign observers to verify its claim that all such inmates
now are free.
   Hidipo Hamutenya, spokesman for the South-West Africa People's
Organization, said the group would allow the International Red
Cross, Amnesty International and the United Nations to inspect sites
in Angola and Zambian where dissidents and suspected spies were
detained.
   The organizations have for years been denied access to the camps
despite repeated requests.
   Hamutenya said the guerrilla group released in May all 201
prisoners in its custody as part of the U.N.-sponsored plan to bring
independence to Namibia next year after 74 years of South African
rule.
   Former detainees have said the group still holds as many as 2,000
additional prisoners in underground pits. The ex-prisoners have
compiled a list with the names of more than 500 people they believe
still are detained or have been killed by the guerrilla group.
   ``The best way to get to the bottom of this issue is for the
groups we have mentioned to go to Angola (and Zambia) ... to satisfy
yourself,'' said Theo-Ben Gurirab, who handles South-West Africa
People's Organization's foreign affairs. ``We will continue to say
we are not holding any more prisoners.''
   Gurirab said some former prisoners ``were tortured and officers
charged with gathering information (from prisoners) ... carried out
brutalities against these persons, which we very much regret.''
   Gurirab said, however, that his group would reject a formal
international investigation of war-time abuses.
   After independence, expected early next year, church leaders,
tribal chiefs and community groups should conduct a ``full
inventory'' of alleged abuses by both the guerrillas and the South
African-led security forces, Gurirab said.
   The two sides fought a 23-year-bush war in northern Namibia, and
the security forces were accused of dozens of abuses against both
civilians and guerrillas.
   Many alleged abuses have been blamed on a paramilitary police
unit known as Koevoet, the Afrikaans word for ``crowbar.'' The unit
was disbanded in January, but many members were integrated into the
regular police force.
   The guerrilla organization, with U.N. backing, has said
ex-Koevoet members continue to harass civilians and should be
removed from the force. Namibia's South African administrator, Louis
Pienaar, has refused to dismiss ex-Koevoet fighters, but has
confined them to base.
   Gurirab said that unless intimidation of guerrilla supporters
ends, ``we cannot see how the election can be free and fair.
   ``We are for a clean campaign, but it is becoming difficult to
restrain our members,'' he added.
   More than 600,000 of an estimated 675,000 eligible voters have
registered for the polls. Namibia, the size of France and West
Germany combined, has only 1.3 million people and more than 50
percent are illiterate.
   Gurirab also said that South-West Africa People's Organization
leader Sam Nujoma has decided not to return to Namibia this weekend
and has set no date for coming back. He has been in exile since 1960.
</TEXT>
