<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     08-23 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Expects Accord on Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister said
Wednesday he expects an international peace conference on Cambodia
to reach a settlement in the decade-old war in that country.
   ``I expect there will be a comprehensive solution, but at the
same time I must be prepared for the worst,'' Nguyen Co Thach said
of prospects for the peace conference in Paris, where he will head
Friday.
   Thach was echoing remarks made by Cambodian Premier Hun Sen in
Phnom Penh on Thursday before he left for Paris. Vietnam invaded
Cambodia in 1978, ousting the communist Khmer Rouge regime and
installing another regime.
   Vietnam has pledged to withdraw its estimated 26,000 troops from
Cambodia by Sept. 26.
   Thach said he expects the main point of disagreement at the
conference to be the role of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia's future.
   ``The main difficulty is the question of recognition of the
genocide of Pol Pot,'' he said.
   Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
during its rule between 1975 and 1978. The Khmer Rouge now controls
the largest fighting force in the three-faction guerrilla alliance.
   The governments of Vietnam and Cambodia have insisted the Khmer
Rouge should not be allowed take part in any future coalition
government in Cambodia while its old leadership remains intact. The
United States has also said the Khmer Rouge should not be allowed to
return to power.
   The rebel clandestine radio station, Voice of The Khmer, on
Thursday quoted the guerrilla coalition leader, Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, as ruling out a proposed two-party power-sharing
arrangement between his faction and Hun Sen.
   The report said Sihanouk restated his demand for forming a
provisional four-party government of all the Cambodian factions,
including the Khmer Rouge and the Hun Sen administration.
   The Paris conference, which began at the end of July, is being
attended by representatives of all four factions.
   The conference sent a investigation team to Cambodia to assess
the possibility of forming international mechanisms to help bring
peace to Cambodia.
</TEXT>
