<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1634EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Turkey-Bulgaria     08-23 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkey to Close Railway Link to Europe to Block Refugee Influx</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto IST1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday it will shut
down its railway link with Europe to stop ethnic Turks from Bulgaria
who are trying to enter Turkey illegally.
   The single European train that travels daily between Munich, West
Germany, and Istanbul goes through Austria, Yugoslavia and Bulgaria.
It is Turkey's only rail link to those countries.
   In his announcement, Foreign Ministry spokesman Murat Sungar told
reporters the train service would stop Friday. He said that until
then, all ethnic Turks traveling on the train without visas would be
turned back.
   Hundreds of ethnic Turks have been arriving daily on the train
since May. About 310,000 ethnic Turks from Bulgaria have flooded
into Turkey in the past three months by train and other means.
   The Turks say they are fleeing a harsh assimilation campaign that
has forced them to use Slavic rather than Moslem names. They say
they have also been fined and beaten for speaking Turkish in public
and for practicing Islam.
   On Tuesday, Turkey began requiring visas for the refugees.
   Turkish officials initially tried to turn back a group of 522
ethnic Turks without visas who rode the European train on Tuesday.
But authorities allowed the refugees to cross the border after some
tried to jump out of the train.
   Sungar said Turkey might review its decision to close the railway
if the Bulgarian government guarantees it will not send immigrants
without visas on the trains.
   Turkish officials say they are trying to negotiate an immigration
accord guaranteeing protections for departing Bulgarian Turks, such
as compensation for property. The officials say that meanwhile, they
are trying to gain some control over the crush of refugees.
   However, opposition parties accuse the government of backing away
from its pledge to accept any of the estimated 1.5 million ethnic
Turks who want to leave Bulgaria.
   A Bulgarian immigrant who crossed the border with a valid visa
said thousands of ethnic Turks were waiting on the Bulgarian side,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Wednesday.
   It quoted Ahmet Durmushev as saying the refugees were living ``in
miserable conditions, with little water or food.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
