<FIRST>r a AM-BarbaraBush     08-23 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Plays Tennis, Turns Cross-Eyed for Reporters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Heminway, 9th graf, is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush played tennis
Wednesday and bantered with her husband a day after beginning new
medication for her Graves' disease, then posed cross-eyed for
reporters in mock exaggeration of her condition.
   ``Can we inspect your eyeballs, please?'' President Bush called
to his wife as she enjoyed a spritely game of doubles at the
couple's seaside vacation home.
   She walked to the edge of the court, where the president had
brought a gaggle of reporters and cameras. Mrs. Bush stood with her
hands on her hips and made a bug-eyed face, crossing her eyes toward
her nose.
   ``My eyes are just fine,'' she said, before the president
playfully ran onto the court and tried to put his hand over her
eyes. ``Don't do that,'' he said laughing.
   Asked by reporters how she was feeling, she at first said she was
``just sick about'' her tennis game, then added, ``No, I feel
wonderful.''
   Mrs. Bush on Tuesday was ordered by doctors to begin taking
prednisone, a mild steroid, for eye irritation and double vision
triggered by Graves' disease, a thyroid condition she suffers.
   The thyroid-attacking characteristics of the disease were
arrested by a radioactive iodine treatment she had a few months ago,
but the eye condition had not improved, her office said.
   She interupted her vacation with Bush to return to the doctors in
Washington on Tuesday, but was back that evening.
   The first lady at first acted annoyed with her husband for
bringing reporters to watch her play with partner Betsy Heminway
against daughter-in-law Margaret Bush and cousin Debbie Stapleton.
   The president took on a mischievous air when suggesting to White
House Chief of Staff John Sununu, Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater
and the reporters that they take a stroll over to the court
following a question-and-answer session in front of the Walker's
Point home.
   ``I thought there were some things George Bush wouldn't stoop
to,'' Mrs. Bush joked.
   Dressed in visor cap and white tennis dress, the first lady
appeared in fine form, vigorously hitting and serving the ball.
   However, the president joshed during serve change between games
that ``it's like watching grass grow out there.''
   He said his wife's eyes already had improved and that the doctors
had said she would get quick relief with the prednisone, a form of
cortisone with fewer side effects.
   Graves' disease results from a mixup in the body's
disease-fighting immune system. The body produces antibodies that
mistakenly attack the thyroid gland as an enemy.
   ``It hasn't interfered with her playing anyway,'' Bush said.
   Tennis, he indicated, is important to the Bushes.
   He told reporters a story about the girlfriend of his sister's
son who learned that.
   Bush's mother, whom he said was a very good player, asked if the
young woman could play tennis and was told she could.
   ``A few days later, Mother watched, and said, `Well, she's a very
nice girl, but she doesn't even play net.'''
   Bush's major lament of the day was that ``the fishing has been
lousy'' in the week that he's been on vacation.
   ``I've fished every single day and haven't got one.''
   When told that an 18-pound bluefish was caught from the ABC-TV
camera boat tht was following his speed boat one day, Bush was
obviously envious.
   ``Eighteen pound bluefish?'' he repeated several times. ``Out
there with us? There's no justice here. That's just not fair.''
</TEXT>
