<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans     08-23 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newly Merged Lutherans Meet for First National Assembly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly merged denomination, the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, headed into its first
national assembly Wednesday seeking a sense of family.
   It also faced specific issues, from proposals for getting rid of
investments in companies doing business in South Africa to
ecumenical relations.
   The 5.3 million-member denomination, formed last year from three
Lutheran groups, is the fourth-largest Protestant body in the
country.
   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, the church's presiding head, said
the convention should provide a greater ``sense of identity'' so
``people will be able to say we belong together in the same family
of faith.''
   ``It's amazing how quickly that spirit is developing,'' he said
in an interview. ``There's very little looking back to what we
were.''
   The assembly is the first occasion for churchwide action on
policy matters since the denomination began functioning at new
headquarters established here.
   About 2,000 Lutherans, including 1,050 voting delegates, were
present for the opening festive service of Holy Communion and a
robed procession of the church's 65 bishops who head regional synods.
   A huge white panel over the podium carries the theme of this
assembly, ``Many Voices, One Song.''
   The preacher for the occasion was the Rev. Emilio Castro, a
Methodist and general secretary of the World Council of Churches.
   Whether the new denomination should join that council of most
major Protestant and Orthodox denominations, and a similarly
constituted domestic body, the National Council of Churches, was an
issue before the assembly.
   Different stances about it were taken by the predecessor Lutheran
bodies. That, however, is only one of many matters the new church is
to settle as it sets its initial course.
   In a state-of-the-church report, Chilstrom said the early phase
of the church's life has been ``a time of incredible adjustment for
all of us.''
   ``Demands of getting ourselves organized were so great that we
found ourselves reacting more often than acting,'' he said.
   But ``we are now nearing the end of this early transition
period,'' he said, and it's up to the assembly to make ``decisions
that will determine the direction of the church for the years to
come.''
   The denomination was created through merger of the Lutheran
Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and the Association
of Evangelical Lutheran Churches, the first two themselves products
of earlier mergers.
   Lutherans in this country once were divided into more than a
score of different denominations, mainly distinguished by the German
or Scandinavian nationalities from which they stemmed.
   The new body has set a goal of becoming at least 10 percent
ethnic minority members by the end of its first decade.
   The eight-day convention runs through next Wednesday, with
financial matters a worrisome concern, including a $15.8 million
shortfall in anticipated revenues last year for a $99.3 million
national budget. Altogether, members contributed $1.1 billion last
year, most of it used for congregational expenses and local
charities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
