<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Anderson     08-23 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Anderson,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Associated Press Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleland ``Andy'' Anderson, a newsman and editor
for The Associated Press for 34 years, died Monday at Bethesda North
Hospital. He was 81.
   Born in Ostrander, Ohio, Anderson earned a bachelor's degree in
journalism at Ohio State University. In the 1930s, he worked for the
Ohio State Journal and Ohio Legion News, both in Columbus; the
Toledo News-Bee, and The Washington Post.
   Anderson joined the AP in 1938 in Huntington, W.Va., and
transferred to Baltimore in 1940.
   In 1944, he transferred to New York, where he worked in the AP
Newsfeatures department and later on the main national news desk. He
retired in 1972.
   Anderson is survived by a son, Richard H. Anderson, of Stamford,
Conn.; a daughter, Margaret Surridge, of Loveland, Ohio; a sister,
Enid Coleman, of New York state; and two grandchildren.
   Visitation was Wednesday night at the Gilligan Funeral Home in
Cincinnati. Burial was scheduled for Thursday in Fairview Cemetery
in Ostrander.
