<FIRST>r w AM-FederalPay 1stLd-Writethru a0620 08-23 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Federal Pay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Pay Still Lags Behind Private Sector</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: RECASTS top 3 grafs to show commission proposed 10 percent pay
raise and CORRECTS that 28.6 percent gap figure was originally cited by
President's Pay Agent; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng, Duggan said xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Advisory Committee on Federal Pay says
government workers should be given a pay increase of 10 percent next
year to help narrow the gap between their salaries and those paid to
counterparts in the private sector.
   ``The bottom line on federal pay is that the gap has become a
canyon,'' said Martin L. Duggan, the committee's chairman, in
releasing its latest annual report.
   He pointed to figures issued two weeks ago by the President's Pay
Agent _ an interagency group involving officials of the Labor
Department, Office of Personnel Management and Office of Management
and Budget _ showing that the pay gap has now grown to 28.6 percent.
   Duggan said that ``we commend the president and Congress for
granting a 3.6 percent increase to become effective in January 1990,
but the committee believes that an additional 6.4 percent is
needed.''
   ``This would send a strong and clear message to young people, who
would not consider a public service career, that the government is
serious about recruiting well-qualified people,'' he said in issuing
the report Tuesday.
   Duggan added that ``the absence of adequate pay increases over
the past decade is driving out the capable people who are already in
the federal government.''
   In addition to the pay raise recommendation, the panel's report
calls for phasing in further increases to remove the pay gap over a
four-year period; reforming the pay system by making salaries more
responsive to labor market conditions; redesigning the health care
benefit program to provide more cost-efficient coverage; and
updating the government's benefits package to better compete for
skills in the labor market.
   Carol A. Bonosaro, president of the Senior Executives
Association, representing top career federal executives, called the
advisory committee's report ``right on target'' in urging the pay
increase.
   She noted that the pay gap tends to be greater at upper levels of
government service, with GS-15s falling 36.7 percent behind their
private sector counterparts.
   ``This is even more strong evidence that senior federal
executives above that level are grossly undercompensated,'' Ms.
Bonosaro said.
   John N. Sturdivant, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, AFL-CIO, commented that ``as a result of the
continued imposition of pay caps, beginning in 1978, the federal
government has found itself in an untenable position, with inferior,
non-competitive salaries in a nationally tight labor market.''
   ``Failure to begin to remedy the current pay gap will virtually
ensure that the nation's largest employer will remain the employer
of last resort,'' Sturdivant said.
   AFGE is the largest union for government workers, representing
700,000 federal employees in the United States and overseas.
</TEXT>
