<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BlindJustice     08-23 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blind Justice,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Education Department Rules Music School Discriminated Against
Blind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until this year, blind students who enrolled at one
of the nation's largest independent music schools were told that no
matter what their academic record, they could never graduate.
   Berklee College of Music required students to learn to sight-read
sheet music, making it impossible for the 2,900-student
undergraduate school's few blind students to get a degree.
   The U.S. Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights
recently ruled that Berklee discriminated against the blind, giving
blind students a chance to get a diploma from the school as well as
an education.
   ``This means something to all blind people, not just the
musically inclined,'' Kenneth Jernigan, executive director of the
50,000-member National Federation for the Blind in Baltimore, said
Wednesday. ``Every time a chip of prejudice is cut away, it helps.''
   Officials at the 44-year-old downtown Boston school have
struggled with the issue for years, said its dean, Lawrence Bethune.
   The sight-reading requirement is tailored to Berklee's reputation
for training students to be able to undertake any musical
assignment, Bethune said. Other schools, such as Juilliard in New
York, train students in a more classical mode, he said.
   Berklee is almost like a trade school, Bethune said. ``The
hardest thing is to teach people to be able to function as a
musician, to make a living from music, for 30 years. At Juilliard,
if you learn the oboe part for Beethoven's Fifth, it's never going
to change. It'll always be the same piece of music.''
   Students with a Berklee degree should be able to walk in any
studio ``and lay down a guitar track with Madonna or play a cut with
Tony Bennett'' and be capable of improvising from whatever sheet
music is used, he said.
   Jernigan disagreed: ``The problem is that sight reading is not
totally relevant to playing music. ... I guess it means that Berklee
wouldn't let Stevie Wonder in.''
   Bethune said no more than a few blind students have studied at
Berklee in his 20 years there.
   The case began two years ago when a visually impaired woman
decided to apply to Berklee and was told she would not graduate. Her
mother filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights.
   The office ruled against the school June 29, concluding that
qualified blind students should not be held back based on their
inability to perform a single test.
   The woman, who has not been identified, did not attend Berklee,
and has not reapplied, Bethune said.
   A Berklee curriculum committee had been looking at the core
requirements before the ruling, and had decided to change the sight
reading requirement irrespective of the discrimination case, Bethune
said.
   The ruling was non-binding, but would have put the issue in court
had Berklee not acted.
   Neither Bethune, Jernigan or officials at the Office of Civil
Rights said they knew of a sight-reading policy such as Berklee's.
   The 800-student Juilliard School modifies its requirements for
visually impaired students, said Assistant Dean Karen Wagner. ``They
certainly haven't been held up for graduation because they couldn't
see,''she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
