<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--OldMurder     08-23 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Old Murder,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Begins in 22-Year-Old Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital supervisor went on trial Wednesday in the
slaying 22 years ago of a 76-year-old woman who lived alone.
   Bob Reilly, head of the orthopedic services department at Baptist
Hospital, was arrested in 1987 when Metro-Dade police assigned to a
``cold-case'' squad came up with evidence implicating him.
   Robert Ball Jr., a salesman from Las Vegas, told investigators
that Reilly and a man now believed to be dead beat, bound and gagged
Josephine Barnhill, 76, on March 29, 1967. She died later.
   ``They needed money,'' Ball testified Tuesday. ``They wanted a
score, that is, to rob somebody.''
   Ball pleaded guilty to manslaughter as the getaway driver. His
sentence will hinge on his testimony at Reilly's trial.
   Reilly, who is charged with first-degree murder, spent seven
years in prison for robbery. He was paroled in 1973 and became a
model citizen.
   Sixty-three friends and co-workers filled a courtroom to urge his
release after his arrest at work, and supporters recalled how he
broke up a knife fight at the hospital.
</TEXT>
