<FIRST>r i AM-Menem-LatinDebt     08-23 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Menem-Latin Debt,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Leader Says Debt Endangers Latin Stability and Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem of Argentine told
a joint session of Brazil's Congress on Wednesday that Latin
America's $400 billion foreign debt puts the region's political
stability in serious danger.
   He urged Latin countries to unite to ``acquire a new voice in the
world.''
   ``There aren't many options,'' he said. ``Either we work out a
joint strategy in line with our development needs, or we will be the
objects of outside stragtegies.''
   Menem is in Brazil on his first major foreign trip since taking
office in July. He arrived Tuesday for talks with President Jose
Sarney of Brazil and Uruguay's President Julio Maria Sanguinetti in
Uruguaiana, a city on the border with Argentina.
   Brazil and Argentina both have civilian administrations that
replaced military dictatorships and both are battling runaway
inflation.
   They have the developing world's first and third-largest foreign
debts, respectively. Brazil's is $112 billion and Argentina's is $56
billion. Mexico is in between them with more than $100 billion.
   ``Democratic Argentina realizes the necessity of continuing the
process of integration with its neighbors and strengthening Latin
American unity,'' Menem said.
   He added that it was time for Latin nations to decide whether to
seek ``a reasonable voice'' on the world stage or ``to continue
living inside the old provincial molds.''
   Menem maintained that a path of regional integration, following a
model started by Brazil and Argentina in 1985, could lead to a more
efficient and equitable role for Latin America in the world economy.
   Since lowering certain customs duties and eliminating some trade
restrictions, Brazil and Argentina, have doubled their mutual
imports and exports, to $1.7 billion. The two countries have
encouraged their small Uruguay to join them in a common market.
</TEXT>
