<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WhalingStation     08-23 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whaling Station,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Last U.S. Whaling Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire destroyed the remains of the last
whaling station in the United States.
   The fire at the abandoned wooden warehouse on pilings at Point
San Pablo, 10 miles inside San Francisco Bay, began Tuesday night.
   ``It's gone to the waterline,'' Richmond Fire Battalion Chief
James Fajardo said Wednesday.
   The Del Monte Fishing Co. opened a whaling business in the
building in the 1950s. In 1971, prodded by ecologists, the federal
government silenced the harpoon cannons of Del Monte's three
103-foot vessels, by then the last American whaling ships.
   The brand name of Del Monte's principal product, used mainly for
poultry and cattle feed, was ``Moby Dick 100 Percent Whale Meat.''
Its logo was a blowing, grinning whale.
   The business stuck in the craw of whale lovers who protested the
suffering and decimation of the herds of sperms, finbacks and seis
Del Monte hunted.
   Del Monte killed 109 of the 21,500 whales taken worldwide in
1969, the company's last manager, Charles Caito, said when the
station closed.
   In the 1840s, the U.S. whaling fleet numbered 750 vessels. It was
a multi-million dollar industry, providing oil fuel for lighting and
cooking in tens of thousands of American homes and inspiring stories
of great courage, like Herman Melville's classic 1851 novel, ``Moby
Dick.''
   The surging petroleum industry and the sinking of many whaling
ships by Confederate warships during the Civil War sent whaling into
a decline. After the war, only 260 whalers were left, and by the
turn of the century, the number had dwindled to 40.
   American whaling ended in 1971 when U.S. Commerce Secretary
Maurice Stans issued a ban aimed at preserving threatened species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
