<FIRST>r a AM-WaitingFood     08-23 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waiting Food,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tons of Food Awaits Distribution to Hungry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a million pounds of food for the
hungry is stacked 18 feet high in a warehouse, its distribution to
outlying parts of the state delayed for lack of money, transport
vehicles and volunteer help, some state officials say.
   ``We've gotten the people to give us the food _ the problem is we
don't have the means to get it to the people who need it, and there
are people starving out there,'' said state Rep. Alyce Clarke of
Jackson, a board member of the state-run Mississippi Food Network.
   The stored food, donated by the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
includes dried beans, instant potatoes, canned pork and citrus
juices. Perishables including dairy products and frozen meats have
been delivered before spoiling.
   Network board members say the agency lacks large transport
vehicles and enough drivers to deliver the food more than 150 miles
to poor counties in the Mississippi Delta and far northern parts of
the state.
   ``We can't get the food to Tunica County and Tishomingo County
where people need it,'' said Jo Ann Gilder Alford, the food bank's
director of development and public relations.
   But the food bank's executive director, Jesse Morris, disagreed
with other assessments of the agency's problem.
   He said USDA food is going on schedule to the network's 150
member agencies, which buy the food for 12 cents a pound, but
distribution would be made easier if the food bank had another
warehouse in northern Mississippi.
   ``The food is going out,'' Morris said. ``The problem is we need
a building'' in north Mississippi.
   This year the network distributed 1.5 million pounds of food, or
about 2.5 million meals.
   But because the agency does not have space in its warehouses for
the surplus food, it has leased private storage at a cost of $1,800
a month.
   The burden on the network is increased because many of its member
agencies lack vehicles and manpower to pick up the food in Jackson,
board members said.
   ``We're trying to open a branch in north Mississippi so we can
better serve the state,'' said board member Rims Barber of Jackson.
   ``This food all came in in a rush and we are trying to get it out
in an orderly manner,'' Barber said. ``The food is going out (to
member agencies), but it is going out slower than we would like it
to.''
</TEXT>
