<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Pact     08-23 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Pact,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Protest Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity and Communist lawmakers on
Wednesday condemned as ``shameful'' the Soviet-German non-aggression
pact signed 50 years ago that opened the way for World War II.
   Legislators passed the resolution 349-0 in the Sejm, or lower
house of parliament, as several hundred protesters marched through
the streets of Warsaw and three other cities to mark the anniversary
of the Ribbentrop-Molotov pact.
   ``The pact was not only shameful from the moral point of view but
also in violation of the basic principles of international law and
thus from the very beginning null and void,'' said the resolution,
introduced by Solidarity lawmakers who comprise 35 percent of the
chamber.
   Solidarity Deputy Janusz Onyszkiewicz, who introduced the
resolution, said the Aug. 23, 1939 pact opened the way for Hitler to
attack Poland just eight days later.
   ``All people in Poland know that this pact made it possible and
helped Hitler to carry out his various political plans,'' said
Onyszkiewicz. ``In particular, it made it easier for him to invade
Poland.
   ``It also made it easier for Stalin to carry out his aspirations
toward various European countries, let me name here only Lithuania,
Latvia and Estonia.''
   In a reference to the Soviet Union, which for many years denied
the key secret provisions of the Molotov-Ribbentrop pact,
Onyszkiewicz said Poland wants relations with its neighbors to be
``based on respect ... And based on truth.''
   ``This is the purpose the statement is supposed to serve,'' he
said.
   At the protest march in central Warsaw, meanwhile, a speaker from
Youth Solidarity called for the withdrawal of all Soviet troops from
Eastern Europe, a declaration of independence by states swallowed by
the Soviet Union and independence for the different ethnic groups in
that country.
   The state news agency PAP said there were also demonstrations in
northern Szczecin, western Pozanan and southern Katowice.
   Youths threw coins and firebombs at police and placed anti-Soviet
slogans at a Soviet monument in Szczecin, the agency said.
   Demonstrators in Warsaw, held up banners saying ``Soviets Go
Home,'' ``Enough of Pacts with Reds.''
   Police stood at a distance watching the Warsaw protest, held at
Constitution Square, on the anniversary of the treaty that resulted
in loss of sovereignty for the three Baltic republics of Estonia,
Latvia and Lithuania.
   Among the groups present at the demonstration were ``Youth
Solidarity,'' ``Fighting Solidarity,'' a splinter faction of the
trade union, and the banned Polish Socialist Party.
   The treaty by Soviet Foreign Minister Vyacheslav Molotov and
German Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop contained a secret
protocol that set a friendly border running through what was then
the Polish Republic.
   On Monday, the Polish Communist Party Politburo condemned the
protocol, saying it represented a ``flagrant violation'' of
international law.
   Last week, a Soviet Communist Party Politburo member admitted for
the first time the secret pact existed, but he denied that the it
bearing on the Baltic states' current legal status.
</TEXT>
