<HEAD>French Ships Bound for East Mediterranean</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the six naval vessels that France
has ordered to the eastern Mediterranean because of the situation in
Lebanon, incorporating modifications announced Wednesday night by
Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement that trim the original
planned flotilla by two ships:
   1. Aircraft carrier Foch with almost 2,000 marines aboard, left
Toulon on Saturday and now in eastern Mediterranean.
   2. Anti-aircraft destroyer Cassard, left Toulon Saturday, to
replace the destroyer Duquesne.
   3. Oil supply ship the Meuse, left Toulon Tuesday and arriving in
zone about Saturday to replace the oil supply ship Var.
   4. Amphibious landing craft Orage, left Brest on Saturday and
expected in zone this Saturday or Sunday.
   5. Anti-submarine destroyer Jean de Vienne, left Toulon on Aug.
17, last Thursday, and reportedly in Larnaca, Cyprus, on Wednesday.
   6. Frigate Estienne d'Orves to be ``pulled back,'' but apparently
to remain within parameters of the zone.
