<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FernaldSettlement     08-23 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernald Settlement,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Question Over Future Cleanup Arises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's $73 million settlement with
neighbors of the Fernald uranium processing plant snagged Wednesday
in a disagreement over whether the terms would prevent future
lawsuits involving cleanup costs.
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel will decide whether to
approve the settlement.
   The judge described the Energy Department's position as
``inconsistent,'' and said he wanted to hear from Energy Secretary
James Watkins. ``At that time, we'll find out just what's going
on,'' Spiegel said.
   Spiegel suggested he could question Watkins next week.
   The snag surfaced after lawyers for both sides urged Spiegel to
approve the settlement, which would end a class-action lawsuit filed
on behalf of 14,000 residents near the Feed Materials Production
Center, which is owned by the Energy Department.
   The residents contended they suffered emotional distress and that
property values were diminished by radioactive pollution from the
plant, about 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   The two sides agreed to the settlement after a jury in a mock
trial found in favor of the residents.
   The government agreed last month to give the residents $73
million, and perhaps $5 million more, to cover costs of regular
medical testing and a medical study for residents, their emotional
distress and depressed land values.
   Only one resident objected to the settlement as inadequate, but
three businesses complained it would unfairly prohibit them from
seeking money from the government to clean their property of any
contamination from the plant that may be uncovered later.
   That resulted in a disagreement between government lawyer Henry
Gill Jr. and Stanley Chesley, representing the residents, over
whether the settlement bars such future claims.
   Chesley contended the companies wouldn't be prohibited from
trying to get the government to pay costs from future cleanup. Gill
disagreed.
   He said the Energy Department believes any such costs should be
paid from the $73 million settlement. But Spiegel noted that the
Energy Department has estimated it could take $5 billion to clean up
the plant site alone.
   ``I have a difficult time understanding your position,'' Spiegel
said.
   The judge can either approve the settlement, reject it or send
both sides back to renegotiate. Spiegel also could clarify the
language of the settlement.
   Chesley said during a break in the hearing that he doesn't think
the disagreement will cause the settlement to unravel.
</TEXT>
