<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     08-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two People's Front Members Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the Azerbaijani People's Front,
which has been organizing mass meetings and strikes against local
authorities, were arrested Wednesday in the Azerbaijani capital of
Baku, an independent journalist said.
   Nazim Ragimov said by telephone from Baku that one of those
arrested was Umudov Dzhambakhaesh, one of nine members of the
grass-roots organization's governing board.
   Dzhambakhaesh was arrested when he went to offices of the
Interior Ministry to investigate the arrest earlier Wednesday of a
People's Front activist who was detained by police while hanging
posters announcing a local meeting of the group, Ragimov said.
   He said he did not have the name of the second activist.
   Workers in Baku struck at least 25 enterprises Monday and Tuesday
to press for control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region and other
demands.
   The Tass news agency reported Wednesday the strike ended with a
rally by 100,000 people in Baku on Tuesday night. Ragimov said the
Tass estimate of the number of participants was several times too
low.
   The rally decided to begin a strike throughout the southern
capital on Sept. 3 to renew its demands, Ragimov said.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has been the scene of ethnic clashes between
mainly Christian Armenians and mainly Moslem Azerbaijanis. It is in
Azerbaijan, but its population is mainly Armenian and the
neighboring republic of Armenia has claimed the enclave be annexed
to it.
