<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Bolivia     08-23 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Bolivia,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Officials Concerned Colombian Drug Barons Heading To Bolivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has reinforced border
patrols to head off Colombian drug runners who may be fleeing to
Bolivia to escape Colombia's offensive against drugs, police said
Wednesday.
   Police helicopters were placed on alert and additional guards
were sent to Bolivia's northern border with Brazil, police said.
   Gonzalo Torrico, the official responsible for drug interdiction,
said the government was concerned Colombia's war against cocaine
will ``generate a stampede of traffickers looking for refuge in
areas they have contacts.''
   There are dozens of cocaine processing labs in northern Bolivia's
Beni jungle region. From there, cocaine is flown to Colombia then
distributed to the United States or Europe.
   This impoverished nation of 7 million people produces the raw
material for at least one-third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. and
European markets, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration said.
   ``The violence and corruption that exists in Colombia could be
transferred to Bolivia, especially because of the offensive by the
Colombian government,'' said Bolivia Sen. Daniel Cabezas, head of
the Senate committee on drugs.
   In June, two Colombian drug traffickers were captured when police
raided the town of Santa Ana de Yacuma, home to some of Bolivia's
top cocaine traffickers. There have been several killings in Santa
Cruz, 450 miles east of La Paz, involving Colombian drug runners,
police have said.
   ``Our problem in controlling the flow of traffickers from
Colombia is that we do not have the resources to control our air
space,'' Cabezas said.
   Police said the border patrols were reinforced and police
helicopters placed on alert.
   At least 350,000 Bolivians make their livings growing coca
leaves. The leaves are processed into cocaine paste, which is
refined into cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
