<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0637 08-23 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Reported Killed by Rockets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. senator supporting guerrillas,
guerrillas rejecting peace plan. Pickup 4th pvs, `Amani blamed ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas fired 150 rockets at
Charikar, north of Kabul, and seven into the capital, killing 17
civilians and wounding 23, the government said Wednesday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani also said the
second cluster-bomb rocket to hit Kabul landed on a street where
children were playing Saturday, killing seven and wounding five.
Amani said the United States supplies cluster rockets to the
guerrillas.
   Washington refuses to say what type of weapons it supplies to the
guerrillas, but the chairman of the U.S. Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on Wednesday suggested they may arm them with even more
sophisticated supplies.
   ``I'm a little leary of raising the military ante by giving them
tanks and bombs, but we may come to that if there's no other
solution,'' Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., told a news conference
Wednesday in Islamabad, Pakistan.
   He said Washington's support should continue despite longstanding
antagonisms between the guerrilla groups that flared into fighting
in the field this week.
   ``I think the `interim' government (of guerrillas in exile) is
the best alternative at this time,'' said Pell.
   Also in Islamabad on Wednesday, guerrilla leaders rejected a
peace plan from Afghan President Najib, reiterating that they will
not stop fighting until the Marxist leader steps down.
   Najibullah Lefraye, spokesman for the guerrillas'
government-in-exile, said Najib's proposal is ``a collection of
bankrupt ideas that have been rejected.''
   Najib had offered to call elections within six months of an
immediate cease-fire.
   In Kabul, Amani said Tuesday's rocketing of Charikar, a small
city 38 miles north of the capital on the Salang Highway to the
Soviet Union, was the most intense of the 11-year-old civil war. He
said seven people were killed and 14 wounded.
   Amani blamed the fundamentalist guerrilla group Hezb-i-Islami led
by Gulbuddin Hekmatyar for the attack on Charikar, which has been
the scene of intermittent fighting in recent months. Hekmatyar's
group is the largest recipient of U.S. military aid.
   He said the seven rockets hit Kabul on Wednesday, killing 10
people and wounding nine, mostly women and children in residential
areas.
   Kabul has been rocketed almost daily since late June. U.N.
sources say 335 people were killed and more than 900 wounded by
rockets and a car bombing from June 25 to Aug. 12, nearly all of
them civilians.
   Guerrillas have claimed responsibility for some of the rockets,
but say they aim at military targets. They have accused the
government of firing rockets at civilian targets, but government
officials deny it.
   Cluster rockets explode in the air, scattering up to 30 bombs.
The government said the first cluster rocket hit Kabul on Aug. 15,
killing five civilians and wounding 23 in a housing complex near the
airport.
   Amani said the second, on Saturday, landed in the Cala-i-Shada
area of southwest Kabul.
</TEXT>
