<FIRST>u i AM-DrugSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0611 08-23 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuelan President Proposes Drug Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th pvs, `Venezuelan press...' to UPDATE
with more border patrols in Bolivia; Pickup 6th, `Perez said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Andres Perez has
proposed that nations of the Western Hemisphere hold a summit to
define strategies to combat drug trafficking.
   Venezuela on Wednesday also increased its forces on the Colombian
border to seal off escape routes during a Colombian military sweep
against the drug cartels.
   ``Narcotics trafficking has to be fought as the most abominable
crime of the century,'' said Perez, speaking at an anniversary
celebration of a cooperative educational institute late Tuesday.
   Perez said narcotics dealing would have to be considered a crime
``without frontiers'' in order to combat it effectively.
   Venezuelan press accounts have warned of a possible wave of drug
smugglers and their families sweeping into Venezuela to escape the
recent crackdown in Colombia.
   In Bolivia, authorities said patrols along that country's border
with Brazil were also reinforced and police helicopters were placed
on alert against Colombian traffickers.
   Perez said Venezuela had tightened patrols along its 1,000 mile
border with Colombia, traditionally an area plagued with smuggling
and guerrilla activity.
   Warning that the scourge of violence in Colombia could also take
place in Venezuela, Perez said: ``We are collaborating with the
Colombian armed forces so that Venezuela does not become a haven for
those people that are causing so much damage in Latin America.''
   The cooperation was limited to ``necessary custody of the border
area and offering our solidarity,'' Perez said.
   Venezuela does not have a history of drug trafficking, although
it is being increasingly used as a transfer point for cocaine and
other drugs being smuggled to Europe and the United States as the
cartels seek to diversify their routes, according to police.
</TEXT>
