<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     08-23 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Yells Obscenity at Judge, is Hauled Out of Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drifter charged with 13 ``Night Stalker''
murders shouted out that his trial is a ``joke'' and called the
judge an obscenity as deputies hauled him to his feet and took him
out of court Wednesday.
   The outburst came during a hearing from which defendant Richard
Ramirez had asked through his attorney to be excluded. The judge
insisted he appear.
   ``Hey, I don't want to be here. Don't you understand, man? What's
the problem?'' Ramirez, 29, shouted from his chair as Superior Court
Judge Michael Tynan tried to proceed.
   ``I won't come back in here _ you understand that?'' Ramirez
continued as two sheriff's deputies approached him, each taking an
arm and lifting him to his feet. ``This trial is a joke,'' he
exclaimed, then used obscenities as he was led out to a holding cell.
   Tynan had told Ramirez's lawyers that he believes the defendant
``is a grown man'' and should be present for proceedings.
   ``If he wants to act like a jerk, we can deal with it at that
time. We can restrain him,'' the judge said before Ramirez came into
court.
   Jurors, deliberating the charges, were unaware of the disruption.
   The defense has filed a motion to question jurors about the
impact on their deliberations of a colleague's slaying last week.
The panel resumed talks Aug. 16 with an alternate. Tynan scheduled a
hearing on the motion Aug. 31. The defense suggested that the motion
was tantamount to seeking a mistrial, but the prosecutor said he did
not interpret it that way.
   Ramirez is charged with 13 murders and 30 felonies stemming from
a killing spree that terrorized Southern California in 1985.
   After Ramirez's courtroom outburst, Tynan met with lawyers, then
summoned Ramirez back to court and said he had been informed by
defense attorneys that the defendant would cause further
disruptions, or ``a physical altercation,'' if he was forced to come
to court for the motions hearing next week.
   ``In light of that, the court finds good cause that you should be
absent when a hearing is held on these motions,'' Tynan said. He
asked Ramirez if he understood his right to be present and if he was
willing to waive it.
   ``Yes,'' he answered in a husky voice.
   The judge said he would be held in a lockup room near the
courtroom, listening to arguments over a loudspeaker.
   Should the jury return with its verdicts, Ramirez would be
required to be present. A verdict before Aug. 31 would make the
scheduled hearing moot.
   Outside court, defense attorney Ray Clark said Ramirez ``has good
days and bad days.''
   ``He just doesn't like court,'' said Clark.
   Meanwhile, Tynan announced he was leaving town until Monday on a
vacation scheduled to celebrate his wedding anniversary. He said any
questions that might arise from jurors would be handled Monday and
``anything extraordinary'' would be taken up by another judge. He
did not address the possibility that a verdict could be returned
while he is away.
</TEXT>
