<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0621 08-23 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Hungarians Freed, 43 Foreigners Still Held in Prague Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with seven Hungarians released, detailing
plight of other foreigners. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Hungarians were released
Wednesday, state media said, but still held were 43 other foreigners
accused of fomenting anti-government protests on the 21st
anniversary of the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   The media said the Foreign Ministry on Wednesday protested the
foreigners' participation in the unrest.
   No official word emerged about the 320 Czechoslovaks reported
detained during Monday's protests.
   The official Hungarian news agency MTI has reported that Polish,
Dutch, Bulgarian, Italian, East and West Germans and Yugoslavs also
were detained.
   MTI said seven of nine Hungarians in custody were let go
Wednesday after ``repeated intervention'' by the Hungarian Embassy
and left Prague for home on a charter flight of the Hungarian state
airlines, Malev.
   It said two activists of a Hungarian youth group still were held
on charges of a grave breach of public order.
   Prague authorites decided to extend indefinitely the detention of
eight Italians, the Italian news agency ANSA said. It speculated
they could be expelled, possibly by Friday.
   Italy's Foreign Ministry summmoned Czechoslovakia's charge
d'affairs for a second time Wednesday to protest the continued
detention of Italian citizens.
   Czechoslovakia's official news agency, CTK, said the Foreign
Ministry summoned representatives of the Hungarian, Polish, Italian
and Dutch embassies and lodged a protest, complaining that their
citizens participated in the protests.
   At least three Poles were said to be among those held in Monday's
demonstration, which began when Hungarian activists unfurled a
banner and addressed a crowd of cheering Czechoslovaks calling for
more freedom.
   Poland's state news agency PAP says no proof exists that Poles
took part in the protests.
   The demonstration marked the anniversary of the 1968 invasion,
led by the Soviet Union and joined by all Warsaw Pact nations except
Romania to crush reforms then under way in Czechoslovakia.
   It took hours Monday before hundreds of helmeted riot police
wielding truncheons broke up crowds of at least 3,000 people calling
for freedom and withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   State media blamed foreign provocateurs, saying they came posing
as tourists.
   The Foreign Ministry reportedly told the diplomats the detained
foreigners had violated the law and their cases would be
investigated accordingly.
   MTI identified the released Hungarians as three cameramen who
tried to film the demonstration, two photo journalists for
independent publications and two youth activists.
   According to MTI, they had to pay fines ranging from $30 to $50
each.
   A statement issued jointly by the independent Czechoslovak human
rights group Charter 77 and the Hungarian opposition group League of
Free Democrats on the quelling of the protests, said despite the
police action, the ``system of repression is wavering in
Czechoslovakia.''
   The statement, referring to the 1968 ``Prague Spring'' reforms
crushed by the invasion, defined Prague as ``the capital of hope''
21 years ago and noted that similar democratic reforms now are under
way in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary.
   ``Today the world looks upon Warsaw, Moscow and Budapest
wondering if this bloody and stupid adventure called communism will
end at long last,'' it added.
   Referring to Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Romania _ the three
countries in the Soviet bloc most resistant to reform _ the
statement said: ``We trust that democracy will cross frontiers and
that the days of the dictatorship are numbered in Prague, Berlin
(and) Bucharest.''
</TEXT>
