<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NewtonKilled     08-23 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newton Killed,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newton Described as Lonely, Prepared for Violent Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends of Huey P. Newton, the
slain co-founder of the Black Panther Party, portrayed him Wednesday
as a lonely man who'd been prepared for years to meet a violent
death.
   ``He felt that once he decided to be a revolutionary, he was in a
position of suicide anyway,'' Newton's older brother, Melvin, said
at a news conference at his home.
   Newton's bullet-riddled body was found before dawn Tuesday in the
same poor west Oakland neighborhood where he began organizing blacks
more than 20 years ago, several miles from his present home.
   Police had no suspects and no motive in the slaying, but said
neighborhood residents were offering help. ``Just about everyone
we've talked to has been very cooperative,'' said Lt. Mike Sims.
   About 200 mourners marched during a candlelight vigil Tuesday
night at the place where Newton, 47, was found, chanting cheering
and holding their fists high in the black-power salute.
   The neighborhood has been plagued by drug-dealing gangs, but
authorities have said they had no reason to believe Newton's slaying
was drug-related.
   Panther leader Eldridge Cleaver's former wife, Kathleen Cleaver,
said in an interview in New York that while Newton was clearly very
intelligent, ``he also was a very troubled person who was not able
to overcome his problems with drugs and alcohol.''
   The Los Angeles Times said he had a history of cocaine abuse, and
had been sentenced earlier this year to 90 days for possession of
drug paraphernalia, a violation of his parole.
   The San Jose Mercury News said that Newton was in Oakland
Municipal Court last week to enter a treatement program resulting
from a drunken driving charge.
   Newton's brother declined to comment on the reports and Huey
Newton's wife, Fredrika, denied her husband used cocaine.
   A coroner's report was completed Tuesday, but authorities refused
to release preliminary findings. Results of drug and alcohol tests
will not be available for two weeks, said Lt. John Dealy.
   Mrs. Newton said she had been prepared for years for Newton to
die violently, and said she recently had a premonition he might die
soon. ``Huey was talking about getting insurance just last week,''
she said.
   Mrs. Newton said the couple was having financial problems and
that Newton had been recovering from two recent abdominal operations.
   She and Melvin Newton said they were unaware of any other
problems plaguing Newton, and refused to speculate about what he was
doing in the neighborhood early Tuesday.
   With Bobby Seale, Newton founded the Black Panther Party. Armed
Panther members followed police cars to monitor their activities in
the black community.
   Under the slogan ``All power to the people,'' the Panthers also
operated a school, a health clinic and programs for ghetto
youngsters.
   The party drifted into violence and gradually disintegrated, as
members were killed and the FBI infiltrated and disrupted the
organization.
   ``As a spokesperson for disillusioned and often bitter youth in
the 1960s, Huey Newton spoke eloquently of their rage and
impatience. He succeeded, in his own way, in calling attention to
the many glaring imperfections in an imperfect society. We were
often in disagreement with his views and strategies, but one had to
admire his courage and persistence,'' said NAACP Executive Director
Benjamin L. Hooks.
   Newton was a frustrated man who longed for the excitement of the
1960s, said former Panther leader David Hilliard.
   ``He was certainly a lonely man in that we didn't have any more
fights, any more struggles,'' said Hilliard. ``We talked a lot about
loneliness and our desire to recreate the energy of the '60s.''
   Melvin Newton said his brother's latest desire was to produce a
film on environmental problems, which he believed were linked to the
racism and classism he'd fought as a Panther leader.
   Mrs. Cleaver, a recent Yale Law School graduate practicing
commercial law, said she saw Newton's slaying and the recent suicide
of Yippie founder Abbie Hoffman as ``epitaphs to the '60s.''
   Eldridge Cleaver was deeply saddened by the death, but was
declining interviews, political aide Susan Thompson said in Berkeley.
   Hilliard said Newton's death had prompted an outcry around the
country, and he urged blacks to organize around the issues that
prompted Newton and Seale to establish the organization.
   ``Let Huey's death move us to some action,'' he said. ``Huey's
spirit and his program can be picked up.''
   Supporters said a memorial fund had been established in Newton's
name to cover funeral costs and to fund community-based programs for
poor children.
   Funeral services were planned for Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
