<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1939EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Amnesty-Peru     08-23 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Peru,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Says Soldiers and Guerrillas Cast ``Pall of Violence'' Over
Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and Maoist guerrillas in Peru have cast a
``pall of violence'' over the country, Amnesty International said
Wednesday, reporting more and more disappearances, torturing and
killings of civilians.
   Peruvian officials in Lima would not comment on the report.
   In seven years, 3,000 prisoners have disappeared while in
government custody and government forces have killed thousands more
in mass executions and assassinations, the London-based human rights
group said in a report.
   Most victims, Amnesty said, are Indian peasants in remote
mountain villages who appear to be killed as punishment for
guerrilla activity.
   Civic leaders, journalists, lawyers and others critical of the
government have been killed, received death threats or had homes and
offices bombed, the report said.
   Many victims were killed soon after being released from short
detentions, or after their homes were searched or military
authorities publicly denounced them as subversives, according to the
report.
   Similar tactics have been used to crush labor unrest, it said.
   Trade unionists have disappeared or been killed, the report said,
and in February an elite police unit fired on striking farmers in
Ucayali. Amnesty said dozens of peasants were killed, but the exact
number was not known because police removed the bodies.
   ``Official statistics put the death toll at 15,000 in the ongoing
conflict and include civilians caught between government and
guerilla violence,'' it said. ``These activities have spread a pall
of violence over much of Peru.''
   Military courts are not known to have convicted any soldiers
implicated in rights abuses and rulings have tended to exonerate the
armed forces, dismiss the charges or prolong proceedings
indefinitely, it said.
   Amnesty said it sent its findings to the Peruvian government in
May but has not received a reply.
   The Associated Press called President Alan Garcia's press office
three times Wednesday and left messages requesting comment on the
report, but no spokesman called back.
   Garcia took office in July 1985 and pledged not to use
``barbarity to fight barbarity.'' One of his first acts was to fire
the commander-in-chief of the armed forces after peasants denounced
a massacre of 69 villagers only weeks after Garcia took office.
   No large-scale killings by army troops were denounced from late
1985 until May 1988, when residents of Cayara village charged that
troops killed 29 villagers in reprisal for a guerrilla ambush of an
army convoy on the village's outskirts.
   The Amnesty report said 11 of some 20 villagers detained in a
jungle village in May 1989 by soldiers were found dead the next day
and four others ``disappeared.''
   Shining Path rebels routinely torture, mutilate and murder
captives, Amnesty said, citing widespread execution-style killings
since 1982.
   In the last several years most of the peasant slaughters
denounced within Peru have been attributed by survivors to the
Maoist guerrilla group, which has intensified its violent campaign
to overthrow the government.
   In the biggest massacre of recent date, Shining Path guerrillas
in late February killed 37 men in a remote mountain village by
cutting their throats and shot to death a mother and her baby when
the woman tried to flee the scene.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
