<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-23 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Indiana, Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Powerful thunderstorms in Indiana and Illinois on Wednesday
spawned flooding, winds that knocked out power to thousands and
lightning that blasted a car on an interstate highway and gouged a
hole in the road.
   Rain-triggered floods in West Virginia closed roads and swamped a
fire house and other buildings.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell in New England, New
York, South Carolina, Georgia and the eastern and central Gulf Coast.
   Showers fell on the northern Rockies and the northern and central
Intermountain region between the Rockies and the Sierra Nevada and
the mountains of eastern Oregon.
   Thunderstorms continued dropping heavy rain on sections of the
Ohio Valley on Wednesday afternoon. A morning storm dropped 1{ inch
of rain in the western Indiana city of Crawfordsville.
   The rain flooded two state highways in Shelby County, Ind.,
southeast of Indianapolis, and homes and streets in Champaign County
in eastern Illinois. A flash-flood watch was in effect for central
Indiana.
   Lightning hit an automobile on Interstate 74 in Montgomery
County, which includes Crawfordsville, but the car's occupants were
not seriously hurt. The strike left a hole 2{ feet wide and 1{ feet
deep.
   Lightning or wind knocked out power to 4,000 homes in Champaign
County, as well as two University of Illinois dormitories in
Champaign-Urbana on the first day of classes. Power was also knocked
out near rural Mayfield, Ky.
   Thunderstorm winds blew down a work shed in the central Illinois
city of Taylorville, and blew down trees south of Coal City in
western Indiana. Nickel-size hail also fell in Coal City.
   In central West Virginia, high water closed roads in Upshur
County and flooded a fire house in Selbyville, a store in Pickens
and homes in Helvetia. Water was 2 feet over a road in Newlon. A
flash-flood watch was in effect in all of West Virginia except the
panhandles.
   The rain in the West was generated by a strong cold front that
was expected to bring snow to higher elevations of western Wyoming.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees in Klamath Falls, Ore., to around 100 degrees in Beeville,
Texas. The low for the lower 48 states Wednesday morning was 33
degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
middle and southern Atlantic Coast to Florida, the eastern and
central Gulf Coast, the Tennessee Valley, the southern half of the
lower Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley; scattered
showers and thunderstorms over the northern High Plains, the
northern and central Rockies, and the region between the mountains
of eastern Oregon and Washington, with strong, gusty winds over the
central Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected in the 90s across much of the
nation, the 60s in northern New England, along the southern shore of
Lake Superior and in the northern Rockies; in the 70s along the
Pacific Coast; in the 70s and 80s from inland northern California to
Nevada and the central and southern Rockies, and from the northern
Plains to the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes, the
Ohio Valley and much of the middle and northern Atlantic Coast; and
between 100 and 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
