<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines     08-23 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Die In Clash To Avenge Massacre Of Churchgoers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-communist vigilantes seeking to
avenge the massacre of 39 Protestant churchgoers clashed Wednesday
with Marxist rebels and 11 people were killed, the government-run
Philippines News Agency reported.
   According to the agency, about 60 members of the anti-communist
``Ituman'' group and soldiers of the army's 46th Infantry Battalion
found a rebel band Wednesday near Baracatan, about 600 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Three vigilantes and eight communist guerrillas were killed, the
agency said Thursday, quoting military sources.
   The Itumans had vowed to avenge the June 25 massacre of 39 people
in the remote mountain village of Rano. The victims, including some
Itumans, were gathered in a United Church of Christ chapel when
rebels entered.
   Communist rebels acknowledged the massacre but claimed Itumans
within the congregation started shooting first. The rebels promised
an investigation of the incident.
   The Itumans are among numerous religious cults armed and
supported by the military to fight Communist rebels.
   Following the massacre, the United Church of Christ condemned the
bloodshed but criticized the armed forces for using churches as
bases of operations in the 20-year-old insurgency.
</TEXT>
