<FIRST>u i AM-Wallenberg     08-23 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wallenberg,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Accepts Soviet Guilt in Wallenberg Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet ambassador to Sweden on
Wednesday acknowedged his nation's guilt in the case of Raoul
Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat missing since his 1945 arrest by
Soviet troops.
   Wallenberg, who would be 77, is credited with saving tens of
thousands of Hungarian Jews from Nazi concentration camps in World
War II.
   The secretary of the Raoul Wallenberg Association, Sonja
Sonnenfeld, called Ambassador Boris Pankin's statement the Soviet's
most explicit public statement about the missing diplomat.
   ``It goes farther than anything they have said before in
accepting guilt,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``It is
remarkable. It must have been dictated by Moscow.''
   Pankin insisted Wallenberg is dead, but Mrs. Sonnenfeld said she
believes the diplomat still is alive.
   Moscow has said Wallenberg died of natural causes in prison in
1947, but Soviet dissidents claim to have seen him alive as late as
1986.
   Pankin did not say why the Soviet Union is guilty and Soviet
authorities never explained why they arrested Wallenberg. Some
historians believe he was mistaken for an American spy.
   
   ``The dead cannot be brought back to life,'' Pankin said in an
article written for the Moscow News and printed in Swedish in the
Expressen daily.
   ``The only thing you can do is to again praise his
accomplishments and express feelings of compassion and guilt to his
people and those closest to him,'' Pankin wrote.
   ``We are ready to do everything to reinstate and strengthen the
growing trust between our countries, to turn the case of the search
for Raoul Wallenberg into a mark of honor for his memory.''
   He denounced Wallenberg's alleged death as an excess of the
Stalin era.
   ``Such is this whole terrible story that the ghastly
pointlessness is typical for that time,'' he wrote.
   The ambassador said it is not surprising many people refuse to
believe Wallenberg is dead, since Soviet authorities initially
denied he was in custody. ``Who believes you if you have lied
before?'' he said.
   Wallenberg issued Swedish travel documents to 20,000 Hungarian
Jews slated for Nazi concentration camps. His intervention with
German authorities was credited with winning survival for another
100,000 Jews from the country's prewar community of 750,000.
   
   He was arrested by Soviet troops who entered Budapest in 1945.
   Earlier this year, Soviet authorities invited four people to
Moscow, including Wallenberg's half-brother and half-sister, to meet
KGB intelligence officers and Foreign Ministry officials. The group
plans to go in October.
   Pankin said they will not be given new information, but will see
the original 1947 document reporting Wallenberg's death, written by
the prison doctor to then State Security Minister Viktor Abakumov.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
