<DOCNO> AP890823-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     08-23 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Decides Former Minister Should Stand Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament voted Wednesday to try a former
socialist minister in a special court for alleged involvement in an
agricultural scandal that defrauded the European Economic Community.
   Lawmakers reached the decision after a two-day stormy debate on
findings of a 12-member parliamentary investigating committee.
   Former Deputy Finance Minister Nikos Athanassopoulos will face
trial before the Supreme Court president and 12 judges.
   The investigating committee presented evidence to the 300-member
parliament that allegedly shows Athanassopoulos was involved in
forging harbor logs and customs invoices.
   The invoices were changed to show that 9,000 tons of Yugoslav
maize sold to the EEC in 1986 were Greek, cheating the European
Community of import duties and making it pay subsidies.
   Athanassopoulos was defeated in his bid for re-election on a
Panhellenic Socialist Movement ticket in June 18 balloting.
   The election ended inconclusively, prompting a
conservative-leftist coalition to pledge to clean up Greek political
life by investigating scandals allegedly involving members of the
former government.
   The alliance of the conservative New Democracy Party and the
Communist-led Coalition of the Left and Progress, pledged to hold
new elections no later than November 5.
   The coalition controls 173 parliamentary seats and the socialists
hold 125 places. The remainder are held by two independents.
   Parliament speaker Athanasis Tsaldaris said lawmakers voted
170-118 to try Athanassopoulos, with five ballots blank, three
declared invalid and four deputies failing to vote.
   Athanassopoulos, who addressed parliament before the vote,
described the charges against him as a ``fairy tale.''
   Parliament is scheduled later this month to debate illegal
wiretapping, financial and arms procurement scandals in which former
Premier Andreas Papandreou and senior members of his Cabinet were
allegedly involved.
   Papandreou has denied any involvement in the $200 million Bank of
Crete scandal and rejected charges that he took kickbacks to procure
French and American built jet fighters for the air force.
   Also Wednesday, the government announced that security files on
Greeks involved in the Communist uprising 40 years ago will be
burned to end a lingering symbol of animosity between rightists and
leftists.
   The files were compiled on people considered a threat to public
security since the 1940s. They will be burned Tuesday, said
government spokesman Athanassios Kanellopoulos.
</TEXT>
