<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BronxParents     08-23 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bronx Parents,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children Reluctant to Talk About Alleged Abuses by Bronx Parents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Contents may be objectionable to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frightened children wouldn't talk about years of
rape, sodomy and beatings allegedly inflicted by their father until
about two weeks after they were taken from their apartment,
authorities said Wednesday.
   At an arraignment, Assistant District Attorney Marie Corliss said
the nine children's treatment by Herman Carlie McMillan and his
wife, Frances, was ``reminiscent of medieval torture.''
   She quoted Mrs. McMillan as saying, ``I have seen my husband
perform sex acts on my oldest female child.''
   The government also said Mrs. McMillan told investigators her
husband had sodomized other children, tied them up and beaten them
with paddle boards.
   McMillan was held without bail, and his wife held in lieu of
$10,500 bail. Both were due back in court Friday.
   In a related development, authorities said McMillan, 42, had
twice escaped from North Carolina prisons, where he was serving time
for a 1967 assault and two charges of breaking and entering.
   After his second escape he spent eight years hiding from the law.
At least part of that time he lived in New York's Bronx borough,
where he was arrested on separate assault charges in 1974.
   Police and social workers on May 25 removed the McMillans' six
boys and three girls, ages 4 months to 16 years, from the cramped
three-room apartment.
   Police arrested the parents Monday night and charged McMillan
with rape, sodomy, assault, incest, reckless endangerment,
endangering the welfare of a minor and sexual abuse.
   Mrs. McMillan, 34, was charged with assault and endangerment. She
had no prior arrest record.
   It was charged that the couple held the children captive for at
least three years in the unlit, unheated apartment where they were
sexually abused, beaten or had their heads held underwater.
   City regulations require that a social worker from either the
city or a voluntary agency interview each child before he or she is
placed in a foster home, and the social workers usually ask the
child about sexual abuse.
   But a spokeswoman for the city's Human Resources Administration,
Suzanne Trazoff, said it usually takes some time before a child
volunteers details of abuse.
   ``Children don't necessarily walk in the door and say `I was
sexually abused,''' she said. ``Information has a way of coming over
time.''
   After his arrest Monday, McMillan told police he had secretly
buried three other children, who had died as infants over the last
five years, apparently of natural causes. Police Wednesday resumed
digging for the bodies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
