<DOCNO> AP890823-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     08-23 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Rationing Ends in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday ended eight
years of gasoline rationing, saying rising prices have curbed demand.
   Gas, once so cheap that trucks and planes from elsewhere in
Central America fueled up in Nicaragua, now sells for $1.86 a gallon.
   Rationing had limited private consumers to 17 gallons a month.
   Energy Minister Emilio Rappaccioli said fuel deliveries to
service stations now will be based on demand, not quotas, reported
Barricada, official newspaper of the ruling Sandinista Party, and
the pro-government El Nuevo Diario.
   Rappaccioli said international missions and the diplomatic corps,
which pay in much-needed hard currency, will still need gasoline
coupons.
   The government began rationing gas by issuing coupons in 1981,
after Nicaragua stopped getting high-quality Venezuelan
reconstituted petroleum. Venezuela stopped deliveries when Nicaragua
stopped paying its bills.
   The high-yield Venezuelan fuel coupled with government subsidies
made for cheap gasoline prices in Nicaragua, leading to fuel
shortages at a time when the leftist government started to fight a
guerrilla war with the U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras.
   Nicaragua gets nearly all its oil from the Soviet Union and its
allies.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge meanwhile announced that the
government will permit Red Cross verification of political prisoners
in Nicaragua.
   The last cross-check by the Red Cross and other international
human rights groups was carried out in 1987.
   Borge told reporters on Tuesday night that 1,440 Contra prisoners
are being held in custody, and that the International Red Cross has
been invited to verify the government figure.
   The country's total prison population is 7,003, including
Contras, former guardsmen of ex-dictator Anastasio Somoza, members
of the military and common criminals, the interior minister said.
   Lino Hernandez, executive secretary of the independent Permanent
Commission on Human Rights, disputed the government figures on
Wednesday.
   He said his organization believed the government is holding at
least 6,000 political prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
