<DOCNO> AP890823-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     08-23 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Election Monitors Off to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. poll watchers leave for Nicaragua this
week to monitor voter registration for national elections, officials
said Wednesday.
   An advance party of up to 10 civilian poll watchers headed by
Iqbal Riza, director of General Assembly Affairs, will open the
headquarters of the U.N. election monitoring mission in Managua on
Friday, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   During Sept. 8-10, the observers will watch voters registering
for the February election, he said.
   The U.N. mission to Nicaragua is the world body's first effort to
monitor election procedures in a sovereign state. The United Nations
frequently has overseen independence referendums in colonies and
territories and currently is monitoring Namibia's independence
elections.
   Under the Central American peace accords, Nicaragua pledged to
hold free and fair national elections on Feb. 25. The Sandinista
government asked for election monitors from the United Nations and
Organization of American States. Opposition parties in Nicaragua
also requested the U.N. election monitors.
   The United States repeatedly has expressed skepticism that the
Sandinistas will permit a fair campaign.
   Officials from the OAS are expected to arrive in Nicaragua in
September, and the U.N. monitors will begin coordinating their
efforts, said Giuliani.
   Nicaragua reformed its constitution and election laws and agreed
to hold national elections for the first time in five years under a
1987 Central American peace plan.
</TEXT>
