<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     08-23 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peasants Reportedly Arrested, Beaten By Soldiers</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers arrested and beat 14
peasants and plundered and burned down their homes in an isolated
village in northern Haiti, radio stations said Wednesday.
   Radio Soleil, owned by the Roman Catholic Church, quoted Francois
Pierre-Louis of the leftist National Popular Assembly party as
saying that 40 soldiers rounded up peasants on the night of Aug. 17
in the hamlet of Champagne, tied them up and beat them.
   The peasants were still jailed Wednesday in nearby Le Borgne, 200
miles from Port-au-Prince, he said, without specifying the charges.
   Other Port-au-Prince radio stations carried the same report. Army
officials in northern Haiti could not be reached for comment
Wednesday.
   Pierre-Louis said the soldiers fell upon the peasants after
failing to find three National Popular Assembly leaders they came to
arrest.
   He told Radio Soleil that Haitian ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril
wants ``to intimidate all members of popular organizations.''
   Several parties and leftist groups have complained about the
army's alleged persecution and illegal arrest of peasants and
radical parish priests in rural Haiti during past months.
   Avril took office in a September coup that ousted Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy. Namphy came to power after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier
fled to exile in France in 1986.
</TEXT>
