<FIRST>r a AM-BARTFraud     08-23 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BART Fraud,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>BART's Former Real Estate Manager Admits Embezzlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former real estate manager of the Bay
Area Rapid Transit District was sentenced to five years in prison
Wednesday after pleading guilty to embezzlement and conspiracy to
defraud the rail system.
   Michael M. Sharpe, 37, of Oakland is the highest-ranking official
charged in a federal investigation of BART. Other charges have been
filed against a half-dozen middle managers and private citizens,
several of whom have admitted paying or collecting kickbacks
   Under U.S. District Judge Fern Smith's sentence, Sharp must repay
the sum he stole, which is yet to be determined. Defense lawyer
Harold Rosenthal estimated it at $125,000, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Ben Burch at $176,000.
   The embezzlement charge covered 17 thefts between March 1986 and
March 1988 in which Sharpe took kickbacks from two contractors and a
building inspector.
   Sharpe also pleaded guilty to conspiring with one of the building
inspectors, David W. Collins, to defraud BART. Collins has pleaded
guilty to the same charge.
   According to the charge, the two men plotted in 1986 to buy a
parcel of land in Oakland for BART at an inflatd price and keep the
extra money.
   Sharpe also pleaded no contest to income tax evasion.
   In a brief statement to the judge, Sharpe said he had been under
emotional and financial stress and was sorry for what he had done.
He is to start his prison sentence Sept. 25.
</TEXT>
