<DOCNO> AP890823-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     08-23 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders Arrested as Striking Workers Rally for Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidents of the AFL-CIO, the United Mine
Workers and other unions demonstrated labor solidarity Wednesday by
participating in a sit-down demonstration and heading off to jail
together.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland and UMW President Richard Trumka
led the group of labor leaders supporting strikes involving
Chesapeake and Potomac Telephone Co., Pittston Coal Group Inc. and
Eastern Airlines.
   The labor leaders faced with common problems _ job losses and
eroding market shares _ attended a rally in Richmond before
traveling to the Russell County Courthouse where a judge has fined
the UMW $7.5 million for violating restrictions on the strike
against Pittston.
   Kirkland, Trumka and 17 others representing a dozen labor unions
locked arms and sat on the steps of the red brick courthouse to
block the entrance.
   At the same time, 1,200 workers joined raised hands under a
slight drizzle and, accompanied by Kirkland on the harmonica, sang
``Solidarity forever ... for the union makes us strong.''
   Trumka gave a thumbs-up sign as he and the others were led away
to the county jail around the corner where they were charged with
obstruction of free passage.
   ``Today gives testimony to the fact that they're never going to
fight us alone again. We're in it together,'' Trumka yelled to the
crowd on the courthouse lawn.
   The officers represented coal miners, machinists, airline pilots,
flight attendants, government employees, communications workers,
service employees, department store workers, electrical workers,
steel workers, firefighters and transport workers.
   The labor leaders were released after posting $500 property
bonds, and drove farther into the southwest Virginia coalfields to
attend another rally Wednesday night in St. Paul.
   The maximum penalty for the misdemeanor is a year in jail and a
$1,000 fine, but defense attorney Scott Mullins said he doubted the
protesters would be penalized heavily.
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said the mass arrest was ``a statement
that the system has failed working people. The courthouse was chosen
to symbolize the failure of government to protect working people.''
   UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts said organized labor is focusing
on Pittston because the company is attempting to ``bust the union''
and they believe a wound to one labor unit is a wound to all.
   Pittston President Michael Odom said Trumka, not companies or
judges, is to blame for the 55,000 UMW job losses since 1982 and the
erosion of the union coal market share because he is negotiating
unworkable contracts.
   ``We're trying to raise public awareness and congressional
awareness of what is happening to the working class in America,''
said Steve A. Danielson, a 22-year veteran pilot for Eastern
Airlines. ``I'm trying to fight Frank Lorenzo and corporate America.
We want justice.''
   Lorenzo is chairman of Eastern, where more than 600 pilots have
crossed picket lines since the strike against the airline began
March 4. Eleven days ago, Eastern announced it had filled its quota
of 1,700 pilots for its smaller, reorganized operation. The ALPA has
about 3,500 striking members.
   Striking Eastern pilots in uniform on Wednesday mingled with
miners dressed in combat fatigues from the southwest coalfields and
telephone workers from Virginia.
   ``We're finally one big unit,'' said Pat C. Easton, an operator
in Richmond. She said she has been off the job since Aug. 6, when
the Communications Workers of America failed to reach contract
agreements with Bell Atlantic.
   Although the union signed a pact with Bell last week, the strike
still hinges on settlements with the company's local subsidiaries.
   The strike against Pittston began April 5 and involves 1,695
union employees in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky.
Negotiations are to resume next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
