<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Sailor     08-23 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Sailor,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Solo Sailor Reaches Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Jane Weber sailed into Plymouth
in southwest England late Wednesday night at the end of a solo
crossing of the Atlantic Ocean aboard her 43-foot yacht Tilley
Endurable.
   Tired but obviously elated, the 44-year-old yachtswoman received
a boisterous welcome at Plymouth's Millbay Marina from Canadians who
gathered to greet her.
   She left Halifax, Nova Scotia, at the start of the 2,700-mile
voyage on July 29 and became the first Canadian woman to sail across
the Atlantic single-handed.
   Born in Bristol in western England, Ms. Weber took up sailing
eight years ago. She said she used the solo Atlantic challenge as
preparation for a round-the-world yacht race next year.
   She told reporters a storm badly damaged her monohull cutter.
   ``The storm damaged my main sail and over two foot of water
flooded the cabin,'' she said. ``It completely knocked out my
computers and damaged my batteries.''
   She figured repairs may run more than $23,000, but said it was
worthwhile.
   ``I have enjoyed the trip. It was hard and challenging,
especially when the weather was bad, but sailors have short memories.
   ``I am looking forward to having a bath. I have just done over
several thousand miles and feel I deserve it.''
</TEXT>
