<FIRST>u i AM-NewZealand-Whales     08-23 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Zealand-Whales,0300</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WHANGAREI, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 46 pilot whales died in a
mass beaching in the remote far north of New Zealand and wildlife
rangers were trying to refloat 10 that survived, officials said
Thursday.
   A spokesman for the Conservation Department said the animals
washed ashore Wednesday on Ninety Mile Beach, a stretch of sand
along the western side of the isthmus of Aupori Peninsula.
   There was no immediate explanation for the beaching. Officials
said the herd must have come in on high tide after midnight.
   Local farmers and members of a diving club worked through the
night with conservation staff to save the whales, which were taken
by truck across the peninsula to calmer waters.
   Officials said 46 dead whales had been counted so far but that
there could be more further up the beach.
   Local tour bus driver David McNee sighted the first dead whale
early Wednesday and reported that others ``appeared to be flapping
about at the edge of the tide.''
   Staff at a nearby farm tried to coax the creatures into the water
and members of a local diving club were called in to help.
   Keith Smith, a local farmer, said it took at least six people to
roll a whale on its side. He said at least 50 people were involved
in the effort, some dug holes to ease the whales' discomfort, caused
by lying on their fins.
   Rescuers stood up to their shoulders in the surf trying to
stabilize the whales.
   ``They would roll over on their side, they didn't know where they
were,'' Smith said.
   He said at least five whales were returned to the water but that
three came back.
</TEXT>
