<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal 1stLd-Writethru   08-23 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0714,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Government Official Apologizes to Nation for Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Cabinet chief apologizing,
considering resigning; picks up 10th pvs, `In those...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key Cabinet official of newly inaugurated Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu publicly apologized Thursday for an
extramarital affair, the latest scandal to hit Japan's
trouble-ridden governing party.
   ``That such news would be reported was due completely to my own
indiscretion,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Tokuo Yamashita said at a
news conference televised live Thursday. Yamashita is the
government's main spokesman and the prime minister's top lieutenant.
   ``The task of he Kaifu Cabinet is to promote clean government and
as I must follow that and support the prime minister ... I can offer
only my deepest apologies to the people of Japan,'' he said, adding
that he was ``seriously considering'' whether to resign or remain in
office.
   Yamashita's remarks were prompted by an article in the respected
weekly Shukan Shincho magazine alleging that he had an affair with a
26-year-old office worker he met at a Tokyo bar where she worked
part time in 1984. It said the affair ended in 1987.
   The magazine, which went on sale Thursday, also said the
69-year-old Yamashita, who is married, offered the woman $21,000
just one week before he assumed office Aug. 9, but quoted him as
saying it was not intended as ``hush money.''
   ``I did it from my own good intentions after hearing that she's
still having problems in her life,'' the magazine quoted Yamashita
as saying. The report said the woman, whom it did not name, did not
accept the money.
   Reports in the mass-circulation Mainichi Shimbun newspaper and by
the Japan Broadcasting Corp. earlier Thursday said Yamashita was
planning to resign. But Kyodo News Service said he had decided
simply to apologize after discussing the matter with his mentor,
Liberal Democratic Party elder Toshio Komoto.
   The reports came just two weeks after similar allegations helped
bring down Kaifu's predecessor, Sousuke Uno, and could deal a severe
blow to Kaifu, who analysts believe to be little more than a
caretaker until his term as party president, and prime minister,
expires in late October.
   ``For the time being we will apologize and try to explain to the
people and wait for further reaction,'' said a member of Komoto's
faction within the party. He requested anonymity.
   After only 69 days in office, Uno, who allegedly kept paid
mistresses, announced his resignation July 24 to accept
responsibility for the governing Liberal Democrats' unprecedented
losses in a parliamentary election the day before.
   In those elections for half the seats in the two-chamber body's
upper house, the governing party lost its majority for the first
time since the party was formed in 1954. Much of the vote against it
went to the Socialists, Japan's leading opposition party.
   Uno had taken office June 2, after Noboru Takeshita stepped down
to take responsibility for the Recruit affair, a widespread
influence-buying scandal that forced three Cabinet ministers to
resign and led to over a dozen arrests.
   Soon after becoming prime minister, however, a report in the
weekly Sunday Mainichi magazine charged that Uno had paid a geisha
to be his mistress and then mistreated her. The woman later told her
story on national television, seriously damaging Uno's public image.
   The Recruit scandal, along with a new sales tax, unpopular
agricultural policies and the sex scandals have created what
governing party leaders acknowledge is the conservative party's most
serious crisis ever.
   Analysts believe the party could also suffer major setbacks in
elections for the more powerful lower house, which chooses the
nation's prime minister. Though such elections need not be held
until July 1990, political pressure from the opposition-controlled
upper chamber could force them to be called sometime this year.
</TEXT>
