<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Miners     08-23 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Miners,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Promises To Lead Mine Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An archbishop in northern Mexico says he will
lead miners in a peaceful takeover of a copper mine to protest the
government's decision to close it rather than give in to workers'
demands, news reports said Wednesday.
   Carlos Quintero Arce, archbishop of Hermosillo, made the
declaration during a Roman Catholic Mass for 2,800 workers of
Cananea, Mexico's biggest copper mine, which now is guarded by 3,000
troops.
   The government-owned mining company declared bankruptcy Sunday,
saying it cannot afford union demands for a 330 percent increase in
wages and benefits.
   The government plans to sell the mine to private investors. It is
about 25 miles from the Arizona border.
   Quintero Arce told a congregation Tuesday night that the Roman
Catholic Church ``is one with those who suffer, in this case (for)
the workers who bear no responsibility for the suppposed bankruptcy
of the mining company.''
   He criticized the government for sending in troops.
   ``This is no way to treat the miners,'' he was quoted as saying.
``They are not criminals.''
   The government says the soldiers, deployed Sunday when the
bankruptcy petition was granted, are guarding explosives at the mine.
   The archbishop said he is ready to lead the miners and their
families when they attempt a peaceful takeover of Cananea on Sept. 6.
   There have been no confrontations between the locked-out miners
and soldiers while miners have conducted several marches and
meetings outside the mine gates.
   ``I don't think the troops will touch the workers,'' Napoleon
Gomez Sada, head of the national miners' union, was quoted as saying
in the Mexico City daily La Jornada.
   Government officials say if Cananea is not sold to private
investors and reopened within a year there will be a national
shortage of copper. The mine produced 123,600 tons of copper last
year.
   Two deals to sell the indebted company have fallen through since
1988.
</TEXT>
