<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv24   08-23 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 24,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Aug 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Off-Campus Economics For Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along with their classroom schedules, many
students heading to college in the next few weeks will be getting
real-life introductory lessons in personal money management.
   By hallowed tradition, the main financial challenge most college
students face is a chronic shortage of funds.
   But the course description includes other assignments as well _
including dealing with unfamiliar financial institutions and
safeguarding possessions away from home.
   ``For many, moving away from home to attend college marks the
first big step toward adult independence,'' says the Credit Union
National Association, a trade group with more than a passing
interest in the subject.
   ``Part of this growth process involves taking control of your own
financial affairs.''
   To start with, most financial advisers agree, a simple
one-step-at-a-time approach is likely to be best.
   All the offers of credit cards, banking services and other
promotional material handed out during orientation week don't have
to be dealt with right away.
   ``If you're a typical student, you don't have a lot of money and
you probably won't make frequent use of the few financial services
you'll need,'' CUNA advises.
   ``Look for services that provide the features you want, but won't
penalize you for infrequent use.''
   Students also may not have to spend a lot of money insuring their
everyday possessions such as clothing, radios and bicycles against
theft.
   If a student's parents have a homeowners' policy, the Insurance
Information Institute notes, it probably already covers property
that might be stolen away from home, up to a specified limit.
   For example, the institute says, a typical policy covering a
house for $100,000 would give the student $5,000 coverage at school,
minus any deductible.
   Still, this bears verifying beforehand for any families who are
uncertain what their policies say. And if a student is taking
anything of significant value along _ jewelry, say, or a personal
computer _ an insurance agent should be consulted to determine
whether special coverage is required.
   Should a student open a checking account? It's a good idea, the
insurance institute says, because cash lying around a dorm room in
any amount is prime prey for theft.
   The checkbook, furthermore, should be kept in a safe place. So
should the automatic teller machine card that comes with most of
today's accounts.
   College-age consumers seem to have developed a special affinity
for the convenience ATMs offer. According to CUNA, people 18 to 24
years old use ATMs more often than any other age group.
   And a credit card? A generation ago, a student might have had a
lot of trouble getting one. Today he or she is more likely to be
inundated with application forms.
   That can be a nice extra. Or it can mean potential trouble for
people taking on new responsibilities in a new place without much
experience in managing money.
   ``Having your own credit card is a good way to begin to establish
your credit history, and it is useful in emergencies,'' CUNA says.
``Be sure not to abuse the convenience, though, or you could damage
your creditworthiness for years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Aug 24</NOTE>
