<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv24   08-23 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 24,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Aug. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gold in The Gravel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the economy shuffling along, and with
economists focused on whether we'll have a recession, there's a
tendency to think that good news doesn't exist.
   It does. Many of the published economic forecasts say inflation
is likely to remain restrained for the time being, that home
mortgage rates could resume their fall, and that most jobs seem
secure into next year.
   It also seems likely that interest rates aren't going to go to
the sky _ it was only a few months ago that such talk sounded
plausible _ and that means an opportunity for Americans to
straighten out their finances.
   It's a buyer's market in many items; compare that with the 1970s,
when prices and interest rates rose so fast that consumers almost
trampled each other to buy before more increases came. By
comparison, these days are serene.
   If you want to look into the future, there are seers who say even
better times are coming in the 1990s, a viewpoint that often becomes
submerged by the tide of foreboding about budget and trade deficits
and Third World loans.
   These optimists about the decade to come cite improvements in
business that make it more efficient, global competition that will
tend to keep prices in line, and the opening of big new consumer
markets, in Asia, for instance.
   But you do not need to go that far into the future to find good
news. Some is mixed with bad, of course, and that makes it harder to
find, but it's there if you want to search. There's gold in the
gravel.
   Amidst a generally bleak picture, for example, there are signs
that some areas of health care costs might finally be submitting to
control. And while doctors still quit rather than risk medical
malpractice, there are signs of a corrective process. The
beginnings, anyway.
   Doctors have learned to avoid some of the incidents that lead to
malpractice claims, to document their motives and methodology, to
communicate better with patients _ even to adjust their bills.
   At the same time, tort reform is reducing the number of cases
brought to court. States are putting caps on claims. Juries are
becoming more aware of the societal costs of litigation and are
cutting back on extravagant awards.
   You might also have thought that foreigners, mainly Japanese,
were buying up America. That's a recurring bad-news theme, a hot
one, a theme that lends itself to such phrases as the selling of
America and economic invasion.
   But America hasn't been sold. Smart foreign investors did, in
effect, let Americans use their money in return for some assets, but
a report from the National Realty Council, made up of real estate
owners and operators, shows they own only about 1 percent of
America's $12 trillion worth of real estate. And the Japanese
weren't the big investors; the British were.
   So what's all the fuss about? Two things: The Japanese did invest
a lot of money in America during the 1980s, and they forced Canada
into third place. Secondly, foreign investments were concentrated,
mainly in downtown areas.
   In 1987, for instance, the real estate firm of Coldwell Banker
estimated that foreigners owned 46 percent of office space in
downtown Los Angeles, 39 percent in Houston and 32 percent in
Minneapolis. Those are headline figures.
   But foreigners owned relatively little in Baltimore, Cincinnati,
San Diego and other large cities, and they owned very little of
America's geographical area. It's a big country, but the myth of
foreign ownership was even bigger.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Aug. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
