<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Stones-Music Adv27   08-23 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Stones-Music, Adv 27,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Keith Richards: You're Right, Music Isn't As Good Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's news for the Woodstock generation
who think rock music today just isn't what it used to be. Keith
Richards thinks you're right.
   ``The music thing is going through a lot of trauma,'' said the
Rolling Stones guitarist in a recent interview with The Associated
Press, during a break from rehearsals for their upcoming U.S. tour,
which begins Aug. 31 in Philadelphia.
   He agreed with respondents to a recent Media General-Associated
Press poll, who said by almost a 2-to-1 margin that the music of the
late 1960s topped the music of today in quality.
   ``The technology is becoming overwhelming,'' he said.
``Throughout the '80s, the record companies are saying, `Why bother
with things like musicians when you can just push a button here?'
   ``It's toytown,'' he continued. ``Everything goes around in
cycles, and I think in the '80s there's been a lot of confusion over
what to do with all of these possibilities and how to sort it out
and bring it back under control, to make it music again.''
   Not surprisingly, Mick Jagger disagrees.
   ``I don't think it's better,'' said the Stones' rubber-limbed
lead singer. ``It's just different. I think it's a banal question to
ask anybody.
   ``It's so subjective to an age group,'' said Jagger, who's spent
much of the '80s battling with Richards, his songwriting partner.
``If you are 19 now, whatever Bon Jovi record is still going to hold
that (memory) for you 20 years down the line. It's got nothing to do
with whether the band is any good or the song is any good, it's your
subjective experience with rock 'n' roll that counts, and I think
that's got a lot to do with the continuing popularity of these
ancient '60s bands.''
   Those stories about competitiveness between the Beatles and
Rolling Stones during the 1960s were true, Jagger said.
   ``It's very hard to come to terms with the fact that someone's
been around for so long,'' he said. ``You don't have very many
contemporaries still with you.
   ``There's no pressure, because there isn't anybody else giving us
any,'' Jagger said. ``The Who, since the death of Keith Moon, were
no longer the Who. It is a drag in a way, and not just in a
competitive sense.''
   Jagger and Richards can't pinpoint why this band of
fortysomething rockers are smashing attendance records across the
country this year. Four shows at New York's Shea Stadium sold out in
hours. Ticket-sale speed records were set in Los Angeles,
Philadelphia, Boston, Toronto, Cincinnati and elsewhere.
   It's a lot of reasons, Richards said, not the least of which is
``it is a good band.
   ``There's people who have grown up with us, been with us all the
way,'' he said. ``Maybe it's because they don't know a world without
the Rolling Stones. There's the sun, the moon, the trees and the
Rolling Stones.''
   Two of today's hottest bands, Living Colour and Guns 'n' Roses,
will open various shows along the Rolling Stones nationwide tour
this fall.
   They're selected, he said, ``because there's a feeling that
they've been elected by the public and not by the (music) business.''
   Richards flashes his intense pride in his own band when asked if
the Stones feel competition from those hot, young sellers.
   ``You can't compete with this,'' Richards whispered, his face
contorting in a wicked laugh.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
