<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-23 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0890</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods
tumbled 1.9 percent in July to the lowest level in nine months, the
government said, providing further evidence of a weakening economy.
   It was the fourth drop this year in the sector, which includes
items ranging from washing machines to warships that are expected to
last three or more years. The sector is considered a bellwether of
the economy's performance.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that demand for durable
goods totaled a seasonally adjusted $122.9 billion last month, the
lowest level since October 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Losses by the nation's savings institutions
rose to $3.7 billion in the April-June quarter, the worst in a year,
regulators said.
   The second-quarter loss was up from $3.5 billion in the first
three months of 1989 and was the worst since the record $4.1 billion
in the same period of last year, the Office of Thrift Supervision
said Tuesday.
   For the first half of the year, losses were mounting at a rate
that could make 1989 the worst year for the savings industry since
the Depression, topping 1988's record of $13.4 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who once peddled fruit and another who made
his money selling junk bonds are among the newest members of the
world's billionaires club, according to estimates released by
Fortune magazine.
   Taiwanese tycoon Tsai Wan-Lin, 64, whose holdings include
insurance, hotels and soy sauce makers, and U.S. financier Michael
R. Milken are among 32 newcomers to Fortune's 1989 list of the
world's billionaires.
   The Sultan of Brunei, who presides over the small oil-rich nation
near the South China Sea, is still the world's wealthiest man with
an estimated fortune of $25 billion, the magazine said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas billionaire Harold Simmons, through one of
his holdings, has contacted the head of Georgia Gulf Corp.,
suggesting a variety of moves that could ``enhance'' the value of
the Atlanta company's stock.
   Georgia Gulf stock jumped $6 a share following the release of the
letter Tuesday, but analysts said the correspondence was vague and
shed little light on the Texan's intentions. Simmons owns almost 10
percent of the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has accused
demolition contractors in 11 states of violating asbestos-removal
safeguards in schools, restaurants and other buildings.
   Civil lawsuits seeking unspecified damages were filed Tuesday by
the government against 33 companies and individuals plus the New
York City Board of Education.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shareholder is suing UAL Corp., contending that
its directors have decided to sell and asking a court to force them
to negotiate with suitor Marvin Davis and then auction the company
to the highest bidder.
   The suit was filed Tuesday in Cook County circuit court on behalf
of a single shareholder. It seeks a temporary injunction to compel
UAL, the parent of United Airlines, ``to bargain in good faith with
all interested acquirers and auction UAL to the highest possible
bidder.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC says that starting Labor Day weekend it will
try to sell its new fall prime-time lineup at Sears, Roebuck and Co.
through an ambitious publicity campaign also geared toward boosting
sales at the nation's No. 1 retailer.
   The month-long joint program, announced Tuesday, is seen by
industry experts as an important step by the television networks in
halting the erosion of audiences to cable, independent TV outlets
and video tapes.
   CBS and K mart Corp. announced a similar arrangement in May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Wall Street trader Richard B. Wigton says
he's angry about being handcuffed and arrested in front of
colleagues two years ago and wants to move on following the
government's aborted investigation of him for insider trading.
   Wigton was one of three securities traders arrested in a February
1987 raid viewed at the time as symbolic of the government's
crackdown on white-collar corruption. The case was dropped last week
and Wigton spoke at a news conference Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. officials say they expect to
complete within 10 days a $1 billion-plus takeover of Prime Computer
Inc., which has been battling another company's hostile buyout offer
for nearly a year.
   Whitney partner Russell E. Planitzer said Tuesday that James F.
McDonald would be named Prime's new president after the tender offer
for 79 percent of Prime's shares is completed at the annual board
meeting Thursday. A new board will be installed when the deal is
complete, he said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled out of a skid with a late rally Tuesday,
ending roughly even a day after the biggest decline in nearly two
months. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished up 3.99 at
2,650.99.
   The dollar fell sharply against most key currencies in thin,
nervous trading.
   Bond prices fell as new government data indicating economic
strength led to disappointing results in a Treasury refinancing
auction.
   Sugar futures prices rose sharply, grain and soybean futures
finished mostly higher while livestock, oil and precious-metal
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
