<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ITX-Landfills     08-23 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-ITX-Landfills,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Awarded Government Toxic Cleanup Contract Target Of Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California company awarded a federal
contract Tuesday to clean up hazardous-waste sites faces a lawsuit
for alleged stock fraud and has been fined $4 million for
infractions at two landfills.
   The Army Corp of Engineers, which awarded the contract, was not
aware of the lawsuit or fines against International Technology
Corp., or ITX, until two weeks ago, when an aide to a Utah
congressman told the agency, said the aide, who asked that he and
the congressman remain anonymous.
   A spokeswoman at the Corps' Omaha office, Betty White, said ITX,
based in Torrance, Calif., had been audited and found ``able to
perform the work we want done.''
   The contract, the first of four to be awarded, could be worth $50
million over five years and entails cleaning up leaking barrels
containing PCBs, kerosene and other hazardous wastes at government
and private landfills nationwide. ITX performs similar work for the
state of California.
   ITX corporate counsel John Allen said the lawsuit and fines are
not relevant to the contract. Allen said the landfill fines were for
administrative violations.
   An attorney in the Corps' Omaha office, Ann Wright, said
companies bidding on the contract are required to disclose all
relevant information. Wright would not say if ITX disclosed the
lawsuit and fines in its bid.
   Allen said companies do not routinely disclose that kind of
information. ``It doesn't relate directly to your ability to provide
a service,'' he said.
   The lawsuit arose from a stock offering in late 1987 when ITX
sold 3.5 million shares to raise $47.5 million. ITX began issuing
the stock in September 1987 but announced that December that it was
closing its hazardous-waste transport and landfill operations, a
substantial part of the company's business.
   The lawsuit alleges that ITX planned to leave the landfill
business before issuing the stock but withheld the information from
the public.
   ``The stock was sold at an inflated price,'' said Ernest Kaufman,
an attorney for the plaintiffs. Kaufman said the suit seeks ``many
millions'' of dollars and represents thousands of people.
   Allen said the stock's price dropped with the rest of the market
during the October 1987 market crash. ITX stock hit $9 a share after
the market collapse. The stock sold for $13 to $14 a share when
issued.
   ITX's annual 10-K report said the Securities and Exchange
Commission is looking into the allegations.
   Five months before ITX issued the stock, the company agreed to
pay the California Department of Health Services $3.2 million in
fines for violations at two landfills the company owned. This past
June, ITX paid another $900,000 fine because it underestimated the
closure and post-closure costs of one of its landfills.
   An attorney for the California Health Services Department, Sue
Bertkin, said the 1987 fines covered several violations, including
disposing of hazardous wastes not identified in the company's
application, not gaining approval before increasing the capacity of
a landfill, and inadequate training of personnel.
   Officials from various California state agencies said none of the
violations threatened public health or the environment. The fines
are not unusual, said Health Services worker Rubia Bertram.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
