<DOCNO> AP890823-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WPPSSBonds 1stLd-Writethru f0160 08-23 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WPPSS Bonds, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0160,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Bank Action Delays Sale of New WPPSS Bonds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with sale delayed two weeks. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `WPPSS, a ...'. SUBS grafs 13-15, `Chemical Bank ... Britton
said,' to conform to change and to UPDATE with bank comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Tuesday delayed for at least two
weeks the sale of refinancing bonds for two troubled nuclear
projects of the Washington Public Power Supply System after a New
York bank said it has a claim against the sale's proceeds.
   WPPSS _ which defaulted on $2.25 billion worth of bonds in 1983
in the biggest-ever municipal bond default _ planned this week to
sell $450 million worth of bonds that would yield an estimated 7
percent to 8 percent interest.
   The bonds would replace bonds sold early this decade at 10
percent to 15 percent interest for its nuclear plants Nos. 1 and 3,
said WPPSS spokesman John Britton.
   WPPSS, a consortium of utilities formed to build power plants,
estimates it will save an average of $70 million to $80 million a
year over the next 30 years through the refinancing.
   The sale would mark the first time WPPSS has sold bonds since the
default.
   The Nos. 1 and 3 plants sit partially completed at the Hanford
nuclear reservation and at Satsop, west of Olympia. Construction was
halted early this decade because of financing problems and doubts
about the need for new electricity sources.
   Late last week, Chemical Bank of New York wrote to the bond
trustees for Nos. 1 and 3, saying it had claims against the proceeds
of the refinancing bonds because of a federal court case involving
the two plants, Britton said.
   Chemical Bank is a trustee for investors who hold bonds in WPPSS
plants Nos. 4 and 5, which were terminated in 1982 when partially
built. It was these bonds that resulted in the WPPSS default.
   Chemical Bank is involved in an action in U.S. District Court in
Seattle in which it claims costs were misallocated between twin
plants Nos. 1 and 4, which sit on the same site at Hanford, and
between Nos. 3 and 5, which share the Satsop site.
   Because of their proximity and design similarities, certain costs
such as engineering work, access roads and some buildings were
shared by plants 1 and 4, and by plants 3 and 5, and those costs
were allocated to each plant according to a formula.
   Chemical Bank claims the formula misallocated some of those costs
to Nos. 4 and 5, and that the bondholders it represents stand to
gain up to $1 billion because of the incorrect billing.
   In May, a federal judge ruled that Chemical Bank does have a lien
against any costs that were misallocated to plants 4 and 5. However,
a decision has not been made on whether any costs were in fact
misallocated, Britton said.
   William Berls, a vice president for Chemical Bank's financial
services division, said Tuesday that the letter to the trustees for
Nos. 1 and 3 contained ``nothing new,'' and was intended solely to
make sure the trustees understood Chemical Bank's interest.
   The exact terms of the refinancing bond sale were to be set
Tuesday by the sale's underwriters, Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. and Smith
Barney Harris Upham and Co., Britton said.
   The sale was scheduled for Thursday, Britton said.
   ``The lawyers are discussing the matter but our position hasn't
changed'' _ that Chemical Bank has no claim against proceeds of the
refinancing sale, Britton said.
   Britton noted that the cost-sharing litigation was covered in the
250-page disclosure statement WPPSS issued for the refinancing sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
