<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-23 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar eased against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices were little
changed.
   Currency dealers said the market was empty with most investors
staying on the sidelines in the absence of any news developments.
   Some market participants attributed the dollar's slightly weaker
stance partly to Tuesday's report of a sharper-than-expected
1.9-percent drop in U.S. durable goods orders for July, and partly
to rumors in New York that the West German central bank would raise
key interest rates Thursday.
   Although the market will be watching for developments when the
Bundesbank resumes its regular policy meetings after a summer pause,
most analysts agree such action is unlikely.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.43 yen to a closing 142.35 Later, in London, it
was quoted at 142.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.9405 West German marks, down from 1.9410; 6.6755
Swiss francs, up from 1.6730; 6.5520 French francs, down from
6.5555; 2.1879 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2835; 1,393.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,403.00; 1.1750 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1742.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5875 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5840 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $366.30 a troy ounce, compared with late
Tuesday's $366.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.80.
   In Zurich, the bid was $366.75, up from $366.40 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 32 cents to close at $367.23.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.23 a troy ounce, down from
Tuesday's $5.24.
</TEXT>
