<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0730EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-23 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped against the Japanese yen
today for the third consecutive day in Tokyo, and share prices fell
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 142.35 yen, down 0.43 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.78 yen. After opening at 142.30 yen, the dollar ranged
between 142.20 and 142.60 yen. It now has fallen 1.17 yen in three
trading days.
   Analysts said the U.S. currency opened lower following its
downswing in New York Tuesday, but then recovered slightly.
   ``There was speculation that the West German Bundesbank would
raise interest rates and it caused the dollar to decline against the
West German mark,'' said a dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank. ``But the
speculation was said to be groundless and it caused the dollar to
bounce back marginally.''
   Another dealer at the bank said, ``It was another quiet day in
Tokyo. Most dealers find it difficult to make substantial moves
because of a lack of incentives. Institutional investors are not
placing large orders, either.''
   Dealers also said market participants were awaiting the results
of a two-day meeting of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board's open market
committee in Washington, which was to end later today. Interest
rates were among topics to be discussed at the meeting.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 26.48 points
Tuesday, fell another 221.07 points, or 0.63 percent, closing at
34,893.28.
   Securities dealers said trading was light throughout the day
because of a lack of incentives.
   ``It (index) surpassed the 35,000 mark at one point during the
day, but market participants quickly took advantage and turned to
profit-taking, causing the Nikkei to fall back again,'' said a
dealer at Nikko Securities Co.
</TEXT>
