<DOCNO> AP890823-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 0937EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     08-23 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Trade Figures Worse Than Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to 2.46
billion pounds in July from a revised shortfall of 1.92 billion
pounds in June, the government announced Wednesday.
   The Central Statistical Office said the worse-than-expected,
seasonally-adjusted figures could have been distorted by a
three-week strike by dock workers at some British ports which ended
earlier this month.
   The pound started to fall in hectic trading on the news from
$1.5875 before the figures were released at to $1.5890, but the Bank
of England quickly intervened.
   The government said the current account deficit for July was 2.06
billion pounds, the equivalent of $3.25 billion, compared with a
month-earlier deficit of 1.52 billion pounds.
   The current account deficit includes invisible trade, such as
services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer
payments. Such trade was estimated to be in surplus by 400 million
pounds.
   Forecasts had called for a merchandise trade gap of 1.7 billion
to 1.8 billion pounds and a current account deficit of 1.3 billion
to 1.4 billion pounds.
   The government said exports totalled 7.73 billion pounds in July,
down from 7.87 billion pounds in June.
   Imports totaled a record 10.19 billion pounds in July, up from
9.79 billion pounds in June.
   Since the beginning of 1989, Britain's merchandise trade balance
has been in deficit by 14.27 billion pounds, compared with a deficit
of 11.22 billion pounds a year earlier.
   The current account has been in deficit by 11.54 billion pounds
so far this year, compared with a deficit of 7.65 billion pounds a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
