<FIRST>r f PM-Oldsmobile-Ringo     08-23 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oldsmobile-Ringo,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ringo Starr, Daughter, in New Oldsmobile Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who else would be in an Oldsmobile but Ringo Starr
and his daughter Lee?
   Oldsmobile, the General Motors Corp. division known mostly for
drivers with graying hair and car trunks big enough for a couple of
sets of golf clubs, kicks off a second-year series of advertisements
Friday night with the theme of ``This is not your father's
Oldsmobile.''
   In one ad, to debut on NBC's ``NFL Preseason Football,'' the
ex-Beatle _ complete with pony tail and an earring _ is chased by a
crowd of middle-aged women, slides down a banquet table and out of a
12th-floor window. His fall is broken by an awning and he winds up
in the passenger seat of a new four-door Olds Cutlass Supreme.
   At the wheel is his 18-year-old daughter, sporting purple hair.
   ``Would you ever have imagined that Oldsmobile would use someone
with a ponytail and an earring and a daughter with purple hair to
sell their cars?'' said Rick Ross, the division's director of
advertising.
   Others in the ``father'' campaign for 1990 will be actor Peter
Graves and his daughter, Amanda; Ted Einstein, great-grandson of
Albert Einstein; and the adult children of entertainer Harry
Belafonte, without their father.
   The campaign begun last year caught the eye of the advertising
world, but may not be attracting buyers to dealer showrooms. Through
Aug. 10 of this year, Oldsmobile sales were running 15.4 percent
behind last year's pace, while GM car sales were down 9 percent.
   ``It takes two or three years, sometimes longer, for a campaign
to end up in a direct-sales boost,'' Ross said. ``I think we're
going to see some sales results in 1990. Our dealers are reporting
they're getting a lot younger traffic.''
   According to Olds, its average buyer is 51 years old, and
executives would like that age to drop into the upper 40s.
   In an effort to broaden the Oldsmobile appeal, the company will
introduce a minivan, the Silhouette, and will get some production of
a new sport-utility vehicle next year, GM officials have said.
   Advertising budget figures are closely held by automakers, but
there have been estimates that GM has spent $120 million advertising
its Oldsmobiles for the 1989 model year, much of that cost in
starting up the new theme.
   Ross said the division is increasing its advertising spending
this year, but not by as much as it did in 1989 to get the
``father'' campaign off the ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
