<FIRST>u f PM-GeorgiaGulf-Simmons     08-23 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia Gulf-Simmons,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simmons Considering Buyout Of Georgia Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NL Industries Inc., a company controlled by Texas
financier Harold Simmons, said it was prepared to offer around $1.3
billion for Georgia Gulf Corp., a commerical concern in which it
recently accumulated a 9.9 percent stake.
   The propsal, made in a letter to Georgia Gulf Chairman James R.
Kuse, sent Georgia Gulf stock surging $7.25 a share to close at
$58.75 Tuesday in active trading on the New York Stock Exchange. NL
shares rose 12.5 cents to finish at $24.625.
   The closing Georgia Gulf price exceeded the $55 a share Simmons
said he was prepared to pay for the company. Two months ago Georgia
Gulf shares traded at around $35.
   ``Such a transaction might take the form of a leveraged
recapitalization, merger or other transaction,'' said the Kuse
letter, which was signed by NL President J. Landis Martin. ``We
believe that the value of Georgia Gulf's common shares would be
enhanced by a transaction in which shareholders receive $55 per
share in cash.''
   Georgia Pacific released the letter without comment on Tuesday, a
day after it was sent.
   The letter follows a recent filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission in which Simmons indicated a takeover attempt of
Georgia Gulf was possible. He said his interest in the company was
``no longer held solely for the purpose of investment.''
   Simmons and his companies owns 2.3 million shares, or 9.9 percent
of Georgia Gulf's approximately 24 million shares outstanding, a
stake that was accumulated in recent months.
   John Garcia, a securities analyst with Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. in
New York, said that Georgia Gulf might try to establish an employee
stock ownership plan to fend off a hostile takeover attempt.
   Georgia Gulf, created in 1985 as a spinoff of Georgia-Pacific
Corp., had 1988 sales of $1.06 billion.
   Simmons has built a fortune estimated at more than $1.6 billion
through acquisitions. His holding company, Dallas-based Valhi Inc.,
had 1988 sales of $2.25 billion.
   Simmons acquired control of NL Industries, a chemical and
petroleum service company, last year in a $1 billion deal.
</TEXT>
