<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PrimeComputer     08-23 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. Prepares to Take Reins at Prime Computer Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restoring customers' confidence in Prime Computer
Inc. will be the first order of business when the company, hobbled
by an expensive antitakeover campaign, completes its friendly merger
with J.H. Whitney &amp; Co.
   Whitney partner Russell E. Planitzer said Tuesday the deal should
be completed within 10 days.
   A new president, James F. McDonald, will immediately take the
reins and a new board will be named, Planitzer said.
   Prime, a Natick-based minicomputer maker, had been searching for
an ally against a $1.13 billion hostile bid from MAI Basic Four Inc.
of Tustin, Calif., when Whitney, the nation's oldest venture capital
firm, came forward in June.
   The companies agreed to a friendly merger under which Prime will
effectively become a private company.
   Whitney offered to pay $20 a share for 49.5 million shares and
exchange notes with a face value of $22 per share for the remaining
21 percent of Prime's shares.
   Securities analysts said those notes would trade at a substantial
discount and estimated the total value of the deal at between $17
and $18.50 a share, or $1.06 billion to $1.16 billion.
   McDonald, the next president, has most recently been president of
Gould Inc., which he guided to a turnaround and subsequent sale to
Nippon Mining Co. in 1988. He succeeds Anthony L. Craig, who has
held the post since November and has chosen to resign after the
Whitney group completes its tender offer for Prime.
   Repaying debt will be pivotal for Prime in the coming months,
said John W. Adams, an analyst who follows Prime for the Boston
investment firm Adams Harkness &amp; Hill.
   ``The real issue is whether all that debt on the balance sheet is
going to make a difference to customers,'' he said. ``Prime had a
very strong balance sheet going into this and goes out with a very
leveraged balance sheet.''
   McDonald said the company's two immediate priorities would be
employees and customers. He said both groups had been severely
shaken by the long struggle against MAI Basic.
   ``If I were a customer in the last 10 months, (the company's
situation) would have bothered me to death,'' he said. ``I think the
change is a very welcome one.''
   McDonald said the computer company would remain in Natick, but
that a new business strategy would include an undetermined number of
layoffs and substantial changes in the company's senior management.
   Prime, which makes minicomputers and computer-aided design and
manufacturing systems, turned a profit of $19 million on sales of
$1.6 billion in 1988.
   But the cost of defending against a takeover and slow sales of
minicomputers led to losses of $14.4 million in the final quarter of
1988, $5 million in the first quarter of this year and $19 million
in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
