<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0318</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground today as interest
rates turned downward.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up .19 to 2,651.18
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 622 up, 332 down and
523 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.63 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   In the credit markets this morning, prices of long-term
government bonds rose nearly $5 for each $1,000 in face value,
lowering their yields to the 8.21 percent-8.27 percent range.
   Analysts said that took a little pressure off the stock market,
which has been weighed down lately by concerns that rates were being
pushed higher by a stronger-than-expected economy.
   Still, many Wall Streeters remain doubtful that the Federal
Reserve will take any further steps any time soon to relax its
credit policy.
   In the view of most observers, recent evidence suggests that the
Fed might be shifting its focus back to restraining inflation in the
absence of any signs of an imminent recession.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Dow Chemical, up \ at 103;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 38{, and Eastman Kodak, up ]
at 50[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.20 to 190.31. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .62 at 376.48.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 3.99 to 2,650.99
after having fallen 40.97 points on Monday.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 635 up, 823 down and 531 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 141.93 million shares, up from 136.80
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
