<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-DigitalCuts     08-23 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digital Cuts,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company May Cut Parts Of Work Force by 25 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. reportedly has told at
least nine of its departments to cut their workforces by 25 percent
through attrition or transfer by July 1991.
   Digital, which is based in Maynard, has about 125,800 employees,
but only an estimated 30,000 apparently would be involved, putting
the total reduction in employees at around 7,500, The Boston Globe
reported today.
   The computer manufacturer confirmed the existence of an internal
memo about the workforce reduction and said any of the cuts would be
made through attrition and transfer of workers whose jobs are
eliminated to other divisions.
   ``We have no plans at all for layoffs,'' said Nikki Richardson, a
spokeswoman for Digital.
   The announcement comes less than a week after Unisys Corp.,
another big computer maker, said it plans to reduce its worldwide
workforce by 7 percent to 8 percent by the end of 1990, a cut of
6,000 to 7,000 jobs would include some layoffs.
   Jobs affected by cutbacks are considered support jobs _ including
those in administration, law, finance, personnel, purchasing data
information services, facilities, materials and quality, the Globe
said.
   Ms. Richardson said she did not know how many employees performed
such job, but analysts told the Globe it could be as many as 30,000.
   Because the company's headquarters is in Maynard, much of any
reduction could affect Massachusetts employees. Digital has 33,700
of its employees in the state.
   The memo, the Globe said, orders heads of affected departments to
plan for cutting budgets for the fiscal year that began July 1 by 10
percent.
   ``It is assumed that this will include a sizable reduction in
population,'' the memo said.
   It also said that to reduce the number of employees in those
departments by 25 percent by July 1991 ``each group will have to
struggle with what work to discontinue.
   ``They should not just shave expenses, but rather eliminate
entire efforts,'' it said.
   ``It's not a plan, it's a working document.... a directional
document to promote ideas within the company,'' Ms. Richardson said
of the memo.
   Digital previously said it will freeze the salaries of all its
employees in the United States and move as many as 4,000 employees
from manufacturing to sales and service because of a slowdown in
demand for its computers.
   It announced last month that profits for the quarter ended June
30 were down 22 percent to $313.2 million on sales of $3.495 billion.
</TEXT>
