<FIRST>r f BC-Fokker     08-23 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fokker,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fokker Reportedly To Expand F-100 Plant In Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dutch aerospace firm Fokker has
decided to expand a Dutch assembly line for its successful F-100
passenger jet, but is still negotiating over a new plant in the
United States, a Dutch newspaper reported Wednesday.
   Fokker denied that any decision had been made on the expansion of
its current F-100 assembly line at Amsterdam's Schiphol Airport, and
said the issue was still wide open.
   However, the Amsterdam newspaper De Volkskrant said the company
had opted to invest $381 million to expand the Schiphol plant, which
can build up to 46 F-100 jets a year.
   Other contenders for the new assembly line, which would be set up
to produce 200 F-100s from 1991 to 1997, are the Lockheed Aircraft
Corp., Grumman Corp. and Rockwell.
   According to the Volkskrant report, Fokker is still negotiating
with Lockheed's Marietta, Georgia, plant but the talks are
stagnating over the price demanded by Lockheed for assembling the
twin-engine, short-haul jets. The report gave no specifics.
   ``Banking circles in Britain openly discuss the impending
expansion at Schiphol,'' said the newspaper report, adding that
several unidentified British banks had financed the new assembly
line.
   However, Fokker spokesman Bart van Veen denied that any British
financiers were involved and characterized the Volkskrant story as
``incorrect.
   ``Nothing's been decided yet. The decisions will all be taken in
the course of or even late next month,'' Van Veen said.
   According to De Volkskrant, Fokker would announce the move to
expand at Schiphol officially on Friday, along with its semi-annual
profit figures.
   So far, Fokker has sold 193 F-100s to customers including
Swissair, USAir, American Airlines and Braniff Airlines. Fokker
customers have taken out options for another 199 of the
fuel-efficient jets.
   However, the company's Schiphol plant, which employs 7,000
people, is too small to meet the demand for F-100s.
   Van Veen said negotiations were still under way ``not only with
Lockheed but also with other'' plane builders in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
