<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Wednesday against most major
foreign currencies in European trading. Gold prices declined.
   The dollar strengthened as rumors of a possible West German
interest rate hike faded and dealers decided that the dollar selling
on Tuesday was overdone.
   News of a wider-than-expected British trade deficit also helped
push the dollar higher against the pound.
   Britain's July merchandise trade gap rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3.87 billion from $3.01 billion the previous month, while
the current account deficit increased to $3.24 billion from $2.38
billion.
   Sterling had gained against the dollar in early trading but ended
the day at $1.5700, down from $1.5840 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.43 yen to a closing 142.35 yen. It rose in London
to 143.10 yen.
   Other late dollar rates compared with Tuesday: 1.9555 West German
marks, up from 1.9410; 1.6870 Swiss francs, up from 1.6730; 6.5965
French francs, up from 6.5555; 2.2000 Dutch guilders, down from
2.2035; 1.1727 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1742; and 1,399.50
Italian lire, down from 1,403.00.
   Gold traded at $364.25 a troy ounce in London, down from $366.75
Tuesday. In Zurich, the bid price was $363.85 an ounce, down from
$366.40.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 32 cents to close at $367.23 an
ounce.
   Silver fell in London to $5.19 a troy ounce from Tuesday's $5.24.
</TEXT>
