<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced slightly today as
interest rates declined.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.31 to 2,656.30 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 820 up, 542 down and
547 unchanged.
   In the credit markets, prices of long-term government bonds rose
about $5 for each $1,000 in face value, lowering their yields to the
8.20 percent-8.27 percent range.
   Analysts said that took a little pressure off the stock market,
which has been weighed down lately by concerns that rates were being
pushed higher by a stronger-than-expected economy.
   Still, many Wall Streeters remain doubtful that the Federal
Reserve will take any further steps any time soon to relax its
credit policy.
   In the view of most observers, recent evidence suggests that the
Fed might be shifting its focus back to restraining inflation in the
absence of any signs of an imminent recession.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Dow Chemical, up 1| at
104]; Alcoa, up } at 74|; Procter &amp; Gamble, up 1 at 124~, and
Eastman Kodak, up 1 at 50}.
   Tesoro Petroleum climbed 1[ to 10}. Harken Energy proposed to
acquire the company for $11.75 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.44 to 190.55. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .43 at 376.29.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 102.92 million shares with two
hours to go.
