<HEAD>London Shares Shrug Off Trade Data</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices shrugged off disappointing British
trade data Wednesday and rallied strongly on the London Stock
Exchange.
   Traders attributed the advance to renewed speculative buying and
steady early trading on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended up 11.6
points, or 0.4 percent, at 2,382.4.
   Volume totaled 439 million shares, up from 391.6 million traded
on Tuesday.
   ``The market just wants to go up,'' one trader said. ``There is a
feeling that the trade figures are so bad they can't get any worse.''
   A British government trade report showed a current-account
deficit of 2.062 billion pounds, or around $3.237 billion, in July,
surpassing market expectations which averaged around 1.35 billion
pounds, or $2.119 billion.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 500-stock index closed at
1,334.73, up 4.09. The narrower Financial Times 30-share index
closed up 9.6 points at 1,975.9.
   At the London close, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was
up 10.24 points at 2,661.23.
