<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-23 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower On Rainy Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mostly
lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting overnight
rainfall in Midwestern growing areas and forecasts for more
precipitation in the region.
   Rainfall amounts ranging from sprinkles to more than an inch were
reported Tuesday in the eastern Corn Belt states of Indiana, Ohio
and Michigan. Overnight showers brought badly needed moisture to
Iowa, Illinois and Missouri.
   But the losses were limited by rising worries about the potential
for damage to crops that were planted later than usual due to wet
conditions in the spring.
   ``Some articles are starting to surface from meteorologists
concerning the potential for an early freeze,'' said Ted Mao, a
grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Perceptions also are growing that crop yields may not be as great
as many experts had earlier thought.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.91{ a bushel; corn
was 2} cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.35{ a
bushel; oats were 1} cents lower to \ cent higher with September at
$1.39\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 5 cents lower with
September at $5.98{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
