<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-23 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Rallies Anew On Mexico Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rallied strongly Wednesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange amid fears that the shutdown of Mexico's largest
copper mine would put another crimp in the already tight supplies of
the metal.
   On other markets, precious metal futures retreated; most oil
futures advanced; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; and
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher.
   Copper futures settled 2.45 cents to 2.55 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $1.2785 a pound, the highest
settlement for a copper contract since May 5. The September contract
traded as high as $1.2920 during the session.
   The Mexican government declared its Cananea copper mine bankrupt
over the weekend and shut it down, prompting speculation that the
mine could be closed for several months.
   The mine is capable of producing about 160,000 metric tons of
refined copper a year, about 2 percent of the world total.
   Copper prices have risen sharply this month, underpinned by an
ongoing nationwide copper miners' strike in Peru, a strike at a
Highland Valley Copper Co. mine in Canada and persistent production
problems in several other major copper-producing countries.
   ``The market will look at any situation that tells us about
supply,'' said Craig Sloane, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``If the situation in Mexico means there's
a potential loss of supply, that's important.''
   Gold and silver futures slid lower on the Comex, partly in
reaction to the dollar's gains against other major currencies.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $2.70 lower with August at $365.80 a troy
ounce; silver was 6 cents lower across the board with September at
$5.175 a troy ounce.
   Most oil futures ended higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange
after an early sell-off tied to the American Petroleum Institute's
bearishly construed weekly inventories report.
   The API report indicated that U.S. stocks of crude oil rose by
4.48 million barrels last week while refinery runs increased 0.8
percent.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 4 cents lower to 11 cents
higher with October at $18.80 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent
lower to .15 cent higher with September at 51.91 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .55 cent lower to .35 cent higher with
September at 53.93 cents a gallon.
   Most grain and soybean futures fell slightly on the Chicago Board
of Trade, reflecting overnight rainfall in Midwestern growing areas
and forecasts for more precipitation in the region.
   But the losses were limited by rising worries about the potential
for freeze damage to crops that were planted later than usual due to
wet conditions in the spring.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with September at
$3.91} a bushel; corn was 2} cents lower to 1 cent higher with
September at $2.36 a bushel; oats were { cent to 1} cents lower with
September at $1.39\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 5 cents
lower with September at $5.98 a bushel.
   Cattle futures ended mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, supported by stronger spot markets. Pork futures advanced
ahead of the Agriculture Department's monthly cold-storage report,
which showed 96.4 million pounds of pork bellies in cold storage on
Aug. 1. The number was close to market expectations.
   The report also showed large supplies of frozen ham and turkey,
which should translate into abundant supplies of Thanksgiving and
Christmas meats, said Charles Levitt, an analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with
September at 74.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower
to .10 cent higher with August at 84.30 cents a pound; hogs were
unchanged to .82 cent higher with October at 41.47 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .40 cent higher with August at
27.17 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
