<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 1828EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SoybeanCorner-White     08-23 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soybean Corner-White,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Farm Bureau Chief Presses For Probe Of CBOT Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An influential farming leader on Wednesday called
for a federal probe of the world's largest commodity exchange for
abruptly forcing a big sale of soybean contracts last month, a move
he called the worst blow to market confidence since the Soviet grain
embargo nearly a decade ago.
   The emergency action by the Chicago Board of Trade caused a sharp
drop in July soybean futures prices and undermined farmer trust in
the exchange, which grain producers rely on to set fair prices for
their crops, said Illinois Farm Bureau President John White Jr.
   ``My own confidence is at an all-time low,'' he told a telephone
news conference.
   White said he will ask federal regulators next Monday to
investigate events leading up to the exchange's July 11 order,
including whether any Board of Trade directors may have improperly
profited from it.
   White, whose organization represents 330,000 Illinois farmers,
also sits on the Agricultural Advisory Committee of the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, the federal agency that regulates
futures trading.
   White said the committee will hold a special meeting Monday, at
his request, to discuss the Board of Trade's order.
   Board of Trade officials have repeatedly denied any conflict of
interest regarding the action, which they say was taken to ensure an
orderly market and prevent defaults as the July contract expired.
   The order was widely perceived as an act aimed at heading off
what some traders called an attempt by the large Italian grain
company Ferruzzi Finanziaria S.p.A. to corner the U.S. soybean
market.
   The order forced Ferruzzi, which has denied any cornering
attempt, to slash to 1 million bushels from 23 million bushels the
amount of soybeans it could have called in for delivery on July 20.
   The Board of Trade said that at the time it issued the
liquidation order, less than 13 million bushels of soybeans were
available for delivery against the July contract.
   White said as many farmers may have profited as lost money from
the resulting drop in futures prices. The real damage, he said, was
to the credibility of the Board of Trade as a free market.
   He said no action had so disturbed farmers since President Carter
ordered an embargo on sales of U.S. grain to the Soviet Union in
retaliation for the December 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
The embargo sent prices plunging because the Soviets were among the
biggest U.S. grain consumers.
   White said the soybean liquidation order was especially damaging
because it followed by six months the revelation of an FBI
investigation of suspected futures trading fraud at the Board of
Trade and the rival Chicago Mercantile Exchange. So far 46 traders
have been indicted because of that probe.
   The news in January of the FBI investigation ``opened a wound,''
White said. ``And here, just a few months later, we have another
gash in the wound. Every time one of these things happens, it just
erodes the credibility of the markets more.''
   Illinois is the nation's second-largest soybean-producing state
behind Iowa. Illinois farmers harvested 235 million bushels last
year, about 15 percent of the U.S. crop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
