<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-23 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices recovered from early lows to
close mostly higher Wednesday.
   Traders said prices were depressed early in the day in response
to new weekly data from the American Petroleum Institute that showed
a rise in U.S. crude oil and gasoline supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 11
cents to finish at $18.80 a barrel after trading as low as $18.58.
   Contracts for later delivery were mixed.
   Among refined products, September unleaded gasoline rose 0.35
cent to close at 53.93 cents a gallon. And domestic heating oil for
September delivery rose 0.12 cent to 51.91 cents a gallon. Other
contract months were mixed.
   The API report for the week ended Aug. 18 showed total gasoline
stocks rose more than 1 million barrels to 222.95 million and were 9
million barrels higher than a year ago. The report was released
after the close of trading on Tuesday.
   Crude stocks rose 4.4 million barrels to 335.2 million for the
week, but were 5 million barrels below last year's level.
   Heating oil inventories declined by 335,000 barrels to 40.7
million barrels, the API said.
   ``The market declined early in reaction to the APIs but recovered
late in the day on short covering,'' said John H. O'Connell, energy
analyst with Refco Inc.
   Analysts said the market had been looking for a decline in
gasoline inventories as an indication of whether refineries were
beginning to wind down production. Wholesale and retail gasoline
prices have fallen in recent weeks due to excess supply and sluggish
demand.
   WTI has remained in the $18 to $19 range despite reports of
excess production by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries. OPEC is believed to be producing about 2 million barrels
a day more than its 19.5 million quota.
   ``The market has grown accustomed to 21.6 million or 21.8 million
barrels so it's already built into prices,'' O'Connell said.
</TEXT>
