<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Dunkin'Donuts     08-23 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Dunkin' Donuts,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drops in Third Quarter Because of Takeover Combat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc. reported a 34 percent
drop in third-quarter earnings Wednesday, attributing much of the
decline to costs associated with fighting a hostile takeover bid.
   The doughnut maker is the target of a takeover by DD Acquisition
Corp., a Canadian partnership of Kingsbridge Capital Group and Cara
Operations Ltd.
   Dunkin' Donuts said earnings for the three months ended July 29
totaled $2.1 million or 24 cents a share on revenue of $30.3
million, compared with earnings of $3.2 million or 49 cents a share
on revenue of $29.2 million.
   The quarterly figures include a pretax charge of nearly $2.5
million for professional fees Dunkin' Donuts needed for battling the
DD Acquisition.
   Last week, DD Acquisition removed some conditions on its $296
million hostile bid for Dunkin' Donuts and said it would raise the
offer to $308 million if it wins a lawsuit challenging the doughnut
shop chain's anti-takeover measures.
   Dunkin' Donuts has established a series of defenses, including an
employee stock ownership plan that holds about 16 percent of its
outstanding common shares.
   For the nine months ended July 29, Dunkin' Donuts said earnings
totaled $7.62 million or $1.08 a share, down 22.7 percent from the
$9.86 million or $1.49 a share a year earlier. Revenues totaled
$89.7 million vs. $82.4 million, an 8 percent increase.
</TEXT>
