<FIRST>u f AM-ExxonSuit     08-23 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Suit,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservationists Ask Fall-Winter Cleanup by Exxon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of state and national
environmental groups sued Exxon Corp. on Wednesday, asking the
courts to order the oil company to continue cleaning up the nation's
worst oil spill throughout the fall and winter.
   Exxon has announced it intends to cease cleanup operations Sept.
15 because the weather in Prince William Sound and along the
southern coast of the Alaska mainland will be too severe to allow
work to continue.
   ``Over the winter, Exxon is proposing to leave only a skeletal
crew, stationed in Anchorage, to monitor the spill,'' said Stewart
Elgie, an attorney for the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund. ``That is
simply outrageous. If Exxon insists that it cannot clean up a spill
after Sept. 15, maybe we shouldn't allow winter traffic into
Valdez.''
   Other environmentalists complained that Exxon's cleanup efforts
to date have been grossly inadequate.
   ``Exxon keeps reassuring the public that the cleanup is going
well, that all beaches will be cleaned up soon, that the ravages to
wildlife are almost over, that things are well in hand,'' said Lauri
Adams, another defense fund attorney. ``They're not.
   ``Exxon's cleanup efforts have proven largely ineffective, and it
has vacillated on a commitment to further cleanup next spring,''
Adams said. ``We want the court to make it absolutely clear that
Exxon will be responsible for cleaning up its mess until the area is
fully restored.''
   Exxon has said only that it will reassess the situation next
spring and comply with any reasonable request for additional cleanup
work.
   Exxon officials declined comment on the suit filed Tuesday in
U.S. District Court until it had a chance to review the complaint.
   The suit is one of more than 100 filed against Exxon in state and
federal courts since the Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24 on Bligh
Reef in Prince William Sound, spilling 11 million gallons of North
Slope crude.
   Adams said the environmental groups represented in the lawsuit
have a membership of more than 2.5 million.
</TEXT>
