<HEAD>Continental Requests Authority to Begin Houston-Tokyo Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines announced Wednesday it is
asking the Department of Transportation for permission to operate
flights from Houston to Tokyo.
   Continental said it is filing with the DOT specified daily Boeing
747 flights between Houston Intercontinental Airport and Tokyo's
Narita International Airport, with an intermediate stop in Honolulu.
   ``This route will be of tremendous benefit to Houston in its
efforts to further develop economic ties with Japan and the Far
East,'' Continental Chairman D. Joseph Corr told a meeting of the
Greater Houston Partnership.
   ``We expect travelers from throughout Texas, the Southeast,
Mexico and Central America will find this to be the most convenient
service available to Japan.''
   Fares for the new flights have not yet been determined.
   Houston-based Continental, a subsidiary of Texas Air Corp., began
service to Tokyo from Seattle-Tacoma in May. The airline also
operates more than 50 flights a week from four Japanese cities to
mid-Pacific destinations, including Guam, Saipan and several
Micronesian Islands.
