<FIRST>r f BC-CommoditiesProbe     08-23 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Commodities Probe,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Trader Pleads Innocent to Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Treasury bond trader at the Chicago Board
of Trade pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges resulting from the
federal undercover probe of corruption at the world's largest
futures markets.
   Howard Goberstein, 33, is charged with violating the Commodities
Exchange Act and mail fraud. He was named in more than 100
indictment counts and is accused of scheming to defraud customers
who placed orders for sale or purchase of futures contracts in
Treasury bonds.
   He entered the plea before U.S. District Judge William Zagel, who
set a Dec. 4 trial date.
   Goberstein is the second of two bond traders to plead to charges
resulting from the FBI investigation. Melanie Kosar, 25, pleaded
guilty to charges against her.
   Of 46 traders indicted for alleged offenses at the CBOT and the
Chicago Merchantile Exchange, 17 have pleaded innocent and five have
entered guilty pleas and agreed to cooperate with the prosecution.
The remaining 25 have yet to be arraigned.
