<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2055EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-NorthwestPenalty     08-23 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest Penalty,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Pays $650,000 Penalty to FAA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines said Wednesday it paid a
$650,000 federal penalty for 10 problems found during a national
airline inspection program, a reduction from the 139 problems
investigators initially identified.
   The penalty was primarily for inadequate record keeping,
conducting certain minor aircraft repairs before the repair
procedures were approved in writing by the aircraft manufacturer,
and not meeting a timetable to conduct a particular follow-up
inspection, Northwest said.
   ``None of these issues involves the safe operation of Northwest
aircraft,'' said William Slattery, Northwest's executive vice
president of operations.
   The airline said it paid the penalty, which the Federal Aviation
Administration reduced from the $801,000 it proposed in February,
last week.
   The month-long inspection leading to the penalty was part of the
National Aviation Safety Inspection Program covering all airlines.
Other fines levied so far range from $9.5 million against Eastern
Airlines to $250,000 against Trans World Airlines, said Northwest
spokesman Kevin Whalen.
   The original inspection report issued in March 1988 found that
Northwest flew two ``unairworthy'' jetliners, improperly delayed
aircraft repairs and let some pilots fly longer than allowed.
   FAA spokesman Mort Edelstein said at the time that the agency
defines unairworthiness as ``any malfunction in any part of the
aircraft.'' The problems found with the two planes cited were ``not
something that would make an airplane fall out of the sky,'' he said.
   The agency also praised Northwest for its cooperation and said it
had a ``very good safety record.''
   Northwest disputed some findings when the report was issued, but
a month later said it had hired more operations workers, revised
procedures and issued disciplinary notices to some employees. By
that point, airline officials said they believed most of the issues
had been resolved.
   Slattery said the number of concerns included in the final
penalty was reduced through discussions and ``information
exchanges'' with the FAA.
   One of the violations for which Northwest was penalized was the
use of Boeing jumbo jets on 8,198 flights without a required engine
bolt inspection.
   Whalen said Northwest had done initial inspections on the bolts,
but failed to meet the timetable for follow-up inspections. No
problems were found when the follow-up inspections were later done,
he said.
   Another problem cited by the FAA was unauthorized repairs on flap
panels and horizontal and vertical stabilizers on two 747s. Whalen
said Northwest received verbal approval from Boeing, the
manufacturer, to perform the repairs but failed to get it in writing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
