<DOCNO> AP890823-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PacificTelecom     08-23 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pacific Telecom,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Telecom Buys Anchorage Phone Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Telecom Inc. has signed an
agreement to purchase the assets of Anchorage Telephone Utility for
$412 million in cash, Pacific Telecom announced Wednesday.
   Under the agreement signed with the Municipality of Anchorage,
Alaska, Pacific Telecom will assume all of the phone company's
liabilities, except bonded indebtedness.
   ATU provides telephone service to about 115,000 lines in the
Anchorage area. As of Dec. 31, ATU had assets of $299 million and
liabilities of $20 million, not counting bonded indebtedness.
   ATU's 1988 net income totaled $4 million on revenues of $81
million.
   The deal is subject to approval by 60 percent of those who vote
in an Anchorage municipal election to be held Oct. 3. It also must
be approved by the Alaska Public Utilities Commission and Federal
Communications Commission.
   Pacific Telecom is a subsidiary of Pacificorp, a Portland,
Ore.-based electric utility, finanical services, natural resources
and communications company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
